{"title_page": "Eccrine carcinoma", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Eccrine carcinoma\n| synonyms        =  '''Syringoid carcinoma'''\n| image           = SkinTumors-P8110577.JPG\n| caption         = Eccrine carcinoma, alveolar type\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = [[dermatology]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Eccrine carcinoma''' is a rare [[skin condition]] characterized by a [[papule|plaque or nodule]] on the [[scalp]], trunk, or extremities.<ref name=\"Andrews\">{{cite book |author1=James, William D. |author2=Berger, Timothy G. |title=Andrews' Diseases of the Skin: Clinical Dermatology |publisher=Saunders Elsevier |location= |year=2006 |pages= |isbn=0-7216-2921-0 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=|display-authors=etal}}</ref>{{rp|669}} It originates from the eccrine sweat glands of the skin, accounting for less than 0.01% of diagnosed cutaneous malignancies.<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=Kaseb|first=Hatem|title=Cancer, An Overview of Eccrine Carcinoma|date=2020|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK541042/|work=StatPearls|publisher=StatPearls Publishing|pmid=31082086|access-date=2020-04-22|last2=Babiker|first2=Hani M.}}</ref> Eccrine carcinoma tumors are locally aggressive with a high rate of recurrence. Lack of reliable immunohistochemical markers and similarity to other common tumors has made identification of eccrine carcinoma difficult.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Symptoms ==\nEccrine carcinoma results in brown, bluish, erythematous skin lesions across the body. Common regions where lesions are found are in the lower extremities (35%), head and neck (24%), and upper extremities (14%).<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Larson|first=Kristian|last2=Babiker|first2=Hani M.|last3=Kovoor|first3=Andrew|last4=Liau|first4=Joy|last5=Eldersveld|first5=Jordan|last6=Elquza|first6=Emad|date=2018|title=Oral Capecitabine Achieves Response in Metastatic Eccrine Carcinoma|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1155/2018/7127048|journal=Case Reports in Oncological Medicine|volume=2018|pages=1\u20135|doi=10.1155/2018/7127048|issn=2090-6706}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Idrissi Serhrouchni|first=Karima|last2=Harmouch|first2=Taoufiq|last3=Chbani|first3=Laila|last4=El Fatemi|first4=Hind|last5=Sekal|first5=Mohammed|last6=Hammas|first6=Nawal|last7=Soughi|first7=Meriem|last8=Benchat|first8=Loubna|last9=Amarti|first9=Afaf|date=2013-02-04|title=Eccrine carcinoma: a rare cutaneous neoplasm|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1186/1746-1596-8-15|journal=Diagnostic Pathology|volume=8|issue=1|doi=10.1186/1746-1596-8-15|issn=1746-1596}}</ref>\n\n== Complications ==\nMetastases and/or antagonistic side effects can occur after surgical excision of tumors.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Types ==\nEccrine carcinoma tumors consist of two types: malignant and benign. Malignant tumors include porocarcinoma, hidradenocarcinoma, malignant spiradenoma carcinoma, malignant cylindroma, syringoid eccrine carcinoma, microcystic adnexal carcinoma, mucinous carcinoma, adenoid cystic carcinoma, and ductal papillary adenocarcinoma.<ref name=\":0\" /> Benign tumors include poroma, hidradenoma, spiradenoma, cylindroma, syringometaplasia, syringoma, syringofibroadenoma, and chondroid syringoma.<ref name=\":0\" /> Other tumors not classified include eccrine ductal carcinoma, basaloid eccrine carcinoma, clear cell eccrine carcinoma and non-specified sweat gland carcinomas.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Causes ==\nThere is no research yet as to what causes Eccrine carcinoma.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Diagnosis ==\nA skin biopsy is the common test used to diagnose Eccrine Carcinoma.<ref name=\":0\" /> The biopsy will detect growth of new or abnormal tissue. Another test that can be performed is using Immunohistochemistry, but it is inconsistent.<ref name=\":0\" /> Markers used to detect Eccrine Carcinoma consist of carcinoembryonic antigen, progesterone receptors, estrogen receptors, epithelial membrane antigen, pancytokeratins, and cytokeratin 7.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Swanson|first=P. E.|last2=Cherwitz|first2=D. L.|last3=Neumann|first3=M. P.|last4=Wick|first4=M. R.|date=1987-2004|title=Eccrine sweat gland carcinoma: an histologic and immunohistochemical study of 32 cases*|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1600-0560.1987.tb00477.x|journal=Journal of Cutaneous Pathology|volume=14|issue=2|pages=65\u201386|doi=10.1111/j.1600-0560.1987.tb00477.x|issn=0303-6987|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ohnishi|first=Takamitsu|last2=Kaneko|first2=Sakae|last3=Egi|first3=Motoko|last4=Takizawa|first4=Hajime|last5=Watanabe|first5=Shinichi|date=2002-2010|title=Syringoid Eccrine Carcinoma|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1097/00000372-200210000-00007|journal=The American Journal of Dermatopathology|volume=24|issue=5|pages=409\u2013413|doi=10.1097/00000372-200210000-00007|issn=0193-1091|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Treatment ==\nTreatment requires surgical excision of tumors brought upon by Eccrine Carcinoma.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moy|first=Ronald L.|last2=Rivkin|first2=Jonathan E.|last3=Lee|first3=Hyo|last4=Brooks|first4=Walter S.|last5=Zitelli|first5=John A.|date=1991-2005|title=Syringoid eccrine carcinoma|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/0190-9622(91)70133-m|journal=Journal of the American Academy of Dermatology|volume=24|issue=5|pages=857\u2013860|doi=10.1016/0190-9622(91)70133-m|issn=0190-9622|via=}}</ref> To treat lesions, chemotherapy and radiation therapy have been used.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sidiropoulos|first=M.|last2=Sade|first2=S.|last3=Al-Habeeb|first3=A.|last4=Ghazarian|first4=D.|date=2011-06-04|title=Syringoid eccrine carcinoma: a clinicopathological and immunohistochemical study of four cases|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1136/jclinpath-2011-200069|journal=Journal of Clinical Pathology|volume=64|issue=9|pages=788\u2013792|doi=10.1136/jclinpath-2011-200069|issn=0021-9746}}</ref>\n\n== Prognosis ==\nEccrine carcinoma has a relative mortality rate of 80%, and the 10-year overall survival rate is 9%.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n== Frequency ==\nEccrine carcinoma accounts for 0.005-0.01% of diagnosed cutaneous malignancies.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Salih|first=Abdulwahid M.|last2=Kakamad|first2=F.H.|last3=Essa|first3=Rawand A.|last4=Rauf|first4=Goran M.|last5=S.A.|first5=Masrur|last6=H.M.|first6=Shvan|last7=Q.S.|first7=Rawezh|last8=A.H.|first8=Hunar|last9=A.H.|first9=Dahat|last10=Othman|first10=Snur|date=2017|title=Porocarcinoma: A systematic review of literature with a single case report|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.ijscr.2016.10.051|journal=International Journal of Surgery Case Reports|volume=30|pages=13\u201316|doi=10.1016/j.ijscr.2016.10.051|issn=2210-2612}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Microcystic adnexal carcinoma]]\n* [[Skin lesion]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|  DiseasesDB     =  \n|  ICD10          =  \n|  ICD9           =  \n|  ICDO           =  \n|  OMIM           =  \n|  MedlinePlus    =  \n|  eMedicineSubj  = article \n|  eMedicineTopic = 1101796 \n|  MeshID         = \n}}\n{{Tumors of skin appendages}}\n\n[[Category:Epidermal nevi, neoplasms, cysts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Eccrine carcinoma\n| synonyms        =  '''Syringoid carcinoma'''\n| image           = SkinTumors-P8110577.JPG\n| caption         = Eccrine carcinoma, alveolar type\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = [[dermatology]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths     