{"title_page": "Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom", "text_new": "{{short description|Timeline of ongoing pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThe following is a timeline of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]].\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Kingdom medical cases chart}}\n\n==Timeline==\n[[File:2020 UK ONS weekly COVID19 deaths.png|right|Graph of weekly England and Wales death data from the [[Office for National Statistics]] including COVID-19 deaths in 2020<ref name=\"ONS_deaths_200403\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/birthsdeathsandmarriages/deaths/bulletins/deathsregisteredweeklyinenglandandwalesprovisional/weekending3april2020 |title=Deaths registered weekly in England and Wales, provisional \u2013 Office for National Statistics |last=[[Office for National Statistics]] |date=2020-04-20 |website=www.ons.gov.uk |access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>]]\n=== January ===\n*25 January \u2013 The [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] advises against all travel to China's [[Hubei Province]], where the city of Wuhan, the original epicentre of the outbreak, is located.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-china-health-britain-idUKKBN1ZO0SW|title=Britain advises against all travel to China's Hubei province|date=25 January 2020|website=Reuters UK}}</ref>\n*27 January \u2013 The Health Secretary, [[Matt Hancock]], tells the House of Commons that 200 British citizens trapped in [[Wuhan]], [[China]], will be offered repatriation to the UK, in light of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak in Hubei|coronavirus outbreak there]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/27/britons-in-wuhan-will-be-offered-help-to-leave-hancock-tells-mps |title=Britons in Wuhan will be offered help to leave, Hancock tells MPs |work=The Guardian|date=27 January 2020 |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n*28 January \u2013 The Foreign and Commonwealth Office updates its travel advisory, advising against all but essential travel to the rest of [[Mainland China]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/amp/uk-51288672 |title=Coronavirus: Foreign Office warns against 'all but essential travel' to China |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=28 January 2020 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n*29 January \u2013 [[British Airways]] suspends all flights to and from mainland China with immediate effect, due to the ongoing coronavirus threat.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/29/evacuation-of-britons-in-coronavirus-hit-hubei-could-begin-thursday |title=Britons evacuated due to coronavirus to be quarantined |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper==The Guardian |date=29 January 2020 |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n*31 January \u2013 The first two cases of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus (2019-nCoV) in the United Kingdom]] are confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-51325192|title=Two coronavirus cases confirmed in UK|date=2020-01-31|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-02|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n*6 February \u2013 A third case of coronavirus is confirmed in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51398039|title=Coronavirus: Third case confirmed in the UK\n|website=BBC News|language=en|date=2020-02-06|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n*27 February \u2013 Authorities confirm the first case of [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus]] in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51667483 |title=Northern Ireland diagnoses first coronavirus case |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=27 February 2020 |accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n*28 February\n**The first British death from the disease is confirmed by the [[Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare|Japanese Health Ministry]]; a man [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships|quarantined]] on the ''[[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]]'' cruise ship.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/28/first-briton-dies-from-coronavirus-japanese-media-report-diamond-princess |title=First British coronavirus death confirmed|work=The Guardian|date=28 February 2020 |accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n**Authorities confirm the first case of coronavirus in Wales, an individual who recently returned from holiday in Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51673068|title=Coronavirus: First case in Wales confirmed|website=BBC News|date=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== March ===\n*1 March \u2013 Authorities confirm the first case of coronavirus in Scotland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gov.scot/news/coronavirus-covid-19/ |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19): First positive case in Scotland |publisher=Scottish Government |date=1 March 2020 |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n*2 March \u2013 The government holds a [[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms|COBRA]] meeting to discuss its preparations and response to the virus, as the number of UK cases jumps to 36.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51700604 |title=Coronavirus: Widespread transmission in UK 'highly likely' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=2 March 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n*3 March \u2013 The government publishes its action plan for dealing with coronavirus. This includes scenarios ranging from a milder pandemic to a \"severe prolonged pandemic [[Spanish flu|as experienced in 1918]]\" and warns that a fifth of the national workforce could be absent from work during the infection's peak.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51718917 |title=Coronavirus: Up to fifth of UK workers 'off sick at same time' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=3 March 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/03/uk-government-coronavirus-plans-strip-fire-and-police-to-essentials-covid-19 |title=UK coronavirus plans would strip police and fire services to essentials |work=The Guardian|date=3 March 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n*5 March\n**The airline [[Flybe]] collapses into administration, due in part to the impact of the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51746564 |title=Collapsed Flybe tells passengers not to travel to airports |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The first death from coronavirus in the UK is confirmed,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51759602 |title=Coronavirus: Older patient becomes first virus fatality in UK |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC News |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> as the number of cases exceeds 100, with a total of 115 having tested positive. England's [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officer]], [[Chris Whitty]], tells MPs that the UK has now moved to the second stage of dealing with COVID-19 \u2013 from \"containment\" to the \"delay\" phase.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/more-than-a-hundred-people-in-uk-infected-with-coronavirus |title=More than a hundred people in UK infected with coronavirus |work=The Guardian|date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n*6 March \u2013 The Prime Minister announces \u00a346 million in funding for research into a coronavirus vaccine and rapid diagnostic tests. During a visit to a laboratory in Bedfordshire, he says: \"It looks like there will be a substantial period of disruption where we have to deal with this outbreak.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/06/coronavirus-update-latest-live-news-symptoms-cases-global-infection-rate-uk-usa-australia-italy-china-updates?page=with:block-5e624ca98f087df56e4c37f9#block-5e624ca98f087df56e4c37f9 |title=Coronavirus latest updates |work=The Guardian|date=6 March 2020 |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n*8 March \u2013 A third death from coronavirus is reported, at [[North Manchester General Hospital]], as the number of cases in the UK reaches 273, the largest single-day increase so far.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51796072 |title=Coronavirus: Man in his 60s becomes third UK death |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=8 March 2020 |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n*9 March \u2013 The [[FTSE 100]] plunges by more than 8 percent, its largest intraday fall since 2008, amid concerns over the spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cityam.com/coronavirus-ftse-100-plunges-on-open-after-oil-prices-crash-30-per-cent/ |title=Coronavirus: FTSE 100 plunges after oil prices crash 30 per cent |work=City AM |publisher=City AM |date=9 March 2020 |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n*10 March \u2013 Health minister [[Nadine Dorries]] tests positive for coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51827356 |title=Coronavirus: Health minister Nadine Dorries tests positive |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*11 March\n**The [[Bank of England]] cuts its baseline interest rate from 0.75% to 0.25%, back down to the lowest level in history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51831004 |title=UK interest rates cut in emergency move |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], [[Rishi Sunak]], presents the Johnson Government's [[March 2020 United Kingdom budget|first budget]], which includes \u00a330 billion in measures to protect the economy from coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-budget/uk-pledges-30-billion-to-protect-economy-from-coronavirus-idUKKBN20Y007 |title=UK pledges \u00a330 billion to protect economy from coronavirus |work=Reuters |publisher=Reuters |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51835306 |title=Budget 2020: Chancellor unveils \u00a330bn coronavirus package |work=BBC News|publisher=BBC News|date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/11/key-points-from-budget-2020-at-a-glance |title=Key points from budget 2020 \u2013 at a glance |work=The Guardian|date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Wales has its first case of \"community transmission\", when a patient in Caerphilly with no travel history tests positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51836057|title=Coronavirus: First community transmission detected in Wales|date=11 March 2020|website=BBC News}}</ref>\n*12 March\n**Following a series of recent major falls, the FTSE100 plunges yet again, this time by over 10%, its biggest drop since 1987.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51829852 |title=Coronavirus: Global stocks plunge as coronavirus fears spread |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2020/mar/12/stock-markets-tumble-trump-europe-travel-ban-ecb-christine-lagarde-business-live?page=with:block-5e6a636e8f08c2df6d278620#block-5e6a636e8f08c2df6d278620 |title=FTSE 100 suffers second worst day ever after 10.87% plunge \u2013 business live |work=The Guardian|date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> Other markets around the world are similarly affected by ongoing economic turmoil.\n**A patient at [[Wrexham Maelor Hospital]] tests positive for COVID-19 \u2013 the first case in North Wales.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-03-12/reports-of-coronavirus-patient-admitted-to-wrexham-maelor-hospital/|title=First case of coronavirus confirmed in north Wales, ITV Wales understands|date=12 March 2020|website=ITV News}}</ref>\n**[[Public Health England]] stops performing [[contact tracing]], in view of the wide spread of infection in the population.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Tapper|first=James|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/04/recruit-volunteer-army-to-trace-coronavirus-contacts-now-urge-top-scientists|title=Recruit volunteer army to trace Covid-19 contacts now, urge top scientists|date=2020-04-04|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n*13 March \n**Authorities confirm the first death from coronavirus in Scotland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51874899 |title=Coronavirus: Death of first Scottish patient with Covid-19 confirmed |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[Premier League]] [[2019\u201320 Premier League|2019\u20132020 season]] is suspended, amid a growing list of worldwide sporting cancellations and postponements due to COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867989 |title=Coronavirus: Premier League and EFL suspended until 3 April at earliest |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Elections including the [[2020 United Kingdom local elections|English local elections]], [[2020 London mayoral election|London mayoral election]] and [[2020 England and Wales police and crime commissioner elections|police and crime commissioner elections]], scheduled for May 2020, are postponed for a year because of the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51876269 |title=Coronavirus: English local elections postponed for a year |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The Welsh Government's Health Minister [[Vaughan Gething]] announces that all non-urgent outpatient appointments and operations will be suspended at hospitals in Wales, in a bid to delay the spread of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-03-13/20-000-deaths-in-wales-predicted-in-worst-case-scenario-as-measures-announced-to-cope-with-coronavirus/ |title=Over 20,000 deaths in Wales predicted in 'worst case scenario' as measures announced to cope with coronavirus |work=ITV News |publisher=ITV |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n*14 March\n**A further 10 people are reported to have died from COVID-19, almost doubling the UK death toll from 11 to 21. The government's aim for a \"[[herd immunity]]\" approach generates controversy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/health/uk-herd-immunity-coronavirus-who-margaret-harris-a4387346.html |title=UK's 'herd immunity' approach to tackling coronavirus questioned by World Health Organisation |work=Evening Standard|date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-51892402 |title=Coronavirus: Scientists say UK virus strategy is 'risking lives' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC News |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://maths.qmul.ac.uk/~vnicosia/UK_scientists_statement_on_coronavirus_measures.pdf |title=Public request to take stronger measures of socialdistancing across the UK with immediate effect |work=Queen Mary University of London |publisher=Queen Mary University of London |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Vice President of the United States]], [[Mike Pence]], announces the US is to extend its European [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States#Travel and entry restrictions|coronavirus travel ban]] to include the UK from 16 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-51891662 |title=Coronavirus: US to extend travel ban to UK and Ireland |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n**UK retailers release a joint letter asking customers not to panic buy products after some supermarkets sell out of items such as pasta, hand gel and toilet paper.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51883440 |title=Coronavirus: Supermarkets ask shoppers to be 'considerate' and stop panic buying |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n*15 March \n**The [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] advises against \"all but essential travel\" to the US.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/15/coronavirus-latest-updates-trump-tests-negative-as-spain-orders-nationwide-lockdown-uk-us-australia-italy-europe-global-economy?page=with:block-5e6e17e48f088d7575593aed#block-5e6e17e48f088d7575593aed |title=UK advises against 'all but essential' travel to US |work=The Guardian|date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Health Secretary [[Matt Hancock]] says that every UK resident over the age of 70 will be told \"within the coming weeks\" to self-isolate for \"a very long time\" to shield them from coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51895873 |title=Coronavirus: Isolation for over-70s 'within weeks' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The government announces plans to hold daily televised press conferences to update the public on the fight against the coronavirus pandemic, starting on Monday 16 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51901818 |title=Coronavirus: Downing Street to give daily update on fight against outbreak |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n*16 March\n**The UK death toll from the pandemic reaches 55, with the number of cases of the illness passing 1,500.<ref name=avoid>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51917562 |title=Coronavirus: PM says everyone should avoid office, pubs and travelling |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Prime Minister Boris Johnson advises everyone in the UK against \"non-essential\" travel and contact with others, to curb coronavirus, as well as suggesting people should avoid pubs, clubs and theatres, and work from home if possible. Pregnant women, people over the age of 70 and those with certain health conditions are urged to consider the advice \"particularly important\", and will be asked to self-isolate within days.<ref name=avoid/>\n**The BBC delays its planned changes to TV licences for the over-75s from June to August because of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51911065 |title=Coronavirus: BBC delays over-75 TV licence fee changes |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n*17 March\n**NHS England announces that from 15 April all non-urgent operations in England will be postponed, to free up 30,000 beds to help tackle the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51933410 |title=Coronavirus: All non-urgent operations in England postponed |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The Chancellor, Rishi Sunak, announces that \u00a3330bn will be made available in loan guarantees for businesses affected by the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/mar/17/boris-johnson-coronavirus-press-conference-rishi-sunak-cabinet-as-rishi-sunak-set-to-announcing-coronavirus-financial-rescue-package-politics-live?page=with:block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b#block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b |title=Sunak says he will make \u00a3330bn available in lending to keep firms in business |work=The Guardian|date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51935467 |title=Coronavirus: Chancellor unveils \u00a3330bn lifeline for economy |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The Foreign and Commonwealth Office advises against all non-essential international travel due to the pandemic and the border restrictions put in place by many countries in response.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/travel-advice-foreign-secreatary-statement-17-march-2020 |title=Travel Advice against all non-essential travel: Foreign Secretary's statement, 17 March 2020 |publisher=GOV.UK |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The UK coronavirus-related death toll rises to 71, while the number of confirmed cases of the illness rises to 1,950.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jane |last=Dalton |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/uk-coronavirus-death-toll-nhs-latest-outbreak-pandemic-a9407311.html |title=UK coronavirus death toll rises to 71 |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/uk-coronavirus-cases-reach-1-950-up-407-in-24-hours-11958875 |title=Coronavirus: 14 more deaths in England \u2013 UK total now 71 |publisher=Sky UK |work=Sky News |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[National Assembly for Wales]] is closed to the public.\n*18 March\n**[[Pound sterling]] falls below $1.18, its lowest level since [[1985 in the United Kingdom|1985]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/40272e84-68ff-11ea-a3c9-1fe6fedcca75 |title=Pound sinks under $1.19 in deepening coronavirus market crisis |publisher=FT |work=FT |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailyfx.com/gbp-usd |title=GBP/USD: Pound \u2013 Dollar Rate, Chart, Forecast &amp; Analysis |publisher=Daily FX |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> Bank of England governor [[Andrew Bailey (banker)|Andrew Bailey]], commenting on the UK and wider economic situation, says: \"It's obviously an emergency. I think we're living in completely unparalleled times... It's going to be a very big downturn \u2013 we know that.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-boe-could-take-radical-money-printing-action-11959670 |title=Coronavirus: 'Radical' money printing plan being considered by the Bank of England |work=Sky News |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The UK death toll from coronavirus exceeds 100, with 32 new cases taking the total to 104.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-32-more-covid-19-patients-die-in-england-taking-uk-total-to-104-11959809 |title=Coronavirus: 32 more COVID-19 patients die in England \u2013 taking UK total to 104 |work=Sky News |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The government announces that all schools in the country will shut from the afternoon of Friday 20 March, except for those looking after the children of key workers and vulnerable children.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51952314 |title=Coronavirus: Schools to close until further notice from Friday |work=BBC News |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> No exams will take place this academic year, [[Secretary of State for Education|Education Secretary]] [[Gavin Williamson]] confirms.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-uk-schools-to-close-from-friday-11959769 |title=Coronavirus: UK schools to close from Friday until further notice |work=Sky News |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The 50th anniversary [[Glastonbury Festival]] is cancelled as a result of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/mar/18/uk-coronavirus-live-boris-johnson-pmqs-cbi-urges-government-pay-businesses-directly-saying-350bn-loangrant-package-not-enough |title=All schools to close from Friday; GCSE and A-level exams cancelled \u2013 UK coronavirus, as it happened |work=The Guardian |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The government announces emergency legislation to bring in a complete ban on new evictions for three months, as part of measures to help protect renters in social and private rented accommodation.\n*19 March \u2013 In an emergency move, the Bank of England cuts interest rates again, from 0.25% to just 0.1%. This is the lowest rate in the Bank's 325-year history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51962982 |title=Coronavirus: UK interest rates slashed to lowest level ever |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n*20 March\n**[[Northwick Park Hospital]] in [[London Borough of Harrow|Harrow]] declares a \"critical incident\" due to a surge in patients with coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/news/hospitals-critical-care-unit-overwhelmed-by-coronavirus-patients/7027189.article |title=Hospital's critical care unit overwhelmed by coronavirus patients |work=HSJ |publisher=HSJ|date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Chancellor Rishi Sunak announces that the government will pay 80% of wages for employees not working, up to \u00a32,500 a month, as part of \"unprecedented\" measures to protect people's jobs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51982005 |title=Wages cover for businesses hit by virus outlined |publisher=BBC News|date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Prime Minister Boris Johnson orders all cafes, pubs and restaurants to close from the evening of 20 March, except for take-away food, to tackle coronavirus. All the UK's nightclubs, theatres, cinemas, gyms and leisure centres are told to close \"as soon as they reasonably can\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51981653 |title=UK pubs and restaurants told to shut in virus fight |publisher=BBC News|date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n*21 March \u2013 [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment Secretary]] [[George Eustice]] urges shoppers to stop [[panic buying]], as supermarkets around the UK struggle to keep up with demand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51989721 |title=Coronavirus: Shoppers told to buy responsibly |publisher=BBC News|date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> [[Tesco]], [[Asda]], [[Aldi]], and [[Lidl]] are reported to have begun a recruitment drive for up to 30,000 new staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51976075 |title=Supermarkets Tesco, Asda, Aldi and Lidl go on hiring spree |publisher=BBC News|date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n*22 March\n**The [[Nursing and Midwifery Council]] announces that more than 5,600 former nurses have registered to offer their services in the fight against coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/22/uk-coronavirus-live-police-could-enforce-london-lockdown-says-khan-seven-people-die-in-wales?page=with:block-5e776a4f8f08dcc95cc20fdd#block-5e776a4f8f08dcc95cc20fdd |title=UK coronavirus live: police could enforce London social distancing; seven people die in Wales |work=The Guardian|date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Boris Johnson warns that \"tougher measures\" may be introduced if people do not follow government advice on social distancing.<ref name=\"tougher measures\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51998559 |title=Coronavirus: Follow virus advice or 'tougher measures' likely, says PM |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> \n**The virus claims its youngest victim so far, with the death of an eighteen-year-old with underlying health problems.<ref name=\"tougher measures\"/>\n*23 March\n**The government announces emergency measures to safeguard the nation's [[Rail transport in the United Kingdom|rail network]], with season ticket holders given refunds if working from home, and [[Passenger rail franchising in Great Britain|rail franchise agreements]] nationalised for at least six months to prevent rail companies from collapsing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-52002272 |title=Commuters to get refund on rail season tickets |publisher=BBC News|date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-rail-franchise-agreements-suspended-to-avoid-company-collapses-11962186 |title=Coronavirus: Rail franchise agreements suspended to avoid company collapses |publisher=Sky News|date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Pride in London]], the UK's largest LGBT [[Pride festival]], scheduled for 27 June, is the latest event to be postponed. It is one of a hundred pride events to be postponed or cancelled in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hunte |first=Ben |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-52001388 |title=Coronavirus postpones London Pride |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n**In a televised address, Boris Johnson announces a UK-wide lockdown with immediate effect, to contain the spread of the virus. People can leave their homes only for \"very limited purposes\" \u2013 shopping for basic necessities; for one form of exercise a day; for any medical need; and to travel to and from work when \"absolutely necessary\". A number of other restrictions are imposed, with police given powers to enforce the measures, including the use of fines.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-52000039 |title='You must stay at home' UK public told| publisher=BBC | date=23 March 2020| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52012432 |title=Coronavirus: Strict new curbs on life in UK announced by PM| publisher=BBC | date=23 March 2020| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/23/boris-johnson-orders-uk-lockdown-to-be-enforced-by-police |title=Boris Johnson orders UK lockdown to be enforced by police| work=The Guardian| date=23 March 2020| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n*24 March\n**The UK records its highest number of coronavirus deaths in one day, after a further 87 people die across the country, bringing the total to 422.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-calls-for-police-at-stations-after-packed-trains-defy-lockdown-11962837|title=Coronavirus: Biggest daily rise in UK deaths \u2013 up by 87 to 422\n| publisher=Sky News| date=24 March 2020| accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**For the first time, all of the UK's [[List of mobile network operators of Europe#United Kingdom|mobile networks]] send out a government text alert, ordering people to stay at home. The message reads: \"''GOV.UK CORONAVIRUS ALERT. New rules in force now: you must stay at home. More info and exemptions at gov.uk/coronavirus Stay at home. Protect the NHS. Save lives.''\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-52017451|title=Coronavirus: Mobile networks send 'stay at home' text| publisher=BBC News| date=24 March 2020| accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Secretary of State for Health|Health Secretary]] [[Matt Hancock]] announces the government will open a temporary hospital, the [[NHS Nightingale Hospital]] at the [[ExCeL London]], to add extra critical care capacity in response to coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52018477|title=Coronavirus: ExCeL Centre planned as NHS field hospital| publisher=BBC News| date=24 March 2020| accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[Scottish Parliament]] closes, with plans to reconvene on 1 April to discuss emergency legislation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-52018354 |title=FMQs cancelled as Holyrood chamber shuts for a week |work=BBC News |date=24 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*25 March\n**[[Prince Charles]] tests positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52033845|title=Coronavirus: Prince Charles tests positive but 'remains in good health'| publisher=BBC News| date=25 March 2020| accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] shuts down for a month.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52032188|title=Coronavirus: Parliament shuts down for a month| publisher=BBC News| date=25 March 2020| accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[British Transport Police]] deploys 500 officers to patrol the UK's rail network, in an effort to discourage non-essential journeys. New measures are also introduced on the [[London Underground]] to reduce passenger numbers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-52023580|title=Coronavirus: New Tube restrictions to stop non-essential journeys| publisher=BBC News| date=25 March 2020| accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n*26 March\n**The government announces that the [[Self-employment|self-employed]] will be paid 80% of profits, up to \u00a32,500 a month, to help them cope during the economic crisis triggered by COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52053914|title=Coronavirus: UK government unveils aid for self-employed| publisher=BBC News| date=26 March 2020| accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n**At 8pm, millions of people around the country take part in a \"[[Clap for our Carers|Clap for Carers]]\" tribute, applauding the NHS and other care workers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52058013|title=Clap for Carers: UK in 'emotional' tribute to NHS and care workers| publisher=BBC News| date=27 March 2020| accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*27 March\n**Prime Minister Boris Johnson tests positive for COVID-19, and will self-isolate in [[10 Downing Street]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52060791|title=PM Boris Johnson tests positive for coronavirus| publisher=BBC News| date=27 March 2020| accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Health Secretary [[Matt Hancock]] tests positive for COVID-19 and reports that he is working from home and self-isolating.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-matt-hancock-boris-johnson-test-positive-covid-19-symptoms-a9430031.html|title=Coronavirus: Health secretary Matt Hancock tests positive| work=The Independent| date=27 March 2020| accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Leon Restaurants]] sets up the \"[[Feed NHS]]\" initiative to deliver 5,600 free meals a day to [[National Health Service|NHS]] [[intensive care medicine|critical care]] staff at London hospitals.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Butler|first=Sarah|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/27/leon-sets-up-initiative-to-deliver-free-hot-meals-to-nhs-staff-coronavirus|title=Leon sets up initiative to deliver free meals to NHS critical care staff|date=2020-03-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-29|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n*28 March \u2013 At 11pm, new regulations come into force in Northern Ireland giving authorities the power to force businesses to close, and impose fines on them if they refuse, as well as on people leaving their homes without a \"reasonable excuse\". The measures, introduced by the [[Northern Ireland Executive]], bring Northern Ireland into line with the rest of the UK.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-52079959 |title=New NI Covid-19 regulations come into force |work=BBC News |date=28 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-28/new-regulations-to-enforce-coronavirus-restrictions-agreed-by-stormont/ |title=Northern Ireland imposes fines up to \u00a35,000 for those breaching social distancing rules |website=ITV News}}</ref>\n*30 March \u2013 [[Foreign Secretary]] [[Dominic Raab]] announces an arrangement between the government and major UK airlines to fly home tens of thousands of British nationals who are stranded abroad by the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52099252|title=Rescue flights for stranded Britons|work=BBC News|date=30 March 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*31 March \u2013 A significant rise in [[anxiety]] and [[Depression (mood)|depression]] among the UK population is reported following the lockdown. The study, by researchers from the [[University of Sheffield]] and [[Ulster University]], finds that people reporting anxiety increased from 17% to 36%, while those reporting depression increased from 16% to 38%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/31/rise-in-depression-and-anxiety-day-after-uk-lockdown-announced-study-coronavirus |title=Rise in depression and anxiety day after UK lockdown announced \u2013 study| work=The Guardian| date=31 March 2020| accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n*1 April\n**The [[contactless payment]] limit for in-store spending is raised from \u00a330 to \u00a345.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2020/mar/24/limit-for-contactless-spending-to-rise-to-45-at-beginning-of-april|title=Limit for contactless spending to rise to \u00a345 at beginning of April|work=The Guardian|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[National Assembly for Wales]] reconvenes using [[Zoom (software)|Zoom]] for a virtual emergency [[Senedd Cymru|Senedd]] meeting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.assembly.wales/en/newhome/pages/newsitem.aspx?itemid=2092|title=Plenary meetings continue, but Senedd buildings will stay closed until June|website=National Assembly for Wales|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n**Multinational pharmaceutical company [[Hoffmann-La Roche|Roche]] denies the existence of a deal to supply Wales with COVID-19 tests after First Minister [[Mark Drakeford]] and Health Minister [[Vaughan Gething]] blame the collapse of a deal for a shortage of testing kits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/politics/mark-drakeford-roche-coronavirus-testing-18025301|title=Pharmaceutical giant Roche and Welsh Government at loggerheads over collapsed Covid-19 testing deal|date=1 April 2020|author=Will Hayward|website=WalesOnline|access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n*2 April \u2013 Matt Hancock, who returns to give the daily government briefing after completing his self-isolation, sets a target of carrying out 100,000 tests a day by the end of the month (encompassing both swab tests and blood tests).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52140376|title=Hancock aims for 100,000 tests a day by May|date=2020-04-02|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n*3 April \u2013 [[NHS Nightingale Hospital London]], the first temporary hospital to treat coronavirus patients, opens at the [[ExCeL London|ExCel centre]] in East London, employing NHS staff and military personnel, with 500 beds and potential capacity for 4,000. It is the first of several such facilities planned across the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52150598|title=Coronavirus: Nightingale Hospital opens at London's ExCel centre|work=BBC News|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n*4 April \u2013 The results of the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election]] and the [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election]] are announced, in which [[Keir Starmer]] is elected as the leader of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], succeeding [[Jeremy Corbyn]], and [[Angela Rayner]] is elected as deputy leader of the party. The results are released by email after a public event to announce the results was cancelled due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52164589|title=Keir Starmer elected as new Labour leader|work=BBC News|date=4 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n*5 April\n**[[Queen Elizabeth II]] makes a [[Addresses to the nation by Elizabeth II|rare broadcast to the UK]] and the wider Commonwealth, something she has done on only four previous occasions. In the address she thanks people for following the government's social distancing rules, pays tribute to key workers, and says the UK \"will succeed\" in its fight against coronavirus but may have \"more still to endure\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Caroline |last=Davies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/03/queen-to-address-nation-on-sunday-over-coronavirus-crisis |title=Queen to address nation on Sunday over coronavirus crisis |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=3 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52176222 |title=Coronavirus: Queen tells UK 'we will succeed' in fight |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n**Prime Minister Boris Johnson is admitted to hospital for tests after testing positive for coronavirus ten days earlier.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52177125 |title=Coronavirus: PM admitted to hospital over virus symptoms |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n*6 April\n**The death toll from COVID-19 in the UK exceeds 5,000. The total number of reported cases is nearly 52,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/apr/06/uk-coronavirus-live-boris-johnson-spends-night-in-hospital?page=with:block-5e8b4c078f080bdb9f535404#block-5e8b4c078f080bdb9f535404|title=UK death toll rises to 5,373|publisher=The Guardian|date=6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n**Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] is taken into [[intensive care unit|intensive care]] after being admitted to hospital for coronavirus the day before. It is announced that [[First Secretary of State]] [[Dominic Raab]] will deputise for him.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52192604 |title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson moved to intensive care |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[Orange Order|Orange Lodge of Ireland]] announces that the traditional [[Twelfth of July]] parades in Northern Ireland have been cancelled for 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52184743 |title=Coronavirus: Twelfth of July parades cancelled due to outbreak|date= 6 April 2020 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[National Express Coaches|National Express]] suspends all its long-distance coach services from this date.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/news-and-advice/national-express-coach-cancelled-suspended-bus-ticket-refund-a9442221.html|title=National Express to suspend all coach services|last=Xie|first=Qin|date=2020-04-02|website=The Independent|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n*7 April \u2013 The number of reported deaths increases by 786, taking the total to 6,159. Sir Patrick Vallance, the government's chief scientific adviser, says that the figures are not accelerating as had been predicted but that it is too early to tell whether the outbreak is peaking.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52206510|title=UK cases 'could be moving in the right direction'|date=7 April 2020|work=BBC News|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-britain-curve-idUSS8N2BU035|title=UK coronavirus cases not accelerating but too early to call a peak \u2013 chief science adviser|date=7 April 2020|newspaper=Reuters|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref>\n*8 April \u2013 The [[Resolution Foundation]], using figures from the [[British Chambers of Commerce]], reports that more than nine million workers are expected to be [[Furlough|furloughed]] under the government's job retention scheme, with an estimated cost to the taxpayer of between \u00a330 and 40bn.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-52209790 |title=Coronavirus: More than 9 million expected to be furloughed |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=8 April 2020 |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n*9 April\n**Foreign Secretary [[Dominic Raab]] says the UK is \"starting to see the impact\" of the restrictions but that it is \"too early\" to lift them, and urges people to stay indoors over the Easter weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52235492|title=Raab urges UK public not to ruin lockdown progress|publisher=BBC News|date=9 April 2020}}</ref> \n**Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] is moved out of intensive care, but remains in hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52238276|title=PM out of intensive care but remains in hospital|publisher=BBC News|date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n*11 April\n**[[Queen Elizabeth II]] makes her first ever [[Easter]] [[Addresses to the nation by Elizabeth II|message to the nation]], in which she states \"coronavirus will not overcome us\" and that \"we need Easter as much as ever.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52255054 |title=Coronavirus: 'We need Easter as much as ever,' says the Queen |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=11 April 2020 |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The number of people in London hospitals for COVID-19 reaches its peak, according to week-on-week change data; elsewhere in the country, patient numbers continue to increase, although the rate of increase is slowing.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1250904238399598594|user=jburnmurdoch|title=Charts: London\u2019s hospitals now have fewer covid patients with each day|author=John Burn-Murdoch, [[Financial Times]]|date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n*12 April\n**Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] is discharged from hospital after being treated for coronavirus and will continue his recovery at [[Chequers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52262012 |title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson discharged from hospital |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=12 April 2020 |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The number of people who died in hospital with coronavirus in the UK passes 10,000, after a daily rise of 737.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52264145 |title=Coronavirus: 'Sombre day' as UK deaths hit 10,000 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=12 April 2020 |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The temporary [[Dragon's Heart Hospital]] opens at Cardiff's [[Principality Stadium]] to admit its first patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/rugby/rugby-news/giant-tents-built-inside-principality-18081445|title=Giant tents emerge over Principality Stadium pitch as pictures show first hospital wards at iconic venue|website=WalesOnline|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n*14 April\n**The [[Office of National Statistics]] indicates that coronavirus was linked to one in five deaths during the week ending 3 April. More than 16,000 deaths in the UK were recorded for that week, 6,000 higher than would be the average for that time of year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-52278825|title=One in five deaths now linked to coronavirus|first=Nick|last=Triggle|work=BBC News|date=14 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Several UK charities, including [[Age UK]] and the [[Alzheimer's Society]], express their concern that older people are being \"airbrushed\" out of official figures because they focus on hospital deaths and do not include those in care homes or a person's own home. Responding to these concerns, [[Therese Coffey]], the [[Secretary of State for Work and Pensions]], says that hospital figures are being used because \"it's accurate and quick\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52275823|title=Elderly being 'airbrushed' out of virus figures|work=BBC News|date=14 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Mobile operators report a further twenty attempted arson attacks on mobile phone masts over the previous weekend.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-52281315|title=Twenty suspected phone mast attacks over Easter|first=Leo|last=Kelion|work=BBC News|date=14 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*15 April\n**Health Secretary Matt Hancock announces new guidelines that will allow close family members to see dying relatives in order to say goodbye to them. Hancock also launches a new network to provide personal protective equipment to care home staff.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52299590|title=Coronavirus: Close family to be allowed to say goodbye to the dying \u2013 BBC News|work=BBC News|date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[NHS England]] and the [[Care Quality Commission]] begin rolling out tests for care home staff and residents as it is reported the number of care home deaths are rising but that official figures, which rely on death certificates, are not reflecting the full extent of the problem. [[Helen Whately]], the Minister for Social Care, says that the government are aware the figures are being understated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/apr/15/coronavirus-death-toll-in-englands-care-homes-reaches-1400|title=Care homes in England say coronavirus death toll has risen to 1,400|first=Robert |last=Booth|date=15 April 2020|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n**[[Arlene Foster]], the [[First Minister of Northern Ireland]], extends the period of lockdown in Northern Ireland to 9 May.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-52298748|title=Three-week extension to NI coronavirus lockdown|first=Jayne|last=McCormack|date=15 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*16 April\n** A 99-year-old war veteran, [[Tom Moore (fundraiser)|Tom Moore]], completes 100 laps of his garden,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52303859 |title=Coronavirus: Capt Tom Moore finishes NHS fundraiser as it tops \u00a313m |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> eventually raising over \u00a325 million for [[NHS Charities Together]], with over a million people donating via his [[JustGiving]] page.<ref name=\"JGTM\">{{cite web |title=Captain Tom Moore's 100th Birthday Walk for the NHS |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs |publisher=[[JustGiving]] |accessdate=19 April 2020 }}</ref>\n**Foreign Secretary [[Dominic Raab]] announces a three-week extension to the nationwide lockdown measures as the number of confirmed COVID-19 cases in the UK surpasses 100,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52313715 |title=Coronavirus: UK lockdown extended for 'at least three weeks' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[NHS Nightingale Hospital Birmingham]], at the [[National Exhibition Centre]], is officially opened by [[William, Duke of Cambridge|Prince William]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-birmingham-52309494|title=Nightingale hospital 'example of pulling together'|date=16 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**The UK stages a fourth round of applause for NHS staff and key workers at 8pm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-04-16/uk-clap-for-our-carers-nhs-coronavirus-lockdown/|title=UK unites for fourth week in nationwide Clap For Our Carers to thank NHS workers fighting coronavirus pandemic|website=ITV News}}</ref>\n*17 April \n**Matt Hancock confirms coronavirus tests will be rolled out to cover more public service staff such as police officers, firefighters and prison staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52322447|title=Virus tests expanded to more public service staff|date=17 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> \n**Chancellor [[Rishi Sunak]] extends the subsidised wage scheme for furloughed workers for another month, to the end of June.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-52323918|title=Government extends furlough scheme to pay staff|date=17 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*18 April \n**[[Imran Ahmad-Khan]], the MP for [[Wakefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Wakefield]], secures a shipment of 110,000 reusable face masks through his connections with charity [[Solidarit\u00e9s international]] and the [[Government of Vietnam|Vietnamese Government]] for [[The Mid Yorkshire Hospitals NHS Trust|Mid Yorkshire Hospitals NHS Trust]] to help tackle the shortage of PPE.<ref name=ImranAhmadkhan-response>{{cite news |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/health/coronavirus/wakefield-mp-arranges-delivery-110000-reusable-face-masks-vietnam-nhs-2539775 |title=Wakefield MP arranges delivery of 110,000 reusable face masks from Vietnam for NHS|work=[[The Yorkshire Post]]|last= Scott|first=Geraldine| date=18 April 2020 |accessdate=18 April 2020 }}</ref>\n**Unions representing doctors and nurses express their concern at a change in government guidelines advising medics to reuse gowns or wear other kit if stocks run low.<ref name=\"BBC gowns\"/>\n**Speaking at the Downing Street daily briefing, [[Robert Jenrick]], the [[Secretary of State for Local Government]] says a further 400,000 gowns will be arriving from Turkey the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/400000-more-gowns-nhs-arriving-18112744|title=400,000 more gowns for NHS arriving from Turkey tomorrow|first=Neil|last=Shaw|date=18 April 2020|website=walesonline}}</ref> \n**The number of recorded deaths rises by 888 to 15,464.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52335561|title=Concern over protective kit guidance change|date=18 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**[[Care England]], the UK's largest care homes representative body, estimates that as many as 7,500 care home residents may have died because of coronavirus, compared to the official figure of 1,400 released a few days earlier.<ref name=\"BBC gowns\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/18/uk-care-home-covid-19-deaths-may-be-five-times-government-estimate|title=UK care home Covid-19 deaths 'may be five times government estimate'|first=Molly|last=Blackall|date=18 April 2020|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n**Jenrick announces a further \u00a31.6bn of support for local authorities, on top of \u00a31.6bn that was given to them at the beginning of the outbreak.<ref name=\"18 April Briefing\"/>\n**Jenrick says that the virus appears to be having a \"disproportionate impact\" on the [[Black, Asian and minority ethnic]] (BAME) communities, while [[Stephen Powis]] says he has asked [[Public Health England]] to investigate what may be accounting for the increased risk within these groups.<ref name=\"18 April Briefing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52339266|title=English councils to get extra \u00a31.6bn virus support|date=18 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Jenrick says that parks and cemeteries must remain open during the lockdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52339266|title=Parks and cemeteries must stay open, says minister|date=18 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*19 April\n** The number of recorded deaths increases by 596 to 16,060, a lower increase than previous days. Dr Jenny Harries says the lower number of deaths is \"very good news\" but cautions against drawing conclusions from the figures.<ref name=\"19 April Briefing\" />\n**After a ''[[The Sunday Times|Sunday Times]]'' article suggests schools could reopen on 11 May, [[Gavin Williamson]], the [[Secretary of State for Education]], tells the Downing Street daily briefing he cannot give a date for when this will happen, and that the focus will be on helping children to learn at home, with lessons made available online and free loans of laptops for disadvantaged children.<ref name=\"19 April Briefing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52332903|title=No date for when schools will reopen \u2013 Williamson|date=19 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**The flight from Turkey carrying a shipment of 84 tonnes of PPE scheduled to land in the UK is delayed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/shipment-ppe-turkey-supply-coronavirus-18114873|title=84 tonnes of vital PPE shipment from Turkey to the UK delayed|first=Kathryn|last=Riddell|date=19 April 2020|website=nechronicle}}</ref>\n**BBC One airs a UK version of the ''[[Together at Home]]'' concert, a virtual global concert staged to celebrate healthcare workers and featuring musicians playing from home. The two-hour broadcast includes highlights of the US version and features stories of frontline workers along with extra footage of British artists.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52333890|title=Coronavirus: Stars take part in One World: Together At Home concert|date=19 April 2020|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 April 2020|publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52348000|title=Coronavirus: Little Mix and Tom Jones in Together At Home concert|date=19 April 2020|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 April 2020|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n*20 April\n**To protect bus drivers, [[Transport for London]] puts buses' front doors out of use, requiring passengers to board through the middle doors. Passengers are no longer required to pay, so that they do not need to use the card reader near the driver.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-free-travel-and-middle-door-only-boarding-on-london-buses-11974594|title=Coronavirus: Free travel and middle door only boarding on London buses|last=|first=|date=17 April 2020|website=Sky News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n**The [[Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme]] is launched, with 67,000 claims registered in the first 30 minutes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-52346685 |title=Coronavirus: Millions to claim as UK furlough scheme goes live |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=20 April 2020 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[NHS Blood and Transplant]] asks those who have survived coronavirus to donate blood for trials of a treatment that will involve giving the [[blood plasma]] of survivors to patients ill in hospital with the disease.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52348368 |title=Coronavirus: Plasma treatment to be trialled |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=20 April 2020 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The number of recorded deaths rises by 449, taking the total to 16,509, but Prof Dame [[Angela Maclean]], the UK's deputy chief scientific adviser, says the number of confirmed cases is \"flattening out\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52351029|title=RAF plane en route to Turkey amid NHS kit row|date=20 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The number of people in hospital for COVID-19 has begun to fall in Scotland, Wales and every region of England, with significant falls in London and the Midlands.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1252341342379728897|user=jburnmurdoch|title=Charts: Hospitals in every region now have fewer covid patients than same time last week|author=John Burn-Murdoch, [[Financial Times]]|date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n*21 April\n**A further 823 deaths are recorded, taking the total to 17,337, a sharp rise on the previous day, but many of these relate to deaths that occurred in previous days and weeks, and some date back as far as March. Prof Sir [[David Spiegelhalter]], of the [[University of Cambridge]], says the figures suggest the UK is past the peak and in a \"steadily\" albeit slowly improving position.<ref name=\"Deaths at 20-year high\">{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/uk-coronavirus-deaths-latest-figures-today-death-toll-overall-2545388|title=Latest daily UK coronavirus deaths rise to 823 as death toll passes 17,000|website=inews.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-52361519|title=Deaths hit 20-year high \u2013 but peak may be over|first=Nick|last=Triggle|date=21 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Figures released by the [[Office for National Statistics]] indicate deaths have reached a twenty year high, with 18,500 deaths in the week up to 10 April, about 8,000 more than the average for that time of year.<ref name=\"Deaths at 20-year high\"/> The deaths include those in care homes, which increased from 217 to 1,043 over the same week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/uk-news/care-home-coronavirus-deaths-rise-18123031|title=Coronavirus deaths in care homes leap to more than 1,000 in one week|first=Helen|last=Carter|date=21 April 2020|website=men}}</ref>\n**Matt Hancock says the government is \"throwing everything\" at developing a vaccine as he announces \u00a342.5m for clinical trials being conducted by [[Imperial College London]] and the [[University of Oxford]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52374653|title=UK 'throwing everything' at coronavirus vaccine|date=21 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Parliament reconvenes after the Easter recess with MPs approving a new arrangement with some in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] chamber and some attending via videolink.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52362667|title=MPs approve new way of working as Commons returns|date=21 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Fundraiser Captain Tom Moore is the guest of honour at the opening of [[NHS Nightingale Hospital Yorkshire and the Humber]] in Harrogate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-52368691|title=Capt Tom opens new NHS Nightingale hospital|date=21 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*22 April\n**An [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] plane carrying the delayed shipment of personal protective equipment from Turkey lands at [[RAF Brize Norton]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52378491|title=RAF plane lands with PPE from Turkey|date=22 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Figures show that UK inflation fell to 1.5% in March, largely because of the falls in the price of clothing and fuel ahead of the lockdown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-52371062|title=UK inflation falls as lockdown begins to bite|date=22 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Parliament holds the first virtual [[Prime Minister's Questions]] with Dominic Raab standing in for Boris Johnson, at which Raab confirms the target of 100,000 tests a day by the end of the month.<ref name=\"Virtual PMQs\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52383073|title=Raab vows to hit 100k test target in eight days|date=22 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**The number of recorded deaths rises by 759 to 18,100.<ref name=\"Virtual PMQs\" />\n**In a Commons statement Matt Hancock tells MPs \"we are at the peak\" of the outbreak but social distancing measures cannot be relaxed until the government's five tests have been met.<ref>https://www.itv.com/news/2020-04-22/we-are-at-the-peak-matt-hancock-notes-positive-sign-but-warns-against-relaxing-coronavirus-lockdown/</ref> Professor [[Chris Whitty]], the government's chief medical adviser, tells the Downing Street briefing the UK will have to live with some social distancing measures for at least the rest of the year, and that it is \"wholly unrealistic\" to expect life to suddenly return to normal in the short term.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52389285|title=Social restrictions 'to remain for rest of year'|date=22 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Doctors in Wales have written a joint letter to First Minister [[Mark Drakeford]] urging him to ban the use of [[Holiday cottage|second homes]] during the outbreak.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52055456</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Portal bar|United Kingdom|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Timeline of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British history timelines|Coronavirus]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Timeline of ongoing pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThe following is a timeline of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]].\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Kingdom medical cases chart}}\n\n==Timeline==\n[[File:2020 UK ONS weekly COVID19 deaths.png|right|Graph of weekly England and Wales death data from the [[Office for National Statistics]] including COVID-19 deaths in 2020<ref name=\"ONS_deaths_200403\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/birthsdeathsandmarriages/deaths/bulletins/deathsregisteredweeklyinenglandandwalesprovisional/weekending3april2020 |title=Deaths registered weekly in England and Wales, provisional \u2013 Office for National Statistics |last=[[Office for National Statistics]] |date=2020-04-20 |website=www.ons.gov.uk |access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>]]\n=== January ===\n*25 January \u2013 The [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] advises against all travel to China's [[Hubei Province]], where the city of Wuhan, the original epicentre of the outbreak, is located.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-china-health-britain-idUKKBN1ZO0SW|title=Britain advises against all travel to China's Hubei province|date=25 January 2020|website=Reuters UK}}</ref>\n*27 January \u2013 The Health Secretary, [[Matt Hancock]], tells the House of Commons that 200 British citizens trapped in [[Wuhan]], [[China]], will be offered repatriation to the UK, in light of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak in Hubei|coronavirus outbreak there]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/27/britons-in-wuhan-will-be-offered-help-to-leave-hancock-tells-mps |title=Britons in Wuhan will be offered help to leave, Hancock tells MPs |work=The Guardian|date=27 January 2020 |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n*28 January \u2013 The Foreign and Commonwealth Office updates its travel advisory, advising against all but essential travel to the rest of [[Mainland China]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/amp/uk-51288672 |title=Coronavirus: Foreign Office warns against 'all but essential travel' to China |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=28 January 2020 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n*29 January \u2013 [[British Airways]] suspends all flights to and from mainland China with immediate effect, due to the ongoing coronavirus threat.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/29/evacuation-of-britons-in-coronavirus-hit-hubei-could-begin-thursday |title=Britons evacuated due to coronavirus to be quarantined |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper==The Guardian |date=29 January 2020 |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n*31 January \u2013 The first two cases of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus (2019-nCoV) in the United Kingdom]] are confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-51325192|title=Two coronavirus cases confirmed in UK|date=2020-01-31|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-02|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n*6 February \u2013 A third case of coronavirus is confirmed in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51398039|title=Coronavirus: Third case confirmed in the UK\n|website=BBC News|language=en|date=2020-02-06|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n*27 February \u2013 Authorities confirm the first case of [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus]] in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51667483 |title=Northern Ireland diagnoses first coronavirus case |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=27 February 2020 |accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n*28 February\n**The first British death from the disease is confirmed by the [[Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare|Japanese Health Ministry]]; a man [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships|quarantined]] on the ''[[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]]'' cruise ship.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/28/first-briton-dies-from-coronavirus-japanese-media-report-diamond-princess |title=First British coronavirus death confirmed|work=The Guardian|date=28 February 2020 |accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n**Authorities confirm the first case of coronavirus in Wales, an individual who recently returned from holiday in Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51673068|title=Coronavirus: First case in Wales confirmed|website=BBC News|date=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== March ===\n*1 March \u2013 Authorities confirm the first case of coronavirus in Scotland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gov.scot/news/coronavirus-covid-19/ |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19): First positive case in Scotland |publisher=Scottish Government |date=1 March 2020 |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n*2 March \u2013 The government holds a [[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms|COBRA]] meeting to discuss its preparations and response to the virus, as the number of UK cases jumps to 36.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51700604 |title=Coronavirus: Widespread transmission in UK 'highly likely' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=2 March 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n*3 March \u2013 The government publishes its action plan for dealing with coronavirus. This includes scenarios ranging from a milder pandemic to a \"severe prolonged pandemic [[Spanish flu|as experienced in 1918]]\" and warns that a fifth of the national workforce could be absent from work during the infection's peak.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51718917 |title=Coronavirus: Up to fifth of UK workers 'off sick at same time' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=3 March 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/03/uk-government-coronavirus-plans-strip-fire-and-police-to-essentials-covid-19 |title=UK coronavirus plans would strip police and fire services to essentials |work=The Guardian|date=3 March 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n*5 March\n**The airline [[Flybe]] collapses into administration, due in part to the impact of the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51746564 |title=Collapsed Flybe tells passengers not to travel to airports |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The first death from coronavirus in the UK is confirmed,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51759602 |title=Coronavirus: Older patient becomes first virus fatality in UK |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC News |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> as the number of cases exceeds 100, with a total of 115 having tested positive. England's [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officer]], [[Chris Whitty]], tells MPs that the UK has now moved to the second stage of dealing with COVID-19 \u2013 from \"containment\" to the \"delay\" phase.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/more-than-a-hundred-people-in-uk-infected-with-coronavirus |title=More than a hundred people in UK infected with coronavirus |work=The Guardian|date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n*6 March \u2013 The Prime Minister announces \u00a346 million in funding for research into a coronavirus vaccine and rapid diagnostic tests. During a visit to a laboratory in Bedfordshire, he says: \"It looks like there will be a substantial period of disruption where we have to deal with this outbreak.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/06/coronavirus-update-latest-live-news-symptoms-cases-global-infection-rate-uk-usa-australia-italy-china-updates?page=with:block-5e624ca98f087df56e4c37f9#block-5e624ca98f087df56e4c37f9 |title=Coronavirus latest updates |work=The Guardian|date=6 March 2020 |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n*8 March \u2013 A third death from coronavirus is reported, at [[North Manchester General Hospital]], as the number of cases in the UK reaches 273, the largest single-day increase so far.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51796072 |title=Coronavirus: Man in his 60s becomes third UK death |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=8 March 2020 |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n*9 March \u2013 The [[FTSE 100]] plunges by more than 8 percent, its largest intraday fall since 2008, amid concerns over the spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cityam.com/coronavirus-ftse-100-plunges-on-open-after-oil-prices-crash-30-per-cent/ |title=Coronavirus: FTSE 100 plunges after oil prices crash 30 per cent |work=City AM |publisher=City AM |date=9 March 2020 |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n*10 March \u2013 Health minister [[Nadine Dorries]] tests positive for coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51827356 |title=Coronavirus: Health minister Nadine Dorries tests positive |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*11 March\n**The [[Bank of England]] cuts its baseline interest rate from 0.75% to 0.25%, back down to the lowest level in history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51831004 |title=UK interest rates cut in emergency move |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], [[Rishi Sunak]], presents the Johnson Government's [[March 2020 United Kingdom budget|first budget]], which includes \u00a330 billion in measures to protect the economy from coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-budget/uk-pledges-30-billion-to-protect-economy-from-coronavirus-idUKKBN20Y007 |title=UK pledges \u00a330 billion to protect economy from coronavirus |work=Reuters |publisher=Reuters |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51835306 |title=Budget 2020: Chancellor unveils \u00a330bn coronavirus package |work=BBC News|publisher=BBC News|date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/11/key-points-from-budget-2020-at-a-glance |title=Key points from budget 2020 \u2013 at a glance |work=The Guardian|date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Wales has its first case of \"community transmission\", when a patient in Caerphilly with no travel history tests positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51836057|title=Coronavirus: First community transmission detected in Wales|date=11 March 2020|website=BBC News}}</ref>\n*12 March\n**Following a series of recent major falls, the FTSE100 plunges yet again, this time by over 10%, its biggest drop since 1987.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51829852 |title=Coronavirus: Global stocks plunge as coronavirus fears spread |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2020/mar/12/stock-markets-tumble-trump-europe-travel-ban-ecb-christine-lagarde-business-live?page=with:block-5e6a636e8f08c2df6d278620#block-5e6a636e8f08c2df6d278620 |title=FTSE 100 suffers second worst day ever after 10.87% plunge \u2013 business live |work=The Guardian|date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> Other markets around the world are similarly affected by ongoing economic turmoil.\n**A patient at [[Wrexham Maelor Hospital]] tests positive for COVID-19 \u2013 the first case in North Wales.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-03-12/reports-of-coronavirus-patient-admitted-to-wrexham-maelor-hospital/|title=First case of coronavirus confirmed in north Wales, ITV Wales understands|date=12 March 2020|website=ITV News}}</ref>\n**[[Public Health England]] stops performing [[contact tracing]], in view of the wide spread of infection in the population.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Tapper|first=James|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/04/recruit-volunteer-army-to-trace-coronavirus-contacts-now-urge-top-scientists|title=Recruit volunteer army to trace Covid-19 contacts now, urge top scientists|date=2020-04-04|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n*13 March \n**Authorities confirm the first death from coronavirus in Scotland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51874899 |title=Coronavirus: Death of first Scottish patient with Covid-19 confirmed |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[Premier League]] [[2019\u201320 Premier League|2019\u20132020 season]] is suspended, amid a growing list of worldwide sporting cancellations and postponements due to COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867989 |title=Coronavirus: Premier League and EFL suspended until 3 April at earliest |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Elections including the [[2020 United Kingdom local elections|English local elections]], [[2020 London mayoral election|London mayoral election]] and [[2020 England and Wales police and crime commissioner elections|police and crime commissioner elections]], scheduled for May 2020, are postponed for a year because of the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51876269 |title=Coronavirus: English local elections postponed for a year |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The Welsh Government's Health Minister [[Vaughan Gething]] announces that all non-urgent outpatient appointments and operations will be suspended at hospitals in Wales, in a bid to delay the spread of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-03-13/20-000-deaths-in-wales-predicted-in-worst-case-scenario-as-measures-announced-to-cope-with-coronavirus/ |title=Over 20,000 deaths in Wales predicted in 'worst case scenario' as measures announced to cope with coronavirus |work=ITV News |publisher=ITV |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n*14 March\n**A further 10 people are reported to have died from COVID-19, almost doubling the UK death toll from 11 to 21. The government's aim for a \"[[herd immunity]]\" approach generates controversy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/health/uk-herd-immunity-coronavirus-who-margaret-harris-a4387346.html |title=UK's 'herd immunity' approach to tackling coronavirus questioned by World Health Organisation |work=Evening Standard|date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-51892402 |title=Coronavirus: Scientists say UK virus strategy is 'risking lives' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC News |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://maths.qmul.ac.uk/~vnicosia/UK_scientists_statement_on_coronavirus_measures.pdf |title=Public request to take stronger measures of socialdistancing across the UK with immediate effect |work=Queen Mary University of London |publisher=Queen Mary University of London |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Vice President of the United States]], [[Mike Pence]], announces the US is to extend its European [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States#Travel and entry restrictions|coronavirus travel ban]] to include the UK from 16 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-51891662 |title=Coronavirus: US to extend travel ban to UK and Ireland |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n**UK retailers release a joint letter asking customers not to panic buy products after some supermarkets sell out of items such as pasta, hand gel and toilet paper.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51883440 |title=Coronavirus: Supermarkets ask shoppers to be 'considerate' and stop panic buying |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n*15 March \n**The [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] advises against \"all but essential travel\" to the US.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/15/coronavirus-latest-updates-trump-tests-negative-as-spain-orders-nationwide-lockdown-uk-us-australia-italy-europe-global-economy?page=with:block-5e6e17e48f088d7575593aed#block-5e6e17e48f088d7575593aed |title=UK advises against 'all but essential' travel to US |work=The Guardian|date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Health Secretary [[Matt Hancock]] says that every UK resident over the age of 70 will be told \"within the coming weeks\" to self-isolate for \"a very long time\" to shield them from coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51895873 |title=Coronavirus: Isolation for over-70s 'within weeks' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The government announces plans to hold daily televised press conferences to update the public on the fight against the coronavirus pandemic, starting on Monday 16 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51901818 |title=Coronavirus: Downing Street to give daily update on fight against outbreak |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n*16 March\n**The UK death toll from the pandemic reaches 55, with the number of cases of the illness passing 1,500.<ref name=avoid>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51917562 |title=Coronavirus: PM says everyone should avoid office, pubs and travelling |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Prime Minister Boris Johnson advises everyone in the UK against \"non-essential\" travel and contact with others, to curb coronavirus, as well as suggesting people should avoid pubs, clubs and theatres, and work from home if possible. Pregnant women, people over the age of 70 and those with certain health conditions are urged to consider the advice \"particularly important\", and will be asked to self-isolate within days.<ref name=avoid/>\n**The BBC delays its planned changes to TV licences for the over-75s from June to August because of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51911065 |title=Coronavirus: BBC delays over-75 TV licence fee changes |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n*17 March\n**NHS England announces that from 15 April all non-urgent operations in England will be postponed, to free up 30,000 beds to help tackle the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51933410 |title=Coronavirus: All non-urgent operations in England postponed |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The Chancellor, Rishi Sunak, announces that \u00a3330bn will be made available in loan guarantees for businesses affected by the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/mar/17/boris-johnson-coronavirus-press-conference-rishi-sunak-cabinet-as-rishi-sunak-set-to-announcing-coronavirus-financial-rescue-package-politics-live?page=with:block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b#block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b |title=Sunak says he will make \u00a3330bn available in lending to keep firms in business |work=The Guardian|date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51935467 |title=Coronavirus: Chancellor unveils \u00a3330bn lifeline for economy |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The Foreign and Commonwealth Office advises against all non-essential international travel due to the pandemic and the border restrictions put in place by many countries in response.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/travel-advice-foreign-secreatary-statement-17-march-2020 |title=Travel Advice against all non-essential travel: Foreign Secretary's statement, 17 March 2020 |publisher=GOV.UK |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The UK coronavirus-related death toll rises to 71, while the number of confirmed cases of the illness rises to 1,950.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jane |last=Dalton |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/uk-coronavirus-death-toll-nhs-latest-outbreak-pandemic-a9407311.html |title=UK coronavirus death toll rises to 71 |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/uk-coronavirus-cases-reach-1-950-up-407-in-24-hours-11958875 |title=Coronavirus: 14 more deaths in England \u2013 UK total now 71 |publisher=Sky UK |work=Sky News |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[National Assembly for Wales]] is closed to the public.\n*18 March\n**[[Pound sterling]] falls below $1.18, its lowest level since [[1985 in the United Kingdom|1985]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/40272e84-68ff-11ea-a3c9-1fe6fedcca75 |title=Pound sinks under $1.19 in deepening coronavirus market crisis |publisher=FT |work=FT |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailyfx.com/gbp-usd |title=GBP/USD: Pound \u2013 Dollar Rate, Chart, Forecast &amp; Analysis |publisher=Daily FX |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> Bank of England governor [[Andrew Bailey (banker)|Andrew Bailey]], commenting on the UK and wider economic situation, says: \"It's obviously an emergency. I think we're living in completely unparalleled times... It's going to be a very big downturn \u2013 we know that.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-boe-could-take-radical-money-printing-action-11959670 |title=Coronavirus: 'Radical' money printing plan being considered by the Bank of England |work=Sky News |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The UK death toll from coronavirus exceeds 100, with 32 new cases taking the total to 104.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-32-more-covid-19-patients-die-in-england-taking-uk-total-to-104-11959809 |title=Coronavirus: 32 more COVID-19 patients die in England \u2013 taking UK total to 104 |work=Sky News |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The government announces that all schools in the country will shut from the afternoon of Friday 20 March, except for those looking after the children of key workers and vulnerable children.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51952314 |title=Coronavirus: Schools to close until further notice from Friday |work=BBC News |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> No exams will take place this academic year, [[Secretary of State for Education|Education Secretary]] [[Gavin Williamson]] confirms.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-uk-schools-to-close-from-friday-11959769 |title=Coronavirus: UK schools to close from Friday until further notice |work=Sky News |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The 50th anniversary [[Glastonbury Festival]] is cancelled as a result of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/mar/18/uk-coronavirus-live-boris-johnson-pmqs-cbi-urges-government-pay-businesses-directly-saying-350bn-loangrant-package-not-enough |title=All schools to close from Friday; GCSE and A-level exams cancelled \u2013 UK coronavirus, as it happened |work=The Guardian |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The government announces emergency legislation to bring in a complete ban on new evictions for three months, as part of measures to help protect renters in social and private rented accommodation.\n*19 March \u2013 In an emergency move, the Bank of England cuts interest rates again, from 0.25% to just 0.1%. This is the lowest rate in the Bank's 325-year history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51962982 |title=Coronavirus: UK interest rates slashed to lowest level ever |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n*20 March\n**[[Northwick Park Hospital]] in [[London Borough of Harrow|Harrow]] declares a \"critical incident\" due to a surge in patients with coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/news/hospitals-critical-care-unit-overwhelmed-by-coronavirus-patients/7027189.article |title=Hospital's critical care unit overwhelmed by coronavirus patients |work=HSJ |publisher=HSJ|date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Chancellor Rishi Sunak announces that the government will pay 80% of wages for employees not working, up to \u00a32,500 a month, as part of \"unprecedented\" measures to protect people's jobs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51982005 |title=Wages cover for businesses hit by virus outlined |publisher=BBC News|date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Prime Minister Boris Johnson orders all cafes, pubs and restaurants to close from the evening of 20 March, except for take-away food, to tackle coronavirus. All the UK's nightclubs, theatres, cinemas, gyms and leisure centres are told to close \"as soon as they reasonably can\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51981653 |title=UK pubs and restaurants told to shut in virus fight |publisher=BBC News|date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n*21 March \u2013 [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment Secretary]] [[George Eustice]] urges shoppers to stop [[panic buying]], as supermarkets around the UK struggle to keep up with demand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51989721 |title=Coronavirus: Shoppers told to buy responsibly |publisher=BBC News|date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> [[Tesco]], [[Asda]], [[Aldi]], and [[Lidl]] are reported to have begun a recruitment drive for up to 30,000 new staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51976075 |title=Supermarkets Tesco, Asda, Aldi and Lidl go on hiring spree |publisher=BBC News|date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n*22 March\n**The [[Nursing and Midwifery Council]] announces that more than 5,600 former nurses have registered to offer their services in the fight against coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/22/uk-coronavirus-live-police-could-enforce-london-lockdown-says-khan-seven-people-die-in-wales?page=with:block-5e776a4f8f08dcc95cc20fdd#block-5e776a4f8f08dcc95cc20fdd |title=UK coronavirus live: police could enforce London social distancing; seven people die in Wales |work=The Guardian|date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Boris Johnson warns that \"tougher measures\" may be introduced if people do not follow government advice on social distancing.<ref name=\"tougher measures\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51998559 |title=Coronavirus: Follow virus advice or 'tougher measures' likely, says PM |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> \n**The virus claims its youngest victim so far, with the death of an eighteen-year-old with underlying health problems.<ref name=\"tougher measures\"/>\n*23 March\n**The government announces emergency measures to safeguard the nation's [[Rail transport in the United Kingdom|rail network]], with season ticket holders given refunds if working from home, and [[Passenger rail franchising in Great Britain|rail franchise agreements]] nationalised for at least six months to prevent rail companies from collapsing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-52002272 |title=Commuters to get refund on rail season tickets |publisher=BBC News|date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-rail-franchise-agreements-suspended-to-avoid-company-collapses-11962186 |title=Coronavirus: Rail franchise agreements suspended to avoid company collapses |publisher=Sky News|date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Pride in London]], the UK's largest LGBT [[Pride festival]], scheduled for 27 June, is the latest event to be postponed. It is one of a hundred pride events to be postponed or cancelled in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hunte |first=Ben |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-52001388 |title=Coronavirus postpones London Pride |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n**In a televised address, Boris Johnson announces a UK-wide lockdown with immediate effect, to contain the spread of the virus. People can leave their homes only for \"very limited purposes\" \u2013 shopping for basic necessities; for one form of exercise a day; for any medical need; and to travel to and from work when \"absolutely necessary\". A number of other restrictions are imposed, with police given powers to enforce the measures, including the use of fines.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-52000039 |title='You must stay at home' UK public told| publisher=BBC | date=23 March 2020| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52012432 |title=Coronavirus: Strict new curbs on life in UK announced by PM| publisher=BBC | date=23 March 2020| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/23/boris-johnson-orders-uk-lockdown-to-be-enforced-by-police |title=Boris Johnson orders UK lockdown to be enforced by police| work=The Guardian| date=23 March 2020| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n*24 March\n**The UK records its highest number of coronavirus deaths in one day, after a further 87 people die across the country, bringing the total to 422.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-calls-for-police-at-stations-after-packed-trains-defy-lockdown-11962837|title=Coronavirus: Biggest daily rise in UK deaths \u2013 up by 87 to 422\n| publisher=Sky News| date=24 March 2020| accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**For the first time, all of the UK's [[List of mobile network operators of Europe#United Kingdom|mobile networks]] send out a government text alert, ordering people to stay at home. The message reads: \"''GOV.UK CORONAVIRUS ALERT. New rules in force now: you must stay at home. More info and exemptions at gov.uk/coronavirus Stay at home. Protect the NHS. Save lives.''\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-52017451|title=Coronavirus: Mobile networks send 'stay at home' text| publisher=BBC News| date=24 March 2020| accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Secretary of State for Health|Health Secretary]] [[Matt Hancock]] announces the government will open a temporary hospital, the [[NHS Nightingale Hospital]] at the [[ExCeL London]], to add extra critical care capacity in response to coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52018477|title=Coronavirus: ExCeL Centre planned as NHS field hospital| publisher=BBC News| date=24 March 2020| accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[Scottish Parliament]] closes, with plans to reconvene on 1 April to discuss emergency legislation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-52018354 |title=FMQs cancelled as Holyrood chamber shuts for a week |work=BBC News |date=24 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*25 March\n**[[Prince Charles]] tests positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52033845|title=Coronavirus: Prince Charles tests positive but 'remains in good health'| publisher=BBC News| date=25 March 2020| accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] shuts down for a month.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52032188|title=Coronavirus: Parliament shuts down for a month| publisher=BBC News| date=25 March 2020| accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[British Transport Police]] deploys 500 officers to patrol the UK's rail network, in an effort to discourage non-essential journeys. New measures are also introduced on the [[London Underground]] to reduce passenger numbers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-52023580|title=Coronavirus: New Tube restrictions to stop non-essential journeys| publisher=BBC News| date=25 March 2020| accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n*26 March\n**The government announces that the [[Self-employment|self-employed]] will be paid 80% of profits, up to \u00a32,500 a month, to help them cope during the economic crisis triggered by COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52053914|title=Coronavirus: UK government unveils aid for self-employed| publisher=BBC News| date=26 March 2020| accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n**At 8pm, millions of people around the country take part in a \"[[Clap for our Carers|Clap for Carers]]\" tribute, applauding the NHS and other care workers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52058013|title=Clap for Carers: UK in 'emotional' tribute to NHS and care workers| publisher=BBC News| date=27 March 2020| accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*27 March\n**Prime Minister Boris Johnson tests positive for COVID-19, and will self-isolate in [[10 Downing Street]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52060791|title=PM Boris Johnson tests positive for coronavirus| publisher=BBC News| date=27 March 2020| accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Health Secretary [[Matt Hancock]] tests positive for COVID-19 and reports that he is working from home and self-isolating.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-matt-hancock-boris-johnson-test-positive-covid-19-symptoms-a9430031.html|title=Coronavirus: Health secretary Matt Hancock tests positive| work=The Independent| date=27 March 2020| accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Leon Restaurants]] sets up the \"[[Feed NHS]]\" initiative to deliver 5,600 free meals a day to [[National Health Service|NHS]] [[intensive care medicine|critical care]] staff at London hospitals.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Butler|first=Sarah|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/27/leon-sets-up-initiative-to-deliver-free-hot-meals-to-nhs-staff-coronavirus|title=Leon sets up initiative to deliver free meals to NHS critical care staff|date=2020-03-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-29|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n*28 March \u2013 At 11pm, new regulations come into force in Northern Ireland giving authorities the power to force businesses to close, and impose fines on them if they refuse, as well as on people leaving their homes without a \"reasonable excuse\". The measures, introduced by the [[Northern Ireland Executive]], bring Northern Ireland into line with the rest of the UK.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-52079959 |title=New NI Covid-19 regulations come into force |work=BBC News |date=28 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-28/new-regulations-to-enforce-coronavirus-restrictions-agreed-by-stormont/ |title=Northern Ireland imposes fines up to \u00a35,000 for those breaching social distancing rules |website=ITV News}}</ref>\n*30 March \u2013 [[Foreign Secretary]] [[Dominic Raab]] announces an arrangement between the government and major UK airlines to fly home tens of thousands of British nationals who are stranded abroad by the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52099252|title=Rescue flights for stranded Britons|work=BBC News|date=30 March 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*31 March \u2013 A significant rise in [[anxiety]] and [[Depression (mood)|depression]] among the UK population is reported following the lockdown. The study, by researchers from the [[University of Sheffield]] and [[Ulster University]], finds that people reporting anxiety increased from 17% to 36%, while those reporting depression increased from 16% to 38%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/31/rise-in-depression-and-anxiety-day-after-uk-lockdown-announced-study-coronavirus |title=Rise in depression and anxiety day after UK lockdown announced \u2013 study| work=The Guardian| date=31 March 2020| accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n*1 April\n**The [[contactless payment]] limit for in-store spending is raised from \u00a330 to \u00a345.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2020/mar/24/limit-for-contactless-spending-to-rise-to-45-at-beginning-of-april|title=Limit for contactless spending to rise to \u00a345 at beginning of April|work=The Guardian|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[National Assembly for Wales]] reconvenes using [[Zoom (software)|Zoom]] for a virtual emergency [[Senedd Cymru|Senedd]] meeting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.assembly.wales/en/newhome/pages/newsitem.aspx?itemid=2092|title=Plenary meetings continue, but Senedd buildings will stay closed until June|website=National Assembly for Wales|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n**Multinational pharmaceutical company [[Hoffmann-La Roche|Roche]] denies the existence of a deal to supply Wales with COVID-19 tests after First Minister [[Mark Drakeford]] and Health Minister [[Vaughan Gething]] blame the collapse of a deal for a shortage of testing kits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/politics/mark-drakeford-roche-coronavirus-testing-18025301|title=Pharmaceutical giant Roche and Welsh Government at loggerheads over collapsed Covid-19 testing deal|date=1 April 2020|author=Will Hayward|website=WalesOnline|access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n*2 April \u2013 Matt Hancock, who returns to give the daily government briefing after completing his self-isolation, sets a target of carrying out 100,000 tests a day by the end of the month (encompassing both swab tests and blood tests).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52140376|title=Hancock aims for 100,000 tests a day by May|date=2020-04-02|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n*3 April \u2013 [[NHS Nightingale Hospital London]], the first temporary hospital to treat coronavirus patients, opens at the [[ExCeL London|ExCel centre]] in East London, employing NHS staff and military personnel, with 500 beds and potential capacity for 4,000. It is the first of several such facilities planned across the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52150598|title=Coronavirus: Nightingale Hospital opens at London's ExCel centre|work=BBC News|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n*4 April \u2013 The results of the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election]] and the [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election]] are announced, in which [[Keir Starmer]] is elected as the leader of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], succeeding [[Jeremy Corbyn]], and [[Angela Rayner]] is elected as deputy leader of the party. The results are released by email after a public event to announce the results was cancelled due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52164589|title=Keir Starmer elected as new Labour leader|work=BBC News|date=4 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n*5 April\n**[[Queen Elizabeth II]] makes a [[Addresses to the nation by Elizabeth II|rare broadcast to the UK]] and the wider Commonwealth, something she has done on only four previous occasions. In the address she thanks people for following the government's social distancing rules, pays tribute to key workers, and says the UK \"will succeed\" in its fight against coronavirus but may have \"more still to endure\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Caroline |last=Davies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/03/queen-to-address-nation-on-sunday-over-coronavirus-crisis |title=Queen to address nation on Sunday over coronavirus crisis |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=3 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52176222 |title=Coronavirus: Queen tells UK 'we will succeed' in fight |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n**Prime Minister Boris Johnson is admitted to hospital for tests after testing positive for coronavirus ten days earlier.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52177125 |title=Coronavirus: PM admitted to hospital over virus symptoms |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n*6 April\n**The death toll from COVID-19 in the UK exceeds 5,000. The total number of reported cases is nearly 52,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/apr/06/uk-coronavirus-live-boris-johnson-spends-night-in-hospital?page=with:block-5e8b4c078f080bdb9f535404#block-5e8b4c078f080bdb9f535404|title=UK death toll rises to 5,373|publisher=The Guardian|date=6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n**Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] is taken into [[intensive care unit|intensive care]] after being admitted to hospital for coronavirus the day before. It is announced that [[First Secretary of State]] [[Dominic Raab]] will deputise for him.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52192604 |title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson moved to intensive care |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[Orange Order|Orange Lodge of Ireland]] announces that the traditional [[Twelfth of July]] parades in Northern Ireland have been cancelled for 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52184743 |title=Coronavirus: Twelfth of July parades cancelled due to outbreak|date= 6 April 2020 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[National Express Coaches|National Express]] suspends all its long-distance coach services from this date.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/news-and-advice/national-express-coach-cancelled-suspended-bus-ticket-refund-a9442221.html|title=National Express to suspend all coach services|last=Xie|first=Qin|date=2020-04-02|website=The Independent|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n*7 April \u2013 The number of reported deaths increases by 786, taking the total to 6,159. Sir Patrick Vallance, the government's chief scientific adviser, says that the figures are not accelerating as had been predicted but that it is too early to tell whether the outbreak is peaking.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52206510|title=UK cases 'could be moving in the right direction'|date=7 April 2020|work=BBC News|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-britain-curve-idUSS8N2BU035|title=UK coronavirus cases not accelerating but too early to call a peak \u2013 chief science adviser|date=7 April 2020|newspaper=Reuters|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref>\n*8 April \u2013 The [[Resolution Foundation]], using figures from the [[British Chambers of Commerce]], reports that more than nine million workers are expected to be [[Furlough|furloughed]] under the government's job retention scheme, with an estimated cost to the taxpayer of between \u00a330 and 40bn.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-52209790 |title=Coronavirus: More than 9 million expected to be furloughed |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=8 April 2020 |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n*9 April\n**Foreign Secretary [[Dominic Raab]] says the UK is \"starting to see the impact\" of the restrictions but that it is \"too early\" to lift them, and urges people to stay indoors over the Easter weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52235492|title=Raab urges UK public not to ruin lockdown progress|publisher=BBC News|date=9 April 2020}}</ref> \n**Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] is moved out of intensive care, but remains in hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52238276|title=PM out of intensive care but remains in hospital|publisher=BBC News|date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n*11 April\n**[[Queen Elizabeth II]] makes her first ever [[Easter]] [[Addresses to the nation by Elizabeth II|message to the nation]], in which she states \"coronavirus will not overcome us\" and that \"we need Easter as much as ever.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52255054 |title=Coronavirus: 'We need Easter as much as ever,' says the Queen |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=11 April 2020 |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The number of people in London hospitals for COVID-19 reaches its peak, according to week-on-week change data; elsewhere in the country, patient numbers continue to increase, although the rate of increase is slowing.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1250904238399598594|user=jburnmurdoch|title=Charts: London\u2019s hospitals now have fewer covid patients with each day|author=John Burn-Murdoch, [[Financial Times]]|date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n*12 April\n**Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] is discharged from hospital after being treated for coronavirus and will continue his recovery at [[Chequers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52262012 |title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson discharged from hospital |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=12 April 2020 |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The number of people who died in hospital with coronavirus in the UK passes 10,000, after a daily rise of 737.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52264145 |title=Coronavirus: 'Sombre day' as UK deaths hit 10,000 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=12 April 2020 |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The temporary [[Dragon's Heart Hospital]] opens at Cardiff's [[Principality Stadium]] to admit its first patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/rugby/rugby-news/giant-tents-built-inside-principality-18081445|title=Giant tents emerge over Principality Stadium pitch as pictures show first hospital wards at iconic venue|website=WalesOnline|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n*14 April\n**The [[Office of National Statistics]] indicates that coronavirus was linked to one in five deaths during the week ending 3 April. More than 16,000 deaths in the UK were recorded for that week, 6,000 higher than would be the average for that time of year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-52278825|title=One in five deaths now linked to coronavirus|first=Nick|last=Triggle|work=BBC News|date=14 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Several UK charities, including [[Age UK]] and the [[Alzheimer's Society]], express their concern that older people are being \"airbrushed\" out of official figures because they focus on hospital deaths and do not include those in care homes or a person's own home. Responding to these concerns, [[Therese Coffey]], the [[Secretary of State for Work and Pensions]], says that hospital figures are being used because \"it's accurate and quick\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52275823|title=Elderly being 'airbrushed' out of virus figures|work=BBC News|date=14 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Mobile operators report a further twenty attempted arson attacks on mobile phone masts over the previous weekend.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-52281315|title=Twenty suspected phone mast attacks over Easter|first=Leo|last=Kelion|work=BBC News|date=14 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*15 April\n**Health Secretary Matt Hancock announces new guidelines that will allow close family members to see dying relatives in order to say goodbye to them. Hancock also launches a new network to provide personal protective equipment to care home staff.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52299590|title=Coronavirus: Close family to be allowed to say goodbye to the dying \u2013 BBC News|work=BBC News|date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[NHS England]] and the [[Care Quality Commission]] begin rolling out tests for care home staff and residents as it is reported the number of care home deaths are rising but that official figures, which rely on death certificates, are not reflecting the full extent of the problem. [[Helen Whately]], the Minister for Social Care, says that the government are aware the figures are being understated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/apr/15/coronavirus-death-toll-in-englands-care-homes-reaches-1400|title=Care homes in England say coronavirus death toll has risen to 1,400|first=Robert |last=Booth|date=15 April 2020|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n**[[Arlene Foster]], the [[First Minister of Northern Ireland]], extends the period of lockdown in Northern Ireland to 9 May.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-52298748|title=Three-week extension to NI coronavirus lockdown|first=Jayne|last=McCormack|date=15 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*16 April\n** A 99-year-old war veteran, [[Tom Moore (fundraiser)|Tom Moore]], completes 100 laps of his garden,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52303859 |title=Coronavirus: Capt Tom Moore finishes NHS fundraiser as it tops \u00a313m |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> eventually raising over \u00a325 million for [[NHS Charities Together]], with over a million people donating via his [[JustGiving]] page.<ref name=\"JGTM\">{{cite web |title=Captain Tom Moore's 100th Birthday Walk for the NHS |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs |publisher=[[JustGiving]] |accessdate=19 April 2020 }}</ref>\n**Foreign Secretary [[Dominic Raab]] announces a three-week extension to the nationwide lockdown measures as the number of confirmed COVID-19 cases in the UK surpasses 100,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52313715 |title=Coronavirus: UK lockdown extended for 'at least three weeks' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[NHS Nightingale Hospital Birmingham]], at the [[National Exhibition Centre]], is officially opened by [[William, Duke of Cambridge|Prince William]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-birmingham-52309494|title=Nightingale hospital 'example of pulling together'|date=16 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**The UK stages a fourth round of applause for NHS staff and key workers at 8pm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-04-16/uk-clap-for-our-carers-nhs-coronavirus-lockdown/|title=UK unites for fourth week in nationwide Clap For Our Carers to thank NHS workers fighting coronavirus pandemic|website=ITV News}}</ref>\n*17 April \n**Matt Hancock confirms coronavirus tests will be rolled out to cover more public service staff such as police officers, firefighters and prison staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52322447|title=Virus tests expanded to more public service staff|date=17 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> \n**Chancellor [[Rishi Sunak]] extends the subsidised wage scheme for furloughed workers for another month, to the end of June.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-52323918|title=Government extends furlough scheme to pay staff|date=17 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*18 April \n**[[Imran Ahmad-Khan]], the MP for [[Wakefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Wakefield]], secures a shipment of 110,000 reusable face masks through his connections with charity [[Solidarit\u00e9s international]] and the [[Government of Vietnam|Vietnamese Government]] for [[The Mid Yorkshire Hospitals NHS Trust|Mid Yorkshire Hospitals NHS Trust]] to help tackle the shortage of PPE.<ref name=ImranAhmadkhan-response>{{cite news |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/health/coronavirus/wakefield-mp-arranges-delivery-110000-reusable-face-masks-vietnam-nhs-2539775 |title=Wakefield MP arranges delivery of 110,000 reusable face masks from Vietnam for NHS|work=[[The Yorkshire Post]]|last= Scott|first=Geraldine| date=18 April 2020 |accessdate=18 April 2020 }}</ref>\n**Unions representing doctors and nurses express their concern at a change in government guidelines advising medics to reuse gowns or wear other kit if stocks run low.<ref name=\"BBC gowns\"/>\n**Speaking at the Downing Street daily briefing, [[Robert Jenrick]], the [[Secretary of State for Local Government]] says a further 400,000 gowns will be arriving from Turkey the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/400000-more-gowns-nhs-arriving-18112744|title=400,000 more gowns for NHS arriving from Turkey tomorrow|first=Neil|last=Shaw|date=18 April 2020|website=walesonline}}</ref> \n**The number of recorded deaths rises by 888 to 15,464.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52335561|title=Concern over protective kit guidance change|date=18 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**[[Care England]], the UK's largest care homes representative body, estimates that as many as 7,500 care home residents may have died because of coronavirus, compared to the official figure of 1,400 released a few days earlier.<ref name=\"BBC gowns\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/18/uk-care-home-covid-19-deaths-may-be-five-times-government-estimate|title=UK care home Covid-19 deaths 'may be five times government estimate'|first=Molly|last=Blackall|date=18 April 2020|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n**Jenrick announces a further \u00a31.6bn of support for local authorities, on top of \u00a31.6bn that was given to them at the beginning of the outbreak.<ref name=\"18 April Briefing\"/>\n**Jenrick says that the virus appears to be having a \"disproportionate impact\" on the [[Black, Asian and minority ethnic]] (BAME) communities, while [[Stephen Powis]] says he has asked [[Public Health England]] to investigate what may be accounting for the increased risk within these groups.<ref name=\"18 April Briefing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52339266|title=English councils to get extra \u00a31.6bn virus support|date=18 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Jenrick says that parks and cemeteries must remain open during the lockdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52339266|title=Parks and cemeteries must stay open, says minister|date=18 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*19 April\n** The number of recorded deaths increases by 596 to 16,060, a lower increase than previous days. Dr Jenny Harries says the lower number of deaths is \"very good news\" but cautions against drawing conclusions from the figures.<ref name=\"19 April Briefing\" />\n**After a ''[[The Sunday Times|Sunday Times]]'' article suggests schools could reopen on 11 May, [[Gavin Williamson]], the [[Secretary of State for Education]], tells the Downing Street daily briefing he cannot give a date for when this will happen, and that the focus will be on helping children to learn at home, with lessons made available online and free loans of laptops for disadvantaged children.<ref name=\"19 April Briefing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52332903|title=No date for when schools will reopen \u2013 Williamson|date=19 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**The flight from Turkey carrying a shipment of 84 tonnes of PPE scheduled to land in the UK is delayed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/shipment-ppe-turkey-supply-coronavirus-18114873|title=84 tonnes of vital PPE shipment from Turkey to the UK delayed|first=Kathryn|last=Riddell|date=19 April 2020|website=nechronicle}}</ref>\n**BBC One airs a UK version of the ''[[Together at Home]]'' concert, a virtual global concert staged to celebrate healthcare workers and featuring musicians playing from home. The two-hour broadcast includes highlights of the US version and features stories of frontline workers along with extra footage of British artists.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52333890|title=Coronavirus: Stars take part in One World: Together At Home concert|date=19 April 2020|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 April 2020|publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52348000|title=Coronavirus: Little Mix and Tom Jones in Together At Home concert|date=19 April 2020|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 April 2020|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n*20 April\n**To protect bus drivers, [[Transport for London]] puts buses' front doors out of use, requiring passengers to board through the middle doors. Passengers are no longer required to pay, so that they do not need to use the card reader near the driver.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-free-travel-and-middle-door-only-boarding-on-london-buses-11974594|title=Coronavirus: Free travel and middle door only boarding on London buses|last=|first=|date=17 April 2020|website=Sky News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n**The [[Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme]] is launched, with 67,000 claims registered in the first 30 minutes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-52346685 |title=Coronavirus: Millions to claim as UK furlough scheme goes live |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=20 April 2020 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[NHS Blood and Transplant]] asks those who have survived coronavirus to donate blood for trials of a treatment that will involve giving the [[blood plasma]] of survivors to patients ill in hospital with the disease.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52348368 |title=Coronavirus: Plasma treatment to be trialled |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=20 April 2020 |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The number of recorded deaths rises by 449, taking the total to 16,509, but Prof Dame [[Angela Maclean]], the UK's deputy chief scientific adviser, says the number of confirmed cases is \"flattening out\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52351029|title=RAF plane en route to Turkey amid NHS kit row|date=20 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The number of people in hospital for COVID-19 has begun to fall in Scotland, Wales and every region of England, with significant falls in London and the Midlands.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1252341342379728897|user=jburnmurdoch|title=Charts: Hospitals in every region now have fewer covid patients than same time last week|author=John Burn-Murdoch, [[Financial Times]]|date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n*21 April\n**A further 823 deaths are recorded, taking the total to 17,337, a sharp rise on the previous day, but many of these relate to deaths that occurred in previous days and weeks, and some date back as far as March. Prof Sir [[David Spiegelhalter]], of the [[University of Cambridge]], says the figures suggest the UK is past the peak and in a \"steadily\" albeit slowly improving position.<ref name=\"Deaths at 20-year high\">{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/uk-coronavirus-deaths-latest-figures-today-death-toll-overall-2545388|title=Latest daily UK coronavirus deaths rise to 823 as death toll passes 17,000|website=inews.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-52361519|title=Deaths hit 20-year high \u2013 but peak may be over|first=Nick|last=Triggle|date=21 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Figures released by the [[Office for National Statistics]] indicate deaths have reached a twenty year high, with 18,500 deaths in the week up to 10 April, about 8,000 more than the average for that time of year.<ref name=\"Deaths at 20-year high\"/> The deaths include those in care homes, which increased from 217 to 1,043 over the same week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/uk-news/care-home-coronavirus-deaths-rise-18123031|title=Coronavirus deaths in care homes leap to more than 1,000 in one week|first=Helen|last=Carter|date=21 April 2020|website=men}}</ref>\n**Matt Hancock says the government is \"throwing everything\" at developing a vaccine as he announces \u00a342.5m for clinical trials being conducted by [[Imperial College London]] and the [[University of Oxford]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52374653|title=UK 'throwing everything' at coronavirus vaccine|date=21 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Parliament reconvenes after the Easter recess with MPs approving a new arrangement with some in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] chamber and some attending via videolink.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52362667|title=MPs approve new way of working as Commons returns|date=21 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Fundraiser Captain Tom Moore is the guest of honour at the opening of [[NHS Nightingale Hospital Yorkshire and the Humber]] in Harrogate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-52368691|title=Capt Tom opens new NHS Nightingale hospital|date=21 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*22 April\n**An [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] plane carrying the delayed shipment of personal protective equipment from Turkey lands at [[RAF Brize Norton]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52378491|title=RAF plane lands with PPE from Turkey|date=22 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Figures show that UK inflation fell to 1.5% in March, largely because of the falls in the price of clothing and fuel ahead of the lockdown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-52371062|title=UK inflation falls as lockdown begins to bite|date=22 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Parliament holds the first virtual [[Prime Minister's Questions]] with Dominic Raab standing in for Boris Johnson, at which Raab confirms the target of 100,000 tests a day by the end of the month.<ref name=\"Virtual PMQs\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52383073|title=Raab vows to hit 100k test target in eight days|date=22 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**The number of recorded deaths rises by 759 to 18,100.<ref name=\"Virtual PMQs\" />\n**In a Commons statement Matt Hancock tells MPs \"we are at the peak\" of the outbreak but social distancing measures cannot be relaxed until the government's five tests have been met.<ref>https://www.itv.com/news/2020-04-22/we-are-at-the-peak-matt-hancock-notes-positive-sign-but-warns-against-relaxing-coronavirus-lockdown/</ref> Professor [[Chris Whitty]], the government's chief medical adviser, tells the Downing Street briefing the UK will have to live with some social distancing measures for at least the rest of the year, and that it is \"wholly unrealistic\" to expect life to suddenly return to normal in the short term.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52389285|title=Social restrictions 'to remain for rest of year'|date=22 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Doctors in Wales have written a joint letter to First Minister [[Mark Drakeford]] urging him to ban the use of [[Holiday cottage|second homes]] during the outbreak.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52055456</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Portal bar|United Kingdom|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Timeline of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British history timelines|Coronavirus]]\n", "name_user": "AntiCompositeNumber", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Remove link toPortal:Pandemic: duplicated byPortal:Coronavirus disease 2019", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timeline_of_the_2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_United_Kingdom"}
{"title_page": "World Wide Fund for Nature", "text_new": "{{short description|International non-governmental organization}}\n{{distinguish|World Wrestling Federation}}\n{{Third-party|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use British English Oxford spelling|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{coord|46.4171864|6.2709482|display=title}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = World Wildlife Fund \n| image = WWF logo.svg\n| image_size = 125px\n| alt = WWF logo\n| map = \n| map_size = \n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = \n| map2 = \n| map2_size = \n| map2_alt = \n| map2_caption = \n| abbreviation = \n| motto = \n| formation = {{start date and age|df=yes|1961|04|29}}\u2009(as World Wildlife Fund)<sup>a</sup>\n| founders = {{plainlist|\n* [[Prince Bernhard of Lippe-Biesterfeld]]\u2009<sup>b</sup>\n* [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]\n* [[Julian Huxley]]<ref name=\"WWF history\"/>\n* [[Edward Max Nicholson|Max Nicholson]]\n* [[Peter Scott]]\n* [[Guy Mountfort]]\n* [[Godfrey A. Rockefeller]]<ref name=\"WWF\"/>\n}}\n| type = [[Charitable trust]]\n| tax_id = <!-- or | vat_id = (for non-profit org) -->\n| registration_id = <!-- for non-profit org -->\n| status = \n| purpose = {{plainlist|\n* [[Environmentalism]]\n* [[Conservation (ethic)|Conservation]]\n* [[Ecology]]\n}}\n| headquarters = Rue Mauverny,<br />[[Gland, Switzerland|Gland]], [[Vaud]], [[Switzerland]]\n| location = \n| region = [[World]]wildlife\n| methods = {{hlist|Lobbying |research |consultancy}}\n| fields = \n| membership = \n| membership_year = \n| language = \n| leader_title = President\n| leader_name = [[Pavan Sukhdev]]\n| leader_title2 = President Emeritus\n| leader_name2 = [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]\n| leader_title3 = Director General\n| leader_name3 = Marco Lambertini\n| main_organ = \n| parent_organization = \n| subsidiaries = \n| secessions = \n| affiliations = \n| budget = \n| budget_year = \n| revenue = [[Euro|\u20ac]] 654 million (2013)\n| revenue_year = <!-- 2010<ref name=\"WWF-INT Annual Review\"/> -->\n| disbursements = \n| expenses = \n| expenses_year| endowment = \n| staff = \n| staff_year = \n| volunteers = \n| volunteers_year = \n| \nmission = \n| website ={{url|https://wwf.panda.org/}}<br />{{url|https://www.worldwildlife.org/}}\n| remarks = \n| footnotes = <div class=\"wraplinks\" style=\"font-size:90%; margin-left:0.65em; text-align:left; line-height:1.3em\">\n<sup>a</sup> First office opened 11 September 1961 in [[Morges, Switzerland|Morges]],<br />{{nbsp|3}}Switzerland.<br />\n<sup>b</sup> Also the WWF's first president.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldwildlife.org/who/History/item353.html |title=WWF - Who We Are - History |publisher=Worldwildlife.org |date= |accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref>\n</div>\n}}\n\nThe '''World Wide Fund for Nature''' ('''WWF''') is an [[Internationalism (politics)|international]] [[non-governmental organization]] founded in 1961, working in the field of wilderness preservation, and the reduction of [[human impact on the environment]].<ref name=\":0\" /> It was formerly named the '''World Wildlife Fund''', which remains its official name in [[Canada]] and the [[United States]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nWWF is the world's largest [[environmental organization|conservation organization]] with over five million supporters worldwide, working in more than 100 countries, supporting around 3000 conservation and environmental projects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panda.org/about_wwf/where_we_work/project/|title=WWF conservation projects around the world|publisher=}}</ref>  They have invested over $1 billion in more than 12,000 conservation initiatives since 1995.<ref name=\"WorldWildLife\">{{cite web|title=WWF - Endangered Species Conservation|url=https://www.worldwildlife.org|website=World Wildlife Fund|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> WWF is a [[Foundation (nonprofit)|foundation]] with 55% of funding from individuals and bequests, 19% from government sources (such as the [[World Bank]], [[Department for International Development|DFID]], [[United States Agency for International Development|USAID]]) and 8% from corporations in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/who_we_are/organization/|title=How is WWF run?|accessdate=21 July 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"WWF-INT Annual Review\">{{cite book |title = WWFN-International Annual Review|year = 2014|publisher = World Wide Fund for Nature|url = http://d2ouvy59p0dg6k.cloudfront.net/downloads/ar2014_v13_final_lr_sp.pdf|accessdate = 17 September 2015|page = 37}}</ref>\n\nWWF aims to \"stop the degradation of the planet's natural environment and to build a future in which humans live in harmony with nature.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wwf.panda.org/mission_principles_goals.cfm |title=WWF's Mission, Guiding Principles and Goals |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=<!--Not stated--> |website=WWF |access-date=2019-01-13 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113210818/https://wwf.panda.org/mission_principles_goals.cfm| archive-date=2019-01-13}}</ref> The [[Living Planet Report]] has been published every two years by WWF since 1998; it is based on a [[Living Planet Index]] and [[ecological footprint]] calculation.<ref name=\":0\" /> In addition, WWF has launched several notable worldwide campaigns including [[Earth Hour]] and [[Debt-for-Nature Swap]], and its current work is organized around these six areas: food, climate, freshwater, wildlife, forests, and oceans.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"WorldWildLife\" />\n\nWWF has received criticism for its alleged corporate ties.<ref name = \"Corp1\"/><ref name = \"Corp2\"/> It has also been accused of supporting paramilitary groups tasked with stopping poaching who are responsible for numerous human rights abuses.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/tomwarren/wwf-world-wide-fund-nature-parks-torture-death |title= WWF Funds Guards Who Have Tortured And Killed People|last= |first= |date= |website= [[BuzzFeed News]] |publisher= [[BuzzFeed]] |access-date= 24 March 2020 |quote=}}</ref><ref name = \"SI abuse\"/>{{coi-source|sure=yes|date=April 2020}}\n\n== History ==\n=== Precursor: the Conservation Foundation ===\n'''The Conservation Foundation''', a precursor to WWF, was founded in 1948 by [[Henry Fairfield Osborn, Jr.|Fairfield Osborn]] as an affiliate of the New York Zoological Society (today known as the [[Wildlife Conservation Society]]) with an aim of protecting the world's natural resources. The advisory council included leading scientists such as [[Charles Sutherland Elton]], [[G. Evelyn Hutchinson]], [[Aldo Leopold]], [[Carl Sauer]], and [[Paul Sears]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=97juQSbKZhQC&pg=RA1-PT280|page=280|title=Conservation and Environmentalism: An Encyclopedia|last=Paehlke|first=Robert C|author-link=Robert C. Paehlke|date=2013|publisher=Routledge}}</ref> It supported much of the scientific work cited by [[Rachel Carson]]'s ''[[Silent Spring]]'', including that of John L. George, Roger Hale, Robert Rudd, and [[George Woodwell]].\n\n=== Founding: Morges Manifesto ===\n{{Third-party|date=July 2019}}\n{{Multiple image\n| align = \n| direction = vertical\n| width = 278\n| image1 = Ora della Terra Verona Piazza Bra Arena 2013 WWF Verona Paolo Villa 9886.JPG\n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Ora della Terra Verona Piazza Bra Arena 2013 WWF Verona Paolo Villa 9954.JPG\n| caption2 = \n| footer = [[Earth Hour]] 2013 at the [[Verona Arena]] amphitheatre, [[Piazza Bra]], [[Verona]], Italy before (top) and while the street lighting was switched off.\n}}The idea for a fund on behalf of endangered animals was officially proposed by [[Victor Stolan]] to [[Julian Huxley|Sir Julian Huxley]] in response to articles he published in the British newspaper ''[[The Observer]]''. This proposal led Huxley to put Stolan in contact with [[Max Nicholson]], a person who had had thirty years experience of linking [[progressivism|progressive]] intellectuals with [[big business]] interests through the [[Political and Economic Planning]] [[think tank]].<ref name=\"WWF history\">{{cite web |url=http://wwf.panda.org/who_we_are/history/sixties/ |title=WWF in the 60s |publisher=World Wildlife Fund for Nature |date= |accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Kellaway\">Kate Kellaway (7 November 2010). [https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2010/nov/07/wwf-world-wildlife-fund-huxley How the Observer brought the WWF into being] [[The Observer]].</ref><ref>Scott, P. (1965). The launching of a new ark: first report of the President and Trustees of the World Wildlife Fund, an international foundation for saving the world's wildlife and wild places; 1962-1965 (Collins).</ref> Nicholson thought up the name of the organization. WWF was conceived on 29 April 1961, under the name of ''World Wildlife Fund'', and its first office was opened on 11 September that same year in [[Morges]], Switzerland.\n\nThe WWF was conceived to act as a funding institution for existing conservation groups such as the [[International Union for the Conservation of Nature|International Union for the Conservation of Nature and Natural Resources]] and The Conservation Foundation.<ref name=\"wwfhistory\">{{cite web|url=https://www.worldwildlife.org/about/history|title=History - WWF|website=World Wildlife Fund}}</ref> [[Godfrey A. Rockefeller]] also played an important role in its creation, assembling the first staff.<ref name=\"WWF\">[http://www.worldwildlife.org/who/media/press/2010/WWFPresitem15151.html In Memoriam: Godfrey A. Rockefeller], [[World Wildlife Fund]], 29 January 2010.</ref> Its establishment was marked with the signing of the \"Morges Manifesto\", the founding document that sets out the fund's commitment to assisting worthy organizations struggling to save the world's wildlife:<ref>\"[http://wwf.panda.org/who_we_are/history/ History: Fifty Years of Environmental Conservation]\". With link to [http://assets.panda.org/downloads/morgesmanifesto.pdf PDF] of \"Morges Manisto\". World Wildlife Fund for Nature. wwf.panda.org. Retrieved 20 June 2017.</ref>\n\n{{quote|They need above all money, to carry out mercy missions and to meet conservation emergencies by buying land where wildlife treasures are threatened, and in many other ways. Money, for example, to pay guardians of wildlife refuges&nbsp;.... Money for education and propaganda among those who would care and help if only they understood. Money to send out experts to danger spots and to train more local wardens and helpers in Africa and elsewhere. Money to maintain a sort of 'war room' at the international headquarters of conservation, showing where the danger spots are and making it possible to ensure that their needs are met before it is too late.|source=Morges Manifesto}}Dutch [[Prince Bernhard of Lippe-Biesterfeld]] helped found the World Wildlife Fund, becoming its first President in 1961. In 1963, the Foundation held a conference and published a major report warning of [[Human impact on the environment|anthropogenic]] [[global warming]], written by Noel Eichhorn based on the work of [[Frank Fraser Darling]] (then foundation vice president), [[Edward Deevey]], Erik Eriksson, [[Charles Keeling]], [[Gilbert Plass]], Lionel Walford, and [[William Garnett (photographer)|William Garnett]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001495147|title=Implications of Rising Carbon Dioxide Content of the Atmosphere: A statement of trends and implications of carbon dioxide research reviewed at a conference of scientists|last=Eichhorn|first=Noel|date=1963|publisher=The Conservation Foundation|place=New York}}</ref>\n\nIn 1970, along with [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Duke of Edinburgh]] and a few associates, [[Prince Bernhard of Lippe-Biesterfeld|Prince Bernhard]] established the WWF's [[financial endowment]] ''[[The 1001: A Nature Trust]]'' to handle the WWF's administration and fund-raising. 1001 members each contributed $10,000 to the trust.<ref name=\"WWF Finland\">{{in lang|en}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20100715155311/http://www.wwf.fi/english/international/history WWF Finland - History of WWF International]</ref> Prince Bernhard resigned his post after being involved in the [[Lockheed Bribery Scandal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1478171/HRH-Prince-Bernhard-of-the-Netherlands.html|title=Obituary: HRH Prince Bernhard of the Netherlands|date=4 December 2004|publisher=The Telegraph|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081108050115/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1478171/HRH-Prince-Bernhard-of-the-Netherlands.html|archivedate=8 November 2008|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Recent development ===\n{{Third-party|date=July 2019}}\n\nThe WWF has set up offices and operations around the world. It originally worked by fundraising and providing grants to existing non-governmental organizations with an initial focus on the protection of [[endangered species]]. As more resources became available, its operations expanded into other areas such as the preservation of [[Extinction|biological diversity]], sustainable use of [[natural resources]], the reduction of [[pollution]], and [[climate change]]. The organization also began to run its own conservation projects and campaigns.{{Citation_needed|date=July 2019}}[[File:WWF Big Ballon 2013.jpg|thumb|A WWF hot air balloon in Mexico (2013).|alt=]]In 1986, the organization changed its name to ''World Wide Fund for Nature'', while retaining the WWF initials. However, it continued at that time to operate under the original name in the United States and Canada.<ref name=\"history-eighties\">{{cite web |url=https://wwf.panda.org/knowledge_hub/history/eighties/ |title=WWF in the 80's |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=<!--Not stated--> |website=WWF |access-date=2019-01-13 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113210304/https://wwf.panda.org/knowledge_hub/history/eighties/| archive-date=2019-01-13}}</ref>\n\n1986 was the 25th anniversary of WWF's foundation, an event marked by a gathering in Assisi, Italy to which the organization's International President Prince Philip, the Duke of Edinburgh, invited religious authorities representing Buddhism, Christianity, Hinduism, Islam and Judaism. These leaders produced The Assisi Declarations, theological statements showing the spiritual relationship between their followers and nature that triggered a growth in the engagement of those religions with conservation around the world.<ref name=\"history-eighties\" />\n\nIn the 1990s, WWF revised its mission statement to:\n\n{{quote|Stop the degradation of the planet's natural environment and to build a future in which humans live in harmony with nature, by:\n* conserving the world's biological diversity;\n* ensuring that the use of renewable natural resources is sustainable; [and]\n* promoting the reduction of pollution and wasteful consumption.}}{{Citation_needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nWWF scientists and many others identified 238 [[ecoregions]] that represent the world's most biologically outstanding [[earth|terrestrial]], [[freshwater]] and [[oceans|marine]] habitats, based on a worldwide biodiversity analysis which the organization says was the first of its kind.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panda.org/about_our_earth/ecoregions/about/ |title=About global ecoregions |publisher=World Wide Fund for Nature |date= |accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref> In the early 2000s (decade), its work was focused on a subset of these ecoregions, in the areas of forest, freshwater and marine [[habitat conservation]], endangered species conservation, climate change, and the elimination of the most toxic chemicals.\n\n{{quote|We shan't save all we should like to, but we shall save a great deal more than if we had never tried.|Sir [[Peter Scott]]<ref name=\"WWF Finland\"/>}}\n\nIn 1990, the Conservation Foundation was completely merged into WWF, after becoming an affiliate of WWF-US in 1985 when it became a distinct legal entity but with the same staff and board.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwildlife.org/about/history|title=History {{!}} WWF|website=World Wildlife Fund|language=en|access-date=2019-01-22}}</ref> The organization now known as the Conservation Foundation in the United States is the former Forest Foundation of DuPage County.<ref name=\"wwfhistory\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://theconservationfoundation.org/page.php?PageID=2|title=The Conservation Foundation|website=theconservationfoundation.org}}</ref> In 1996, the organization obtained general [[consultative status]] from [[UNESCO]].{{Citation_needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n== Panda symbol ==\n{{Third-party|date=July 2019}}\n[[File:Grosser Panda.JPG|thumb|The giant panda has become the symbol of WWF.|alt=|200x200px]]\n\nWWF's [[giant panda]] logo originated from a panda named [[Chi Chi (giant panda)|Chi Chi]] that had been transferred from [[Beijing Zoo]] to [[London Zoo]] in 1958, three years before WWF became established.  Being famous as the only panda residing in the Western world at that time, her uniquely recognisable physical features and status as an endangered species were seen as ideal to serve the organization's need for a strong recognisable symbol that would overcome all language barriers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/who_we_are/history/sixties/|title=WWF - WWF in the 60's|date=|publisher=WWF|accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref> The organization also needed an animal that would have an impact in black and white printing. The logo was then designed by [[Peter Scott (conservationist)|Sir Peter Scott]] from preliminary sketches by Gerald Watterson, a Scottish naturalist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/who_we_are/history/sixties/|title=WWF in the 60's|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldwildlife.org/species/finder/giantpanda/panda.html|title=WWF - Giant Panda - Overview|date=|publisher=Worldwildlife.org|accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe logo was slightly simplified and made more geometric in 1978, and was revised significantly again in 1986, at the time that the organization changed its name, with the new version featuring solid black shapes for eyes.<ref>\"[http://www.logodesignlove.com/world-wildlife-fund World Wildlife Fund logo sketches]\". Logo Design Love. 7 June 2011; updated by Jerry Kuyper, 9&nbsp;June2011. logodesignlove.com. Retrieved 21 June 2017.</ref> In 2000 a change was made to the font used for the initials \"WWF\" in the logo.<ref>\"[https://www.famouslogos.us/wwf-logo/ WWF Logo]\". Famous Logos. famouslogos.us. Retrieved 21 June 2017.</ref>\n\n== Organization and operation ==\n\n===Policy-making===\n{{Third-party|date=July 2019}}\nPolicies of the WWF are made by board members elected for three-year terms. An Executive Team guides and develops WWF's strategy. There is also a National Council which stands as an advisory group to the board and a team of scientists and experts in conservation who research for WWF.\n\nNational and international law plays an important role in determining how habitats and resources are managed and used. Laws and regulations become one of the organization's global priorities.\n\nThe WWF has been opposed to the extraction of oil from the Canadian [[tar sands]] and has campaigned on this matter. Between 2008 and 2010 the WWF worked with [[The Co-operative Group]], the [[UK]]'s largest [[consumer co-operative]] to publish reports which concluded that: (1) exploiting the Canadian tar sands to their full potential would be sufficient to bring about what they described as 'runaway climate change;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.co-operative.coop/upload/ToxicFuels/docs/WWF_CFS_Unconventionals_report.pdf|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150708080954/http://www.co-operative.coop/upload/ToxicFuels/docs/WWF_CFS_Unconventionals_report.pdf|archivedate=8 July 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref> (2) carbon capture and storage (CCS) technology cannot be used to reduce the release of carbon dioxide into the atmosphere to a level comparable to that of other methods of oil extraction;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.co-operative.coop/upload/ToxicFuels/docs/CCS-in-the-Alberta-oil-sands-a-dangerous-myth.pdf|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923205501/http://www.co-operative.coop/upload/ToxicFuels/docs/CCS-in-the-Alberta-oil-sands-a-dangerous-myth.pdf|archivedate=23 September 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref> (3) the $379 billion which is expected to be spent extracting oil from [[tar sands]] could be better spent on research and development in renewable energy technology;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.co-operative.coop/upload/ToxicFuels/docs/opportunity-cost-report.pdf|title=Opportunity cost of tar sands development|work=co-operative.coop|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906001129/https://www.co-operative.coop/upload/ToxicFuels/docs/opportunity-cost-report.pdf|archivedate=6 September 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=25 September 2018}}</ref> and (4) the expansion of tar sands extraction poses a serious threat to the caribou in Alberta .<ref>http://www.co-operative.coop/upload/ToxicFuels/docs/caribou-report.pdf</ref>\n\nThe organization convinces and helps governments and other political bodies to adopt, enforce, strengthen and/or change policies, guidelines and laws that affect biodiversity and natural resource use. It also ensures government consent and/or keeps their commitment to international instruments relating to the protection of biodiversity and natural resources.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/what_we_do/how_we_work/tackling_the_causes/|title=Tackling the Causes|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/what_we_do/how_we_work/policy/|title=Advocacy & policy|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, David Nussbaum, Chief Executive of WWF-UK, spoke out against the way [[shale gas]] is used in the UK, saying: \"...{{nbsp}}the Government must reaffirm its commitment to tackling climate change and prioritise renewables and energy efficiency.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.securingthefuture.co.uk/energy/12572-take-foot-off-the-pedal-on-shale-gas-charities-warn-government|title='Take foot off the pedal on shale gas', charities warn Government|last=Buckler|first=Scott|website=www.securingthefuture.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n=== Collaboration ===\n{{Third-party|date=July 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=July 2019}}\nWWF's strategy for achieving its mission specifically concentrates on restoring populations of 36 [[species]] (species or species groups that are important for their [[ecosystem]] or to people, including [[elephant]]s, [[tuna]]s, [[Cetacea|whales, dolphins and porpoises]]), and [[ecological footprint]] in 6 areas (carbon emissions, cropland, grazing land, fishing, forestry and water).{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nThe organization also works on a number of [[global issue]]s driving [[biodiversity loss]] and unsustainable use of natural resources, including finance, business practices, laws, and consumption choices. Local offices also work on national or regional issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panda.org/what_we_do/|title=What does the World Wild Life Fund do?|date=|publisher=World Wide Fund for Nature|accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nWWF works with a large number of different groups to achieve its goals, including other NGOs, governments, business, investment banks, scientists, fishermen, farmers and local communities. It also undertakes public campaigns to influence decision makers, and seeks to educate people on how to live in a more environmentally friendly manner. It urges people to donate funds to protect the environment. The donors can also choose to receive gifts in return.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\n=== List of presidents ===\n[[File:Yolanda Kakabadse 2.jpg|thumb|Yolanda Kakabadse, WWF president from 2010 to 2017]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"\n! Years<ref name=\"presidents\">[http://wwf.panda.org/who_we_are/organization/presidents/ Presidents - past and present], official website of the World Wide Fund for Nature (page visited on 4 March 2018).</ref>\n! Name<ref name=\"presidents\" />\n|-\n|&nbsp; 1961\u20131976 ||[[Prince Bernhard of Lippe-Biesterfeld]]\n|-\n|&nbsp; 1976\u20131981 ||[[John Hugo Loudon]]\n|-\n|&nbsp; 1981\u20131996 ||[[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]\n|-\n|&nbsp; 1996\u20131999 ||[[Syed Babar Ali]]\n|-\n|&nbsp; {{0|2000\u2013}}2000 ||[[Ruud Lubbers]]\n|-\n|&nbsp; 2000\u20132001 ||[[Sara Morrison]]\n|-\n|&nbsp; 2001\u20132010 ||[[Emeka Anyaoku|Chief Emeka Anyaoku]]\n|-\n|&nbsp; 2010\u20132017 ||[[Yolanda Kakabadse]]\n|-\n|&nbsp; 2018\u2013present&nbsp;|| [[Pavan Sukhdev]]\n|}\n\n== Notable initiatives and programs ==\n=== Campaigns ===\n\n*[[Debt-for-Nature Swap]]\n*[[Earth Hour]]\n*[[Healthy Grown]]\n*[[Marine Stewardship Council]]\n\n=== Global initiatives ===\n{{Third-party|date=July 2019}}\nSince 2008, through its Global Programme Framework (GPF), WWF has said it is concentrating its efforts on 13 global initiatives:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/what_we_do/how_we_work/key_initiatives/|title=Our Global Goals|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n*[[Amazon rainforest|Amazon]]\n* Arctic\n* China for a Global Shift\n* Climate and Energy\n* Coastal East Africa[[File:People's Climate March 2017 20170429 4331 (34351241115).jpg|thumb|[[People's Climate March (2017)|People's Climate March]] 2017|alt=]]\n* Coral Triangle\n* Forest and Climate\n* Green Heart of Africa\n* Heart of Borneo\n* Living Himalayas\n* Market Transformation\n* Smart Fishing\n* Tigers<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wwf.sg/business/asian_tigers_mobility_group.cfm|title=Asian Tigers Mobility Group {{!}} WWF|website=www.wwf.sg|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Publications ===\n\nWWF publishes the ''[[Living Planet Index]]'' in collaboration with the [[Zoological Society of London]]. Along with [[ecological footprint]] calculations, the ''Index'' is used to produce a bi-yearly ''[[Living Planet Report]]'' giving an overview of the impact of human activity on the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.panda.org/about_our_earth/all_publications/living_planet_report/ |title=Living Planet Report |publisher=World Wide Fund for Nature |date= |accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref> In 2019, WWF and [[Knorr (brand)|Knorr]] jointly published the [[Future 50 Foods report]] identifying \"50 Foods for Healthier People and a Healthier Planet\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/2019-02/Knorr_Future_50_Report_FINAL_Online.pdf|title=Future 50 Foods: 50 foods for healthier people and a healthier planet|last=Drewnowski|first=Adam|date=February 2019|website=World Wide Fund for Nature|access-date=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe organization also regularly publishes reports, fact sheets and other documents on issues related to its work, to raise awareness and provide information to policy and decision makers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panda.org/about_our_earth/all_publications/|title=Publication & Resources|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== Promotions ===\n\n* ''[[No One's Gonna Change Our World]]'' was a charity album released in 1969, for the benefit of the WWF.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/story-of-the-song-across-the-universe-by-the-beatles-in-1968-and-beady-eye-in-2011-2265187.html|title=Story of the Song: Across the Universe by The Beatles in 1968 and|date=2011-04-08|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n* [[Peter Rose and Anne Conlon]] are music theatre writers, well known for their environmental musicals for children, who were commissioned by WWF-UK to write several environmental musicals as part of an education plan.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/version/191183717|title=Yanomamo : an ecological musical for soloists, chorus, narrator & stage band|last=Rose|first=Peter|last2=Conlon|first2=Anne|last3=Dept|first3=World Wide Fund for Nature UK Education|date=1993|publisher=London : Josef Weinberger in association with the World Wide Fund for Nature|language=English}}</ref> Some were narrated by [[David Attenborough]], and broadcast on television in numerous countries.\n* The British pop group [[S Club|S Club 7]] were ambassadors for WWF-UK during their time together as a band (1999-2003).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GoaBAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT35&lpg=PT35&dq=S+Club+7+world+wide+fund&source=bl&ots=m4is-VhXgX&sig=ACfU3U1fEYOqljyCeR_nF0aODi1Q4IlJBA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj2sIKjrezgAhVJ04MKHcAvD9wQ6AEwD3oECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=S%20Club%207%20world%20wide%20fund&f=false|title=S Club 7|last=Golden|first=Anna Louise|date=2014-06-17|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=9781466873940|language=en}}</ref> Each of the members sponsored an endangered animal, and in 2000, traveled to the various locations around the world of their chosen animals for a seven-part [[BBC]] documentary series entitled ''[[S Club 7 Go Wild!|S Club 7 Go Wild]]''.\n* ''Environmentally Sound: A Select Anthology of Songs Inspired by the Earth'' is a benefit album released in 2006, for WWF-Philippines, featuring artists that included [[Up Dharma Down]], [[Radioactive Sago Project]], [[Kala (band)|Kala]], [[Cynthia Alexander]], and [[Joey Ayala]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwf.org.ph/newsfacts.php?pg=det&id=25|title=The Harmonics of being Environmentally Sound|date=18 August 2006|publisher=[[World Wildlife Fund]] - Philippines|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720233747/http://www.wwf.org.ph/newsfacts.php?pg=det&id=25|archivedate=20 July 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=30 June 2010}}</ref>\n* In June 2012, WWF launched an online [[music download]] store with [[fairsharemusic]] from which 50% of the profit goes to the charity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nonprofitquarterly.org/2010/06/22/nonprofit-newswire-british-website-connects-music-lovers-and-charities/|title=Nonprofit Newswire {{!}} British Website Connects Music Lovers and Charities|last=Trachtenberg|first=Bruce S.|date=2010-06-22|website=Non Profit News {{!}} Nonprofit Quarterly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n* In April 2015, [[Hailey Gardiner]] released her solo EP, titled The Woods. In honor of [[Earth Day]], 15% of the proceeds made towards the purchase of the EP would be donated to the WWF.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gardinersisters.com/blog/rdinersisters.com/2015/04/the-woods.html|title=The Woods|website=Gardiner Sisters|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies and disputes ==\n\n=== ARD documentary and \"PandaLeaks\" book ===\nThe German public television [[ARD (broadcaster)|ARD]] aired a documentary on 22 June 2011 that claimed to show how the WWF cooperates with corporations such as [[Monsanto]], providing sustainability certification in exchange for donations{{nbsp}}\u2013 essentially [[greenwashing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ardmediathek.de/ard/servlet/content/3517136?documentId=7495082|title=''Der Pakt mit dem Panda: Was uns der WWF verschweigt'' (Pact with the Panda: What the WWF conceals)|date=22 June 2011|work=DasErste.de|publisher=tagesschau.de ARD|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728032810/http://www.ardmediathek.de/ard/servlet/content/3517136?documentId=7495082|archive-date=28 July 2011|accessdate=25 July 2011}} See also: [http://programm.ard.de/TV/Programm/Sender/?sendung=281117723794509 program overview for rebroadcast], 2 April 2012, programm.ARD.de, noting the objections raised by WWF supporters after the initial broadcast, and retracting two claims made in the film; retrieved 16 July 2017.</ref> WWF has denied the allegations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwf.de/themen/huismann-kritik-pakt-mit-dem-panda-faktencheck|title=WWF-Mitarbeiter treffen Chief Kasimirus Sangara|last=WWF|accessdate=9 July 2011}}</ref> By encouraging high-impact eco-tourism, the program alleges that WWF contributes to the destruction of habitat and species it claims to protect while also harming indigenous peoples.<ref>{{cite thesis |last= Harryman|first= Ian|date= Spring 2016|title= Ecological Problem Solving: A Comparative Study of Primate Conservation|type= Undergraduate Honors|publisher= University of Colorado, Boulder|url= https://scholar.colorado.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2266&context=honr_theses|access-date=15 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe filmmaker, [[:de:Wilfried Huismann|Wilfried Huismann]], was sued by the WWF over his documentary and the book \"Schwarzbuch WWF\" published in 2012, which was based on the documentary. In an out of court settlement, he agreed to remove or revise certain claims. Speaking on behalf of WWF Germany, Marco Vollmar indicated \"[Huismann] draws a distorted picture of false statements, defamations and exaggerations, but we will accept that as expressions of opinion.\" (Translated from the original German: \"ein Zerrbild aus falschen Aussagen, Diffamierungen und \u00dcbertreibungen, aber das werden wir als Meinungs\u00e4u\u00dferungen hinnehmen.\")<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spiegel.de/kultur/literatur/schwarzbuch-wwf-einigung-zwischen-wwf-und-huismann-steht-bevor-a-844243.html |title=environmental organization and critics before agreement|last=Seidler |first=Christoph |date=20 July 2012 |website=www.spiegel.de |publisher=Spiegel Online|access-date=15 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, German investigative journalist [[:de:Wilfried Huismann|Wilfried Huismann]] published a revised edition of his 2012 book, originally called ''The Silence of the Pandas''. The original edition had become a bestseller in Germany, but was banned from Britain until 2014, when it was released under the title of ''PandaLeaks - The Dark Side of the WWF'', after a series of injunctions and court orders.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2014/oct/04/wwf-international-selling-its-soul-corporations|title=WWF International accused of 'selling its soul' to corporations|last=Vidal|first=John|date=4 October 2014|work=The Guardian}}</ref> The book criticizes WWF for its supposed involvement with corporations that are responsible for large-scale destruction of the environment, such as Coca-Cola, and gives details into the existence of the secret [[1001 Club]], whose members, Huismann claims, continue to have an unhealthy influence on WWF's policy making.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\" /> WWF has denied the allegations made against it.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wwf.panda.org/wwf_news/press_releases/a_quick_guide_to_the_silence_of_the_pandas_documentary.cfm|title=A quick guide to the silence of the pandas documentary|publisher=WWF}}</ref>\n\n=== Corporate partnerships ===\nWWF has been accused by the campaigner [[Corporate Watch]] of being too close to business to campaign objectively.<ref name= \"Corp1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.corporatewatch.org/?lid=1873 |title=PANDA-ING TO THE SOYA BARONS? |author= |date=30 September 2009 |work= |publisher=Corporate Watch |accessdate=9 December 2009}}</ref><ref name= \"Corp2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/2009/apr/02/greenwash-ikea-diy-earth-hour |title=Ikea \u2013 you can't build a green reputation with a flatpack DIY manual |author=Fred Pearce |date=2 April 2009 |work= |publisher=Guardian UK |accessdate=9 December 2009 |location=London}}</ref> WWF claims partnering with corporations such as [[Coca-Cola]], [[Lafarge (company)|Lafarge]], [[Carlos Slim]]'s and [[IKEA]] will reduce their effect on the environment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panda.org/what_we_do/how_we_work/businesses/ |title=Changing the nature of business |publisher=World Wide Fund for Nature|date= |accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref>  WWF received \u20ac56 million (US$80 million) from corporations in 2010 (an 8% increase in support from corporations compared to 2009), accounting for 11% of total revenue for the year.<ref name=\"WWF-INT Annual Review\"/>\n\nFor their 2019 fiscal year, WWF reported 4% of their total operating revenue coming from corporations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwildlife.org/about/financials|title=Funding and Financial Overview {{!}} WWF|website=World Wildlife Fund|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Human rights abuses by paramilitaries ===\nIn 2017, a report by [[Survival International]] claimed that WWF-funded [[paramilitaries]] are not only committing abuses against the indigenous Baka and Bayaka in the Congo Basin, who \"face harassment and beatings, torture and death\", but are also corrupt and aid in the destruction of conserved areas. The report accused the WWF and its guards of partnering with several logging companies who carried out deforestation, while the rangers ignored wildlife trafficking networks.<ref name = \"SI abuse\">{{Cite web |url=https://assets.survivalinternational.org/documents/1683/how-will-we-survive.pdf|title=How will we survive? |year=2017 |website=[[Survival International]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, an investigation by ''[[BuzzFeed News]]'' alleged that paramilitary groups funded by the organisation are engaged in serious human rights abuses against villagers, and the organisation has covered up the incidents and acted to protect the perpetrators from law enforcement. These armed groups were claimed to torture, sexually assault, and execute villagers based on false accusations. In one instance found by ''BuzzFeed News'' investigators, an 11-year-old boy was allegedly tortured by WWF-funded rangers in front of his parents;<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/tomwarren/wwf-world-wide-fund-nature-parks-torture-death|title=WWF Funds Guards Who Have Tortured And Killed People |last=Warren|first=Tom |last2=Baker |first2=Katie J. M. |date=4 March 2019 |website=www.buzzfeednews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> the WWF ignored all complaints against the rangers. In another incident, a ranger attempted to rape a Tharu woman and, when she resisted, attacked her with bamboo stick until she lost consciousness. While the ranger was arrested, the woman was pressured not to press charges, resulting in the ranger going free. In 2010, WWF-sponsored rangers reportedly killed a 12-year-old girl who was collecting tree bark in [[Bardiya National Park]]. Park and WWF officials allegedly obstructed investigations in these cases, by \"falsifying and destroying evidence, falsely claiming the victims were poachers, and pressuring the families of the victims to withdraw criminal complaints\".<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2019/mar/04/wwf-accused-of-funding-guards-who-allegedly-tortured-killed-scores-of-people|title=WWF accused of funding guards who 'tortured and killed scores of people'|last=McVeigh|first=Karen|date=2019-03-04|website=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> In July 2019 Buzzfeed reported that a leaked report by the WWF accused guards of beating and raping women including pregnant women while torturing men by tying their penises with fishing lines. The investigations were cut short after paramilitary groups threatened investigators with death. The investigators accused WWF of covering up the crimes. Releasing an official statement, the WWF claimed that the report was not made public to ensure the safety of the victims and that the guards were suspended and are awaiting prosecution. However Buzzfeed accused the WWF of attempting to withhold the report to the US congressional committee investigating the human rights violations by providing high redacted versions instead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/tomwarren/leaked-report-wwf-backed-guards-raped-pregnant-women|title=Leaked Report: WWF-Backed Guards Raped Pregnant Women And Tortured Villagers At A Wildlife Park Funded By The US Government|website=BuzzFeed News|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/?349754|title=Statement on safeguarding human rights in conservation, and addressing allegations of human rights abuse {{!}} WWF|website=wwf.panda.org|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Central African Republic]], WWF officials were reportedly involved in an arms deal, where the organization paid for 15 AK assault rifles and ammunition; but part of the money went unaccounted and apparently defrauded by the CAR army representatives selling the weapons.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'', which cooperated with ''BuzzFeed News'' on the investigations in [[Nepal]], claimed there was intense lobbying and political pressure to release WWF-funded rangers arrested for murder. They interviewed activists who claimed they were promised donations for pressuring victims of abuse to drop charges against the rangers. When the local [[Tharu people|Tharu]] community protested, WWF officials carried out a counter-protest in favour of the accused and used park elephants to block [[Prithvi Highway]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2019-03-03/nepals-park-officials-who-beat-and-tortured-a-man-were-rewarded-by-the-government-and-the-world-wide-fund-for-nature.html|title=Nepali park officials tortured a man to death. Then, the government and the World Wide Fund for Nature rewarded them. |date=3 March 2019 |website=Kathmandu Post |language=English|access-date=2019-03-05}}</ref>\n\nAn investigation by [[Rainforest Foundation UK]] found evidence of widespread physical and sexual assault by \u2018eco-guards\u2019  employed by the [[Salonga National Park]] in the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]] funded by the WWF.  These include two cases of gang rape, two extrajudicial killings, and multiple accounts of torture and other forms of mistreatment committed by park guards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rainforestfoundationuk.org/widespread-human-rights-abuses-in-africas-largest-forest-park |title=Widespread human rights abuses in Africa\u2019s largest forest park |date=4 March 2019 |website=Rainforest Foundation UK |language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref>\n\nIn reply to the investigations, the WWF stated that it takes any allegations seriously and would be launching an independent review into the cases raised. The organisation stated it has stringent policies designed to ensure it and its partners are safeguarding the rights and well-being of indigenous peoples and local communities, and should the review uncover any breaches, it is committed to taking swift action.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/wwf_news/press_releases/?343750/WWF-Response-to-BuzzFeed-allegations|title=WWF response to Buzzfeed reports |date=4 March 2019 |website=wwf.panda.org|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Initialism dispute ===\n{{see also|WWE#Legal disputes and controversies}}\n\nIn 2000, the World Wide Fund for Nature sued the [[World Wrestling Federation]] (now named [[WWE]]) for unfair trade practices. Both parties had shared the initials \"WWF\" since 1979. The conservation organization claimed that the [[professional wrestling]] company had violated a 1994 agreement regarding international use of the WWF initials.<ref>[http://www.internetnews.com/bus-news/article.php/3_1038611 InternetNews Realtime IT News \u2013 Wildlife Fund Pins Wrestling Federation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061114234625/http://www.internetnews.com/bus-news/article.php/3_1038611|date=14 November 2006}}</ref><ref>[http://contracts.corporate.findlaw.com/agreements/wwf/worldwildlife.1997.01.20.html Text of the 1994 legal agreement with the World Wrestling Federation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013110155/http://contracts.corporate.findlaw.com/agreements/wwf/worldwildlife.1997.01.20.html|date=13 October 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 August 2001, a UK court ruled in favour of the World Wide Fund for Nature. The World Wrestling Federation filed an appeal in October 2001. However, on 10 May 2002, the World Wrestling Federation changed its [[Web address]] from ''WWF.com'' to ''WWE.com'', and replaced every \"WWF\" reference on the existing site with \"WWE\", as a prelude to changing the company's name to \"World Wrestling Entertainment.\" Its stock ticker also switched from WWF to WWE.\n\nThe wrestling organization's abandonment of the \"WWF\" [[initialism]] did not end the two organizations' legal conflict. Later in 2002, the World Wide Fund for Nature petitioned the court for $360 million in damages, but was not successful. A subsequent request to overturn by the World Wide Fund for Nature was dismissed by the British [[Court of Appeal of England and Wales|Court of Appeal]] on 28 June 2007. In 2003, World Wrestling Entertainment won a limited decision which permitted them to continue marketing certain pre-existing products with the abandoned WWF logo. However, WWE was mandated to issue newly branded merchandise such as apparel, action figures, video games, and [[DVD]]s with the \"WWE\" initials. Additionally, the court order required the company to remove both auditory and visual references to \"WWF\" in its library of video footage outside the United Kingdom.\n\nStarting with the 1,000th episode of ''Raw'' in July 2012, the WWF \"scratch\" logo is no longer censored in archival footage. In addition, the WWF initials are no longer censored when spoken or when written in plain text in archival footage.  In exchange, WWE is no longer permitted to use the WWF initials or logo in any new, original footage, packaging, or advertising, with any old-school logos for retro-themed programming now using a modification of the original WWF logo without the F.\n\n=== Mekong River dolphins report ===\nIn June 2009, Touch Seang Tana, chairman of [[Cambodia]]'s Commission for Conservation and Development of the [[Mekong River]] Dolphins Eco-tourism Zone, argued that the WWF had misrepresented the danger of extinction of the [[Irrawaddy dolphin|Mekong dolphin]] to boost fundraising.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.cri.cn/6966/2009/06/24/2001s496246.htm |title=Cambodia Rejects CNN, WWF Reports about Mekong Dolphin |publisher=CRIEnglish.com |date=24 June 2009 |accessdate=2 March 2013}}</ref> The report stated that the deaths were caused by a bacterial disease that became fatal due to environmental contaminants suppressing the dolphins' immune systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/wwf_news/?167401/Mekong-dolphins-on-the-brink-of-extinction|title=Mekong dolphins on the brink of extinction|access-date=21 September 2016}}</ref> He called the report unscientific and harmful to the Cambodian government and threatened the WWF's Cambodian branch with suspension unless they met with him to discuss his claims.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://khmerization.blogspot.com/2009/06/cambodia-threatens-to-suspend-wwf-after.html |title=Cambodia threatens to suspend WWF after dolphin report |accessdate=2 August 2017}}</ref> Touch Seang Tana later said he would not press charges of supplying false information and would not make any attempt to prevent WWF from continuing its work in Cambodia, but advised WWF to adequately explain its findings and check with the commission before publishing another report. After this, in January 2012, Touch Seang Tana signed the \"Kratie Declaration on the Conservation of the Mekong River Irrawaddy Dolphin\" along with WWF and the Cambodian Fisheries Administration, an agreement binding the parties to work together on a \"roadmap\" addressing dolphin conservation in the Mekong River.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phnompenhpost.com/national/authors-report-dolphins-will-not-face-charges-official-says|title=Authors of report on dolphins will not face charges official says|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=|accessdate=22 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Centres of Plant Diversity]]\n* [[Conservation movement]]\n* [[Environmental Dispute Resolution Fund]]\n* [[Environmental movement]]\n* [[Eugene Green Energy Standard]], founded by the WWF.\n* [[Global 200]], ecoregions identified by the WWF as priorities for conservation\n* [[List of environmental organizations]]\n* [[Natural environment]]\n* [[Sustainability]]\n* [[Sustainable development]]\n* [[Traffic (conservation programme)]], a joint programme of WWF and the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature|International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN)]]\n* [[West Coast Environmental Law]]\n* [[World Conservation Award]], created in conjunction with the WWF\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|World Wide Fund For Nature|<br />WWF<br />(World Wide Fund For Nature)}}\n\n* {{official website|https://panda.org/|Panda.org}} (WWF International website)\n* [http://www.worldwildlife.org World Wildlife Fund], WWF-US Website.\n* {{YouTube|user=wwf|WWF}}.\n* [http://www.wwf.org/ WWF's global network]\n** {{hlist |[http://www.wwf.org.uk/ WWF-UK] |{{EW charity|1081247|WWF - UK}}}}\n** [http://scotland.wwf.org.uk/ WWF Scotland]\n** [http://armenia.panda.org/ WWF Armenia]\n** [http://www.wwfpak.org/  WWF-Pakistan]\n** [http://www.wwfindia.org/index.cfm WWF-India]\n** [http://www.wwfguianas.org/ WWF Guianas]\n** [http://www.wwf.ru/eng WWF Russia]\n\n{{WWFN}}\n{{Prince of Asturias Award for Concord}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Environment|Ecology|Earth sciences}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:World Wide Fund For Nature}}\n[[Category:World Wide Fund for Nature| ]]\n[[Category:International environmental organizations]]\n[[Category:Conservation organizations]]\n[[Category:Ecology organizations]]\n[[Category:Wildlife conservation organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations with general consultative status to the United Nations Economic and Social Council]]\n[[Category:Environmental organizations established in 1961]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1961]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organisations based in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organisations based in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:1961 establishments in Switzerland]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|International non-governmental organization}}\n{{distinguish|World Wrestling Federation}}\n{{Third-party|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use British English Oxford spelling|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{coord|46.4171864|6.2709482|display=title}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = World Wildlife Fund \n| image = WWF logo.svg\n| image_size = 125px\n| alt = WWF logo\n| map = \n| map_size = \n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = \n| map2 = \n| map2_size = \n| map2_alt = \n| map2_caption = \n| abbreviation = \n| motto = \n| formation = {{start date and age|df=yes|1961|04|29}}\u2009(as World Wildlife Fund)<sup>a</sup>\n| founders = {{plainlist|\n* [[Prince Bernhard of Lippe-Biesterfeld]]\u2009<sup>b</sup>\n* [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]\n* [[Julian Huxley]]<ref name=\"WWF history\"/>\n* [[Edward Max Nicholson|Max Nicholson]]\n* [[Peter Scott]]\n* [[Guy Mountfort]]\n* [[Godfrey A. Rockefeller]]<ref name=\"WWF\"/>\n}}\n| type = [[Charitable trust]]\n| tax_id = <!-- or | vat_id = (for non-profit org) -->\n| registration_id = <!-- for non-profit org -->\n| status = \n| purpose = {{plainlist|\n* [[Environmentalism]]\n* [[Conservation (ethic)|Conservation]]\n* [[Ecology]]\n}}\n| headquarters = Rue Mauverny,<br />[[Gland, Switzerland|Gland]], [[Vaud]], [[Switzerland]]\n| location = \n| region = [[World]]wildlife\n| methods = {{hlist|Lobbying |research |consultancy}}\n| fields = \n| membership = \n| membership_year = \n| language = \n| leader_title = President and CEO : Carter Roberts\n| leader_name = [[Carter Roberts]]<ref>https://https://www.worldwildlife.org/about/leadership/</ref>\n| leader_title2 = President Emeritus\n| leader_name2 = [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]\n| leader_title3 = Director General\n| leader_name3 = Marco Lambertini\n| main_organ = \n| parent_organization = \n| subsidiaries = \n| secessions = \n| affiliations = \n| budget = \n| budget_year = \n| revenue = [[Euro|\u20ac]] 654 million (2013)\n| revenue_year = <!-- 2010<ref name=\"WWF-INT Annual Review\"/> -->\n| disbursements = \n| expenses = \n| expenses_year| endowment = \n| staff = \n| staff_year = \n| volunteers = \nA| volunteers_year = \n| \nmission = \n| website ={{url|https://wwf.panda.org/}}<br />{{url|https://www.worldwildlife.org/}}\n| remarks = \n| footnotes = <div class=\"wraplinks\" style=\"font-size:90%; margin-left:0.65em; text-align:left; line-height:1.3em\">\n<sup>a</sup> First office opened 11 September 1961 in [[Morges, Switzerland|Morges]],<br />{{nbsp|3}}Switzerland.<br />\n<sup>b</sup> Also the WWF's first president.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldwildlife.org/who/History/item353.html |title=WWF - Who We Are - History |publisher=Worldwildlife.org |date= |accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref>\n</div>\n}}\n\nThe '''World Wide Fund for Nature''' ('''WWF''') is an [[Internationalism (politics)|international]] [[non-governmental organization]] founded in 1961, working in the field of wilderness preservation, and the reduction of [[human impact on the environment]].<ref name=\":0\" /> It was formerly named the '''World Wildlife Fund''', which remains its official name in [[Canada]] and the [[United States]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nWWF is the world's largest [[environmental organization|conservation organization]] with over five million supporters worldwide, working in more than 100 countries, supporting around 3000 conservation and environmental projects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panda.org/about_wwf/where_we_work/project/|title=WWF conservation projects around the world|publisher=}}</ref>  They have invested over $1 billion in more than 12,000 conservation initiatives since 1995.<ref name=\"WorldWildLife\">{{cite web|title=WWF - Endangered Species Conservation|url=https://www.worldwildlife.org|website=World Wildlife Fund|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> WWF is a [[Foundation (nonprofit)|foundation]] with 55% of funding from individuals and bequests, 19% from government sources (such as the [[World Bank]], [[Department for International Development|DFID]], [[United States Agency for International Development|USAID]]) and 8% from corporations in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/who_we_are/organization/|title=How is WWF run?|accessdate=21 July 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"WWF-INT Annual Review\">{{cite book |title = WWFN-International Annual Review|year = 2014|publisher = World Wide Fund for Nature|url = http://d2ouvy59p0dg6k.cloudfront.net/downloads/ar2014_v13_final_lr_sp.pdf|accessdate = 17 September 2015|page = 37}}</ref>\n\nWWF aims to \"stop the degradation of the planet's natural environment and to build a future in which humans live in harmony with nature.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wwf.panda.org/mission_principles_goals.cfm |title=WWF's Mission, Guiding Principles and Goals |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=<!--Not stated--> |website=WWF |access-date=2019-01-13 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113210818/https://wwf.panda.org/mission_principles_goals.cfm| archive-date=2019-01-13}}</ref> The [[Living Planet Report]] has been published every two years by WWF since 1998; it is based on a [[Living Planet Index]] and [[ecological footprint]] calculation.<ref name=\":0\" /> In addition, WWF has launched several notable worldwide campaigns including [[Earth Hour]] and [[Debt-for-Nature Swap]], and its current work is organized around these six areas: food, climate, freshwater, wildlife, forests, and oceans.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"WorldWildLife\" />\n\nWWF has received criticism for its alleged corporate ties.<ref name = \"Corp1\"/><ref name = \"Corp2\"/> It has also been accused of supporting paramilitary groups tasked with stopping poaching who are responsible for numerous human rights abuses.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/tomwarren/wwf-world-wide-fund-nature-parks-torture-death |title= WWF Funds Guards Who Have Tortured And Killed People|last= |first= |date= |website= [[BuzzFeed News]] |publisher= [[BuzzFeed]] |access-date= 24 March 2020 |quote=}}</ref><ref name = \"SI abuse\"/>{{coi-source|sure=yes|date=April 2020}}\n\n== History ==\n=== Precursor: the Conservation Foundation ===\n'''The Conservation Foundation''', a precursor to WWF, was founded in 1948 by [[Henry Fairfield Osborn, Jr.|Fairfield Osborn]] as an affiliate of the New York Zoological Society (today known as the [[Wildlife Conservation Society]]) with an aim of protecting the world's natural resources. The advisory council included leading scientists such as [[Charles Sutherland Elton]], [[G. Evelyn Hutchinson]], [[Aldo Leopold]], [[Carl Sauer]], and [[Paul Sears]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=97juQSbKZhQC&pg=RA1-PT280|page=280|title=Conservation and Environmentalism: An Encyclopedia|last=Paehlke|first=Robert C|author-link=Robert C. Paehlke|date=2013|publisher=Routledge}}</ref> It supported much of the scientific work cited by [[Rachel Carson]]'s ''[[Silent Spring]]'', including that of John L. George, Roger Hale, Robert Rudd, and [[George Woodwell]].\n\n=== Founding: Morges Manifesto ===\n{{Third-party|date=July 2019}}\n{{Multiple image\n| align = \n| direction = vertical\n| width = 278\n| image1 = Ora della Terra Verona Piazza Bra Arena 2013 WWF Verona Paolo Villa 9886.JPG\n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Ora della Terra Verona Piazza Bra Arena 2013 WWF Verona Paolo Villa 9954.JPG\n| caption2 = \n| footer = [[Earth Hour]] 2013 at the [[Verona Arena]] amphitheatre, [[Piazza Bra]], [[Verona]], Italy before (top) and while the street lighting was switched off.\n}}The idea for a fund on behalf of endangered animals was officially proposed by [[Victor Stolan]] to [[Julian Huxley|Sir Julian Huxley]] in response to articles he published in the British newspaper ''[[The Observer]]''. This proposal led Huxley to put Stolan in contact with [[Max Nicholson]], a person who had had thirty years experience of linking [[progressivism|progressive]] intellectuals with [[big business]] interests through the [[Political and Economic Planning]] [[think tank]].<ref name=\"WWF history\">{{cite web |url=http://wwf.panda.org/who_we_are/history/sixties/ |title=WWF in the 60s |publisher=World Wildlife Fund for Nature |date= |accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Kellaway\">Kate Kellaway (7 November 2010). [https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2010/nov/07/wwf-world-wildlife-fund-huxley How the Observer brought the WWF into being] [[The Observer]].</ref><ref>Scott, P. (1965). The launching of a new ark: first report of the President and Trustees of the World Wildlife Fund, an international foundation for saving the world's wildlife and wild places; 1962-1965 (Collins).</ref> Nicholson thought up the name of the organization. WWF was conceived on 29 April 1961, under the name of ''World Wildlife Fund'', and its first office was opened on 11 September that same year in [[Morges]], Switzerland.\n\nThe WWF was conceived to act as a funding institution for existing conservation groups such as the [[International Union for the Conservation of Nature|International Union for the Conservation of Nature and Natural Resources]] and The Conservation Foundation.<ref name=\"wwfhistory\">{{cite web|url=https://www.worldwildlife.org/about/history|title=History - WWF|website=World Wildlife Fund}}</ref> [[Godfrey A. Rockefeller]] also played an important role in its creation, assembling the first staff.<ref name=\"WWF\">[http://www.worldwildlife.org/who/media/press/2010/WWFPresitem15151.html In Memoriam: Godfrey A. Rockefeller], [[World Wildlife Fund]], 29 January 2010.</ref> Its establishment was marked with the signing of the \"Morges Manifesto\", the founding document that sets out the fund's commitment to assisting worthy organizations struggling to save the world's wildlife:<ref>\"[http://wwf.panda.org/who_we_are/history/ History: Fifty Years of Environmental Conservation]\". With link to [http://assets.panda.org/downloads/morgesmanifesto.pdf PDF] of \"Morges Manisto\". World Wildlife Fund for Nature. wwf.panda.org. Retrieved 20 June 2017.</ref>\n\n{{quote|They need above all money, to carry out mercy missions and to meet conservation emergencies by buying land where wildlife treasures are threatened, and in many other ways. Money, for example, to pay guardians of wildlife refuges&nbsp;.... Money for education and propaganda among those who would care and help if only they understood. Money to send out experts to danger spots and to train more local wardens and helpers in Africa and elsewhere. Money to maintain a sort of 'war room' at the international headquarters of conservation, showing where the danger spots are and making it possible to ensure that their needs are met before it is too late.|source=Morges Manifesto}}Dutch [[Prince Bernhard of Lippe-Biesterfeld]] helped found the World Wildlife Fund, becoming its first President in 1961. In 1963, the Foundation held a conference and published a major report warning of [[Human impact on the environment|anthropogenic]] [[global warming]], written by Noel Eichhorn based on the work of [[Frank Fraser Darling]] (then foundation vice president), [[Edward Deevey]], Erik Eriksson, [[Charles Keeling]], [[Gilbert Plass]], Lionel Walford, and [[William Garnett (photographer)|William Garnett]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001495147|title=Implications of Rising Carbon Dioxide Content of the Atmosphere: A statement of trends and implications of carbon dioxide research reviewed at a conference of scientists|last=Eichhorn|first=Noel|date=1963|publisher=The Conservation Foundation|place=New York}}</ref>\n\nIn 1970, along with [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Duke of Edinburgh]] and a few associates, [[Prince Bernhard of Lippe-Biesterfeld|Prince Bernhard]] established the WWF's [[financial endowment]] ''[[The 1001: A Nature Trust]]'' to handle the WWF's administration and fund-raising. 1001 members each contributed $10,000 to the trust.<ref name=\"WWF Finland\">{{in lang|en}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20100715155311/http://www.wwf.fi/english/international/history WWF Finland - History of WWF International]</ref> Prince Bernhard resigned his post after being involved in the [[Lockheed Bribery Scandal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1478171/HRH-Prince-Bernhard-of-the-Netherlands.html|title=Obituary: HRH Prince Bernhard of the Netherlands|date=4 December 2004|publisher=The Telegraph|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081108050115/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1478171/HRH-Prince-Bernhard-of-the-Netherlands.html|archivedate=8 November 2008|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Recent development ===\n{{Third-party|date=July 2019}}\n\nThe WWF has set up offices and operations around the world. It originally worked by fundraising and providing grants to existing non-governmental organizations with an initial focus on the protection of [[endangered species]]. As more resources became available, its operations expanded into other areas such as the preservation of [[Extinction|biological diversity]], sustainable use of [[natural resources]], the reduction of [[pollution]], and [[climate change]]. The organization also began to run its own conservation projects and campaigns.{{Citation_needed|date=July 2019}}[[File:WWF Big Ballon 2013.jpg|thumb|A WWF hot air balloon in Mexico (2013).|alt=]]In 1986, the organization changed its name to ''World Wide Fund for Nature'', while retaining the WWF initials. However, it continued at that time to operate under the original name in the United States and Canada.<ref name=\"history-eighties\">{{cite web |url=https://wwf.panda.org/knowledge_hub/history/eighties/ |title=WWF in the 80's |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=<!--Not stated--> |website=WWF |access-date=2019-01-13 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113210304/https://wwf.panda.org/knowledge_hub/history/eighties/| archive-date=2019-01-13}}</ref>\n\n1986 was the 25th anniversary of WWF's foundation, an event marked by a gathering in Assisi, Italy to which the organization's International President Prince Philip, the Duke of Edinburgh, invited religious authorities representing Buddhism, Christianity, Hinduism, Islam and Judaism. These leaders produced The Assisi Declarations, theological statements showing the spiritual relationship between their followers and nature that triggered a growth in the engagement of those religions with conservation around the world.<ref name=\"history-eighties\" />\n\nIn the 1990s, WWF revised its mission statement to:\n\n{{quote|Stop the degradation of the planet's natural environment and to build a future in which humans live in harmony with nature, by:\n* conserving the world's biological diversity;\n* ensuring that the use of renewable natural resources is sustainable; [and]\n* promoting the reduction of pollution and wasteful consumption.}}{{Citation_needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nWWF scientists and many others identified 238 [[ecoregions]] that represent the world's most biologically outstanding [[earth|terrestrial]], [[freshwater]] and [[oceans|marine]] habitats, based on a worldwide biodiversity analysis which the organization says was the first of its kind.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panda.org/about_our_earth/ecoregions/about/ |title=About global ecoregions |publisher=World Wide Fund for Nature |date= |accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref> In the early 2000s (decade), its work was focused on a subset of these ecoregions, in the areas of forest, freshwater and marine [[habitat conservation]], endangered species conservation, climate change, and the elimination of the most toxic chemicals.\n\n{{quote|We shan't save all we should like to, but we shall save a great deal more than if we had never tried.|Sir [[Peter Scott]]<ref name=\"WWF Finland\"/>}}\n\nIn 1990, the Conservation Foundation was completely merged into WWF, after becoming an affiliate of WWF-US in 1985 when it became a distinct legal entity but with the same staff and board.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwildlife.org/about/history|title=History {{!}} WWF|website=World Wildlife Fund|language=en|access-date=2019-01-22}}</ref> The organization now known as the Conservation Foundation in the United States is the former Forest Foundation of DuPage County.<ref name=\"wwfhistory\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://theconservationfoundation.org/page.php?PageID=2|title=The Conservation Foundation|website=theconservationfoundation.org}}</ref> In 1996, the organization obtained general [[consultative status]] from [[UNESCO]].{{Citation_needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n== Panda symbol ==\n{{Third-party|date=July 2019}}\n[[File:Grosser Panda.JPG|thumb|The giant panda has become the symbol of WWF.|alt=|200x200px]]\n\nWWF's [[giant panda]] logo originated from a panda named [[Chi Chi (giant panda)|Chi Chi]] that had been transferred from [[Beijing Zoo]] to [[London Zoo]] in 1958, three years before WWF became established.  Being famous as the only panda residing in the Western world at that time, her uniquely recognisable physical features and status as an endangered species were seen as ideal to serve the organization's need for a strong recognisable symbol that would overcome all language barriers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/who_we_are/history/sixties/|title=WWF - WWF in the 60's|date=|publisher=WWF|accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref> The organization also needed an animal that would have an impact in black and white printing. The logo was then designed by [[Peter Scott (conservationist)|Sir Peter Scott]] from preliminary sketches by Gerald Watterson, a Scottish naturalist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/who_we_are/history/sixties/|title=WWF in the 60's|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldwildlife.org/species/finder/giantpanda/panda.html|title=WWF - Giant Panda - Overview|date=|publisher=Worldwildlife.org|accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe logo was slightly simplified and made more geometric in 1978, and was revised significantly again in 1986, at the time that the organization changed its name, with the new version featuring solid black shapes for eyes.<ref>\"[http://www.logodesignlove.com/world-wildlife-fund World Wildlife Fund logo sketches]\". Logo Design Love. 7 June 2011; updated by Jerry Kuyper, 9&nbsp;June2011. logodesignlove.com. Retrieved 21 June 2017.</ref> In 2000 a change was made to the font used for the initials \"WWF\" in the logo.<ref>\"[https://www.famouslogos.us/wwf-logo/ WWF Logo]\". Famous Logos. famouslogos.us. Retrieved 21 June 2017.</ref>\n\n== Organization and operation ==\n\n===Policy-making===\n{{Third-party|date=July 2019}}\nPolicies of the WWF are made by board members elected for three-year terms. An Executive Team guides and develops WWF's strategy. There is also a National Council which stands as an advisory group to the board and a team of scientists and experts in conservation who research for WWF.\n\nNational and international law plays an important role in determining how habitats and resources are managed and used. Laws and regulations become one of the organization's global priorities.\n\nThe WWF has been opposed to the extraction of oil from the Canadian [[tar sands]] and has campaigned on this matter. Between 2008 and 2010 the WWF worked with [[The Co-operative Group]], the [[UK]]'s largest [[consumer co-operative]] to publish reports which concluded that: (1) exploiting the Canadian tar sands to their full potential would be sufficient to bring about what they described as 'runaway climate change;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.co-operative.coop/upload/ToxicFuels/docs/WWF_CFS_Unconventionals_report.pdf|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150708080954/http://www.co-operative.coop/upload/ToxicFuels/docs/WWF_CFS_Unconventionals_report.pdf|archivedate=8 July 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref> (2) carbon capture and storage (CCS) technology cannot be used to reduce the release of carbon dioxide into the atmosphere to a level comparable to that of other methods of oil extraction;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.co-operative.coop/upload/ToxicFuels/docs/CCS-in-the-Alberta-oil-sands-a-dangerous-myth.pdf|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923205501/http://www.co-operative.coop/upload/ToxicFuels/docs/CCS-in-the-Alberta-oil-sands-a-dangerous-myth.pdf|archivedate=23 September 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref> (3) the $379 billion which is expected to be spent extracting oil from [[tar sands]] could be better spent on research and development in renewable energy technology;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.co-operative.coop/upload/ToxicFuels/docs/opportunity-cost-report.pdf|title=Opportunity cost of tar sands development|work=co-operative.coop|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906001129/https://www.co-operative.coop/upload/ToxicFuels/docs/opportunity-cost-report.pdf|archivedate=6 September 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=25 September 2018}}</ref> and (4) the expansion of tar sands extraction poses a serious threat to the caribou in Alberta .<ref>http://www.co-operative.coop/upload/ToxicFuels/docs/caribou-report.pdf</ref>\n\nThe organization convinces and helps governments and other political bodies to adopt, enforce, strengthen and/or change policies, guidelines and laws that affect biodiversity and natural resource use. It also ensures government consent and/or keeps their commitment to international instruments relating to the protection of biodiversity and natural resources.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/what_we_do/how_we_work/tackling_the_causes/|title=Tackling the Causes|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/what_we_do/how_we_work/policy/|title=Advocacy & policy|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, David Nussbaum, Chief Executive of WWF-UK, spoke out against the way [[shale gas]] is used in the UK, saying: \"...{{nbsp}}the Government must reaffirm its commitment to tackling climate change and prioritise renewables and energy efficiency.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.securingthefuture.co.uk/energy/12572-take-foot-off-the-pedal-on-shale-gas-charities-warn-government|title='Take foot off the pedal on shale gas', charities warn Government|last=Buckler|first=Scott|website=www.securingthefuture.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n=== Collaboration ===\n{{Third-party|date=July 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=July 2019}}\nWWF's strategy for achieving its mission specifically concentrates on restoring populations of 36 [[species]] (species or species groups that are important for their [[ecosystem]] or to people, including [[elephant]]s, [[tuna]]s, [[Cetacea|whales, dolphins and porpoises]]), and [[ecological footprint]] in 6 areas (carbon emissions, cropland, grazing land, fishing, forestry and water).{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nThe organization also works on a number of [[global issue]]s driving [[biodiversity loss]] and unsustainable use of natural resources, including finance, business practices, laws, and consumption choices. Local offices also work on national or regional issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panda.org/what_we_do/|title=What does the World Wild Life Fund do?|date=|publisher=World Wide Fund for Nature|accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nWWF works with a large number of different groups to achieve its goals, including other NGOs, governments, business, investment banks, scientists, fishermen, farmers and local communities. It also undertakes public campaigns to influence decision makers, and seeks to educate people on how to live in a more environmentally friendly manner. It urges people to donate funds to protect the environment. The donors can also choose to receive gifts in return.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\n=== List of presidents ===\n[[File:Yolanda Kakabadse 2.jpg|thumb|Yolanda Kakabadse, WWF president from 2010 to 2017]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"\n! Years<ref name=\"presidents\">[http://wwf.panda.org/who_we_are/organization/presidents/ Presidents - past and present], official website of the World Wide Fund for Nature (page visited on 4 March 2018).</ref>\n! Name<ref name=\"presidents\" />\n|-\n|&nbsp; 1961\u20131976 ||[[Prince Bernhard of Lippe-Biesterfeld]]\n|-\n|&nbsp; 1976\u20131981 ||[[John Hugo Loudon]]\n|-\n|&nbsp; 1981\u20131996 ||[[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]\n|-\n|&nbsp; 1996\u20131999 ||[[Syed Babar Ali]]\n|-\n|&nbsp; {{0|2000\u2013}}2000 ||[[Ruud Lubbers]]\n|-\n|&nbsp; 2000\u20132001 ||[[Sara Morrison]]\n|-\n|&nbsp; 2001\u20132010 ||[[Emeka Anyaoku|Chief Emeka Anyaoku]]\n|-\n|&nbsp; 2010\u20132017 ||[[Yolanda Kakabadse]]\n|-\n|&nbsp; 2018\u2013present&nbsp;|| [[Pavan Sukhdev]]\n|}\n\n== Notable initiatives and programs ==\n=== Campaigns ===\n\n*[[Debt-for-Nature Swap]]\n*[[Earth Hour]]\n*[[Healthy Grown]]\n*[[Marine Stewardship Council]]\n\n=== Global initiatives ===\n{{Third-party|date=July 2019}}\nSince 2008, through its Global Programme Framework (GPF), WWF has said it is concentrating its efforts on 13 global initiatives:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/what_we_do/how_we_work/key_initiatives/|title=Our Global Goals|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n*[[Amazon rainforest|Amazon]]\n* Arctic\n* China for a Global Shift\n* Climate and Energy\n* Coastal East Africa[[File:People's Climate March 2017 20170429 4331 (34351241115).jpg|thumb|[[People's Climate March (2017)|People's Climate March]] 2017|alt=]]\n* Coral Triangle\n* Forest and Climate\n* Green Heart of Africa\n* Heart of Borneo\n* Living Himalayas\n* Market Transformation\n* Smart Fishing\n* Tigers<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wwf.sg/business/asian_tigers_mobility_group.cfm|title=Asian Tigers Mobility Group {{!}} WWF|website=www.wwf.sg|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Publications ===\n\nWWF publishes the ''[[Living Planet Index]]'' in collaboration with the [[Zoological Society of London]]. Along with [[ecological footprint]] calculations, the ''Index'' is used to produce a bi-yearly ''[[Living Planet Report]]'' giving an overview of the impact of human activity on the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.panda.org/about_our_earth/all_publications/living_planet_report/ |title=Living Planet Report |publisher=World Wide Fund for Nature |date= |accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref> In 2019, WWF and [[Knorr (brand)|Knorr]] jointly published the [[Future 50 Foods report]] identifying \"50 Foods for Healthier People and a Healthier Planet\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/2019-02/Knorr_Future_50_Report_FINAL_Online.pdf|title=Future 50 Foods: 50 foods for healthier people and a healthier planet|last=Drewnowski|first=Adam|date=February 2019|website=World Wide Fund for Nature|access-date=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe organization also regularly publishes reports, fact sheets and other documents on issues related to its work, to raise awareness and provide information to policy and decision makers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panda.org/about_our_earth/all_publications/|title=Publication & Resources|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== Promotions ===\n\n* ''[[No One's Gonna Change Our World]]'' was a charity album released in 1969, for the benefit of the WWF.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/story-of-the-song-across-the-universe-by-the-beatles-in-1968-and-beady-eye-in-2011-2265187.html|title=Story of the Song: Across the Universe by The Beatles in 1968 and|date=2011-04-08|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n* [[Peter Rose and Anne Conlon]] are music theatre writers, well known for their environmental musicals for children, who were commissioned by WWF-UK to write several environmental musicals as part of an education plan.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/version/191183717|title=Yanomamo : an ecological musical for soloists, chorus, narrator & stage band|last=Rose|first=Peter|last2=Conlon|first2=Anne|last3=Dept|first3=World Wide Fund for Nature UK Education|date=1993|publisher=London : Josef Weinberger in association with the World Wide Fund for Nature|language=English}}</ref> Some were narrated by [[David Attenborough]], and broadcast on television in numerous countries.\n* The British pop group [[S Club|S Club 7]] were ambassadors for WWF-UK during their time together as a band (1999-2003).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GoaBAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT35&lpg=PT35&dq=S+Club+7+world+wide+fund&source=bl&ots=m4is-VhXgX&sig=ACfU3U1fEYOqljyCeR_nF0aODi1Q4IlJBA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj2sIKjrezgAhVJ04MKHcAvD9wQ6AEwD3oECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=S%20Club%207%20world%20wide%20fund&f=false|title=S Club 7|last=Golden|first=Anna Louise|date=2014-06-17|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=9781466873940|language=en}}</ref> Each of the members sponsored an endangered animal, and in 2000, traveled to the various locations around the world of their chosen animals for a seven-part [[BBC]] documentary series entitled ''[[S Club 7 Go Wild!|S Club 7 Go Wild]]''.\n* ''Environmentally Sound: A Select Anthology of Songs Inspired by the Earth'' is a benefit album released in 2006, for WWF-Philippines, featuring artists that included [[Up Dharma Down]], [[Radioactive Sago Project]], [[Kala (band)|Kala]], [[Cynthia Alexander]], and [[Joey Ayala]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwf.org.ph/newsfacts.php?pg=det&id=25|title=The Harmonics of being Environmentally Sound|date=18 August 2006|publisher=[[World Wildlife Fund]] - Philippines|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720233747/http://www.wwf.org.ph/newsfacts.php?pg=det&id=25|archivedate=20 July 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=30 June 2010}}</ref>\n* In June 2012, WWF launched an online [[music download]] store with [[fairsharemusic]] from which 50% of the profit goes to the charity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nonprofitquarterly.org/2010/06/22/nonprofit-newswire-british-website-connects-music-lovers-and-charities/|title=Nonprofit Newswire {{!}} British Website Connects Music Lovers and Charities|last=Trachtenberg|first=Bruce S.|date=2010-06-22|website=Non Profit News {{!}} Nonprofit Quarterly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n* In April 2015, [[Hailey Gardiner]] released her solo EP, titled The Woods. In honor of [[Earth Day]], 15% of the proceeds made towards the purchase of the EP would be donated to the WWF.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gardinersisters.com/blog/rdinersisters.com/2015/04/the-woods.html|title=The Woods|website=Gardiner Sisters|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies and disputes ==\n\n=== ARD documentary and \"PandaLeaks\" book ===\nThe German public television [[ARD (broadcaster)|ARD]] aired a documentary on 22 June 2011 that claimed to show how the WWF cooperates with corporations such as [[Monsanto]], providing sustainability certification in exchange for donations{{nbsp}}\u2013 essentially [[greenwashing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ardmediathek.de/ard/servlet/content/3517136?documentId=7495082|title=''Der Pakt mit dem Panda: Was uns der WWF verschweigt'' (Pact with the Panda: What the WWF conceals)|date=22 June 2011|work=DasErste.de|publisher=tagesschau.de ARD|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728032810/http://www.ardmediathek.de/ard/servlet/content/3517136?documentId=7495082|archive-date=28 July 2011|accessdate=25 July 2011}} See also: [http://programm.ard.de/TV/Programm/Sender/?sendung=281117723794509 program overview for rebroadcast], 2 April 2012, programm.ARD.de, noting the objections raised by WWF supporters after the initial broadcast, and retracting two claims made in the film; retrieved 16 July 2017.</ref> WWF has denied the allegations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwf.de/themen/huismann-kritik-pakt-mit-dem-panda-faktencheck|title=WWF-Mitarbeiter treffen Chief Kasimirus Sangara|last=WWF|accessdate=9 July 2011}}</ref> By encouraging high-impact eco-tourism, the program alleges that WWF contributes to the destruction of habitat and species it claims to protect while also harming indigenous peoples.<ref>{{cite thesis |last= Harryman|first= Ian|date= Spring 2016|title= Ecological Problem Solving: A Comparative Study of Primate Conservation|type= Undergraduate Honors|publisher= University of Colorado, Boulder|url= https://scholar.colorado.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2266&context=honr_theses|access-date=15 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe filmmaker, [[:de:Wilfried Huismann|Wilfried Huismann]], was sued by the WWF over his documentary and the book \"Schwarzbuch WWF\" published in 2012, which was based on the documentary. In an out of court settlement, he agreed to remove or revise certain claims. Speaking on behalf of WWF Germany, Marco Vollmar indicated \"[Huismann] draws a distorted picture of false statements, defamations and exaggerations, but we will accept that as expressions of opinion.\" (Translated from the original German: \"ein Zerrbild aus falschen Aussagen, Diffamierungen und \u00dcbertreibungen, aber das werden wir als Meinungs\u00e4u\u00dferungen hinnehmen.\")<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spiegel.de/kultur/literatur/schwarzbuch-wwf-einigung-zwischen-wwf-und-huismann-steht-bevor-a-844243.html |title=environmental organization and critics before agreement|last=Seidler |first=Christoph |date=20 July 2012 |website=www.spiegel.de |publisher=Spiegel Online|access-date=15 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, German investigative journalist [[:de:Wilfried Huismann|Wilfried Huismann]] published a revised edition of his 2012 book, originally called ''The Silence of the Pandas''. The original edition had become a bestseller in Germany, but was banned from Britain until 2014, when it was released under the title of ''PandaLeaks - The Dark Side of the WWF'', after a series of injunctions and court orders.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2014/oct/04/wwf-international-selling-its-soul-corporations|title=WWF International accused of 'selling its soul' to corporations|last=Vidal|first=John|date=4 October 2014|work=The Guardian}}</ref> The book criticizes WWF for its supposed involvement with corporations that are responsible for large-scale destruction of the environment, such as Coca-Cola, and gives details into the existence of the secret [[1001 Club]], whose members, Huismann claims, continue to have an unhealthy influence on WWF's policy making.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\" /> WWF has denied the allegations made against it.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wwf.panda.org/wwf_news/press_releases/a_quick_guide_to_the_silence_of_the_pandas_documentary.cfm|title=A quick guide to the silence of the pandas documentary|publisher=WWF}}</ref>\n\n=== Corporate partnerships ===\nWWF has been accused by the campaigner [[Corporate Watch]] of being too close to business to campaign objectively.<ref name= \"Corp1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.corporatewatch.org/?lid=1873 |title=PANDA-ING TO THE SOYA BARONS? |author= |date=30 September 2009 |work= |publisher=Corporate Watch |accessdate=9 December 2009}}</ref><ref name= \"Corp2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/2009/apr/02/greenwash-ikea-diy-earth-hour |title=Ikea \u2013 you can't build a green reputation with a flatpack DIY manual |author=Fred Pearce |date=2 April 2009 |work= |publisher=Guardian UK |accessdate=9 December 2009 |location=London}}</ref> WWF claims partnering with corporations such as [[Coca-Cola]], [[Lafarge (company)|Lafarge]], [[Carlos Slim]]'s and [[IKEA]] will reduce their effect on the environment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panda.org/what_we_do/how_we_work/businesses/ |title=Changing the nature of business |publisher=World Wide Fund for Nature|date= |accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref>  WWF received \u20ac56 million (US$80 million) from corporations in 2010 (an 8% increase in support from corporations compared to 2009), accounting for 11% of total revenue for the year.<ref name=\"WWF-INT Annual Review\"/>\n\nFor their 2019 fiscal year, WWF reported 4% of their total operating revenue coming from corporations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwildlife.org/about/financials|title=Funding and Financial Overview {{!}} WWF|website=World Wildlife Fund|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Human rights abuses by paramilitaries ===\nIn 2017, a report by [[Survival International]] claimed that WWF-funded [[paramilitaries]] are not only committing abuses against the indigenous Baka and Bayaka in the Congo Basin, who \"face harassment and beatings, torture and death\", but are also corrupt and aid in the destruction of conserved areas. The report accused the WWF and its guards of partnering with several logging companies who carried out deforestation, while the rangers ignored wildlife trafficking networks.<ref name = \"SI abuse\">{{Cite web |url=https://assets.survivalinternational.org/documents/1683/how-will-we-survive.pdf|title=How will we survive? |year=2017 |website=[[Survival International]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, an investigation by ''[[BuzzFeed News]]'' alleged that paramilitary groups funded by the organisation are engaged in serious human rights abuses against villagers, and the organisation has covered up the incidents and acted to protect the perpetrators from law enforcement. These armed groups were claimed to torture, sexually assault, and execute villagers based on false accusations. In one instance found by ''BuzzFeed News'' investigators, an 11-year-old boy was allegedly tortured by WWF-funded rangers in front of his parents;<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/tomwarren/wwf-world-wide-fund-nature-parks-torture-death|title=WWF Funds Guards Who Have Tortured And Killed People |last=Warren|first=Tom |last2=Baker |first2=Katie J. M. |date=4 March 2019 |website=www.buzzfeednews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> the WWF ignored all complaints against the rangers. In another incident, a ranger attempted to rape a Tharu woman and, when she resisted, attacked her with bamboo stick until she lost consciousness. While the ranger was arrested, the woman was pressured not to press charges, resulting in the ranger going free. In 2010, WWF-sponsored rangers reportedly killed a 12-year-old girl who was collecting tree bark in [[Bardiya National Park]]. Park and WWF officials allegedly obstructed investigations in these cases, by \"falsifying and destroying evidence, falsely claiming the victims were poachers, and pressuring the families of the victims to withdraw criminal complaints\".<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2019/mar/04/wwf-accused-of-funding-guards-who-allegedly-tortured-killed-scores-of-people|title=WWF accused of funding guards who 'tortured and killed scores of people'|last=McVeigh|first=Karen|date=2019-03-04|website=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> In July 2019 Buzzfeed reported that a leaked report by the WWF accused guards of beating and raping women including pregnant women while torturing men by tying their penises with fishing lines. The investigations were cut short after paramilitary groups threatened investigators with death. The investigators accused WWF of covering up the crimes. Releasing an official statement, the WWF claimed that the report was not made public to ensure the safety of the victims and that the guards were suspended and are awaiting prosecution. However Buzzfeed accused the WWF of attempting to withhold the report to the US congressional committee investigating the human rights violations by providing high redacted versions instead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/tomwarren/leaked-report-wwf-backed-guards-raped-pregnant-women|title=Leaked Report: WWF-Backed Guards Raped Pregnant Women And Tortured Villagers At A Wildlife Park Funded By The US Government|website=BuzzFeed News|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/?349754|title=Statement on safeguarding human rights in conservation, and addressing allegations of human rights abuse {{!}} WWF|website=wwf.panda.org|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Central African Republic]], WWF officials were reportedly involved in an arms deal, where the organization paid for 15 AK assault rifles and ammunition; but part of the money went unaccounted and apparently defrauded by the CAR army representatives selling the weapons.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'', which cooperated with ''BuzzFeed News'' on the investigations in [[Nepal]], claimed there was intense lobbying and political pressure to release WWF-funded rangers arrested for murder. They interviewed activists who claimed they were promised donations for pressuring victims of abuse to drop charges against the rangers. When the local [[Tharu people|Tharu]] community protested, WWF officials carried out a counter-protest in favour of the accused and used park elephants to block [[Prithvi Highway]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2019-03-03/nepals-park-officials-who-beat-and-tortured-a-man-were-rewarded-by-the-government-and-the-world-wide-fund-for-nature.html|title=Nepali park officials tortured a man to death. Then, the government and the World Wide Fund for Nature rewarded them. |date=3 March 2019 |website=Kathmandu Post |language=English|access-date=2019-03-05}}</ref>\n\nAn investigation by [[Rainforest Foundation UK]] found evidence of widespread physical and sexual assault by \u2018eco-guards\u2019  employed by the [[Salonga National Park]] in the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]] funded by the WWF.  These include two cases of gang rape, two extrajudicial killings, and multiple accounts of torture and other forms of mistreatment committed by park guards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rainforestfoundationuk.org/widespread-human-rights-abuses-in-africas-largest-forest-park |title=Widespread human rights abuses in Africa\u2019s largest forest park |date=4 March 2019 |website=Rainforest Foundation UK |language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref>\n\nIn reply to the investigations, the WWF stated that it takes any allegations seriously and would be launching an independent review into the cases raised. The organisation stated it has stringent policies designed to ensure it and its partners are safeguarding the rights and well-being of indigenous peoples and local communities, and should the review uncover any breaches, it is committed to taking swift action.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/wwf_news/press_releases/?343750/WWF-Response-to-BuzzFeed-allegations|title=WWF response to Buzzfeed reports |date=4 March 2019 |website=wwf.panda.org|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Initialism dispute ===\n{{see also|WWE#Legal disputes and controversies}}\n\nIn 2000, the World Wide Fund for Nature sued the [[World Wrestling Federation]] (now named [[WWE]]) for unfair trade practices. Both parties had shared the initials \"WWF\" since 1979. The conservation organization claimed that the [[professional wrestling]] company had violated a 1994 agreement regarding international use of the WWF initials.<ref>[http://www.internetnews.com/bus-news/article.php/3_1038611 InternetNews Realtime IT News \u2013 Wildlife Fund Pins Wrestling Federation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061114234625/http://www.internetnews.com/bus-news/article.php/3_1038611|date=14 November 2006}}</ref><ref>[http://contracts.corporate.findlaw.com/agreements/wwf/worldwildlife.1997.01.20.html Text of the 1994 legal agreement with the World Wrestling Federation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013110155/http://contracts.corporate.findlaw.com/agreements/wwf/worldwildlife.1997.01.20.html|date=13 October 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 August 2001, a UK court ruled in favour of the World Wide Fund for Nature. The World Wrestling Federation filed an appeal in October 2001. However, on 10 May 2002, the World Wrestling Federation changed its [[Web address]] from ''WWF.com'' to ''WWE.com'', and replaced every \"WWF\" reference on the existing site with \"WWE\", as a prelude to changing the company's name to \"World Wrestling Entertainment.\" Its stock ticker also switched from WWF to WWE.\n\nThe wrestling organization's abandonment of the \"WWF\" [[initialism]] did not end the two organizations' legal conflict. Later in 2002, the World Wide Fund for Nature petitioned the court for $360 million in damages, but was not successful. A subsequent request to overturn by the World Wide Fund for Nature was dismissed by the British [[Court of Appeal of England and Wales|Court of Appeal]] on 28 June 2007. In 2003, World Wrestling Entertainment won a limited decision which permitted them to continue marketing certain pre-existing products with the abandoned WWF logo. However, WWE was mandated to issue newly branded merchandise such as apparel, action figures, video games, and [[DVD]]s with the \"WWE\" initials. Additionally, the court order required the company to remove both auditory and visual references to \"WWF\" in its library of video footage outside the United Kingdom.\n\nStarting with the 1,000th episode of ''Raw'' in July 2012, the WWF \"scratch\" logo is no longer censored in archival footage. In addition, the WWF initials are no longer censored when spoken or when written in plain text in archival footage.  In exchange, WWE is no longer permitted to use the WWF initials or logo in any new, original footage, packaging, or advertising, with any old-school logos for retro-themed programming now using a modification of the original WWF logo without the F.\n\n=== Mekong River dolphins report ===\nIn June 2009, Touch Seang Tana, chairman of [[Cambodia]]'s Commission for Conservation and Development of the [[Mekong River]] Dolphins Eco-tourism Zone, argued that the WWF had misrepresented the danger of extinction of the [[Irrawaddy dolphin|Mekong dolphin]] to boost fundraising.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.cri.cn/6966/2009/06/24/2001s496246.htm |title=Cambodia Rejects CNN, WWF Reports about Mekong Dolphin |publisher=CRIEnglish.com |date=24 June 2009 |accessdate=2 March 2013}}</ref> The report stated that the deaths were caused by a bacterial disease that became fatal due to environmental contaminants suppressing the dolphins' immune systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/wwf_news/?167401/Mekong-dolphins-on-the-brink-of-extinction|title=Mekong dolphins on the brink of extinction|access-date=21 September 2016}}</ref> He called the report unscientific and harmful to the Cambodian government and threatened the WWF's Cambodian branch with suspension unless they met with him to discuss his claims.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://khmerization.blogspot.com/2009/06/cambodia-threatens-to-suspend-wwf-after.html |title=Cambodia threatens to suspend WWF after dolphin report |accessdate=2 August 2017}}</ref> Touch Seang Tana later said he would not press charges of supplying false information and would not make any attempt to prevent WWF from continuing its work in Cambodia, but advised WWF to adequately explain its findings and check with the commission before publishing another report. After this, in January 2012, Touch Seang Tana signed the \"Kratie Declaration on the Conservation of the Mekong River Irrawaddy Dolphin\" along with WWF and the Cambodian Fisheries Administration, an agreement binding the parties to work together on a \"roadmap\" addressing dolphin conservation in the Mekong River.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phnompenhpost.com/national/authors-report-dolphins-will-not-face-charges-official-says|title=Authors of report on dolphins will not face charges official says|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=|accessdate=22 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Centres of Plant Diversity]]\n* [[Conservation movement]]\n* [[Environmental Dispute Resolution Fund]]\n* [[Environmental movement]]\n* [[Eugene Green Energy Standard]], founded by the WWF.\n* [[Global 200]], ecoregions identified by the WWF as priorities for conservation\n* [[List of environmental organizations]]\n* [[Natural environment]]\n* [[Sustainability]]\n* [[Sustainable development]]\n* [[Traffic (conservation programme)]], a joint programme of WWF and the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature|International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN)]]\n* [[West Coast Environmental Law]]\n* [[World Conservation Award]], created in conjunction with the WWF\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|World Wide Fund For Nature|<br />WWF<br />(World Wide Fund For Nature)}}\n\n* {{official website|https://panda.org/|Panda.org}} (WWF International website)\n* [http://www.worldwildlife.org World Wildlife Fund], WWF-US Website.\n* {{YouTube|user=wwf|WWF}}.\n* [http://www.wwf.org/ WWF's global network]\n** {{hlist |[http://www.wwf.org.uk/ WWF-UK] |{{EW charity|1081247|WWF - UK}}}}\n** [http://scotland.wwf.org.uk/ WWF Scotland]\n** [http://armenia.panda.org/ WWF Armenia]\n** [http://www.wwfpak.org/  WWF-Pakistan]\n** [http://www.wwfindia.org/index.cfm WWF-India]\n** [http://www.wwfguianas.org/ WWF Guianas]\n** [http://www.wwf.ru/eng WWF Russia]\n\n{{WWFN}}\n{{Prince of Asturias Award for Concord}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Environment|Ecology|Earth sciences}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:World Wide Fund For Nature}}\n[[Category:World Wide Fund for Nature| ]]\n[[Category:International environmental organizations]]\n[[Category:Conservation organizations]]\n[[Category:Ecology organizations]]\n[[Category:Wildlife conservation organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations with general consultative status to the United Nations Economic and Social Council]]\n[[Category:Environmental organizations established in 1961]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1961]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organisations based in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organisations based in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:1961 establishments in Switzerland]]\n", "name_user": "219.77.74.102", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Wide_Fund_for_Nature"}
{"title_page": "Annie LeBlanc", "text_new": "{{short description|American Internet personality, actress and singer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{for|the Canadian athlete|Annie LeBlanc (athlete)}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name                 = Annie LeBlanc\n| logo                 = \n| logo_caption         = \n| image                =\n| caption              =\n| birth_name           = Julianna Grace LeBlanc\n| birth_date           = {{Birth date and age|2004|12|5|mf}}\n| birth_place          = [[Augusta, Georgia]], U.S.\n| nationality          = American\n| occupation           = {{flatlist| \n* YouTuber\n* actress\n* singer\n}}\n| website              = {{URL|bratayley.com/annie}}\n| pseudonym            = \n| channel_name = acroanna\n| channel_display_name = Annie LeBlanc Bratayley \n| years_active         = 2008\u2013present\n| genre                = \n| subscribers          = 3.8 million\n| subscriber_date      = February 21, 2020\n| views                = 462 million\n| view_date            = February 21, 2020\n| network              = [[Brat (digital network)|Brat]] ({{small|current}})<br>[[Disney Digital Network|Maker Studios Inc.]] ({{small|former}})  \n| associated_acts      = {{Plainlist|\n*Bratayley\n}}\n| catchphrase(s)       = \n| silver_button        = yes\n| silver_year          =2012 \n| gold_button          = yes\n| gold_year            =2012 \n| diamond_button       = \n| diamond_year         = \n| ruby_button          = \n| ruby_year            = \n| stats_update         = \n| module               = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed = yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Electronic music|Electronic]]|[[Country music|country]]}}\n| years_active     = 2017\u2013present\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Julianna Grace''' \"'''Annie'''\" '''LeBlanc''' ({{IPAc-en|l|\u0259|\u02c8|b|l|\u0252|\u014b|k}}; born December 5, 2004) is an American Internet personality, actress, singer, and former gymnast. In December 2018, ''[[Business Insider]]'' called her one of the \"most famous teens in the world.\"<ref name=bi /> She has been featured in online videos since she was four years old and has an extensive online following. She stars as Rhyme in the family drama ''[[Chicken Girls]]'' on [[Brat (digital network)|Brat]] on [[YouTube]], starred in the YouTube Brat show ''A Girl Named Jo'' playing the part of Jo Chambers, and also played Rhyme in ''[[Chicken Girls: The Movie]]''. She has starred on the ''Bratayley'' family [[vlog]] since 2010 and the [[YouTube Premium|YouTube Red]] Originals series ''We Are Savvy'' since from 2016 to 2018.\n\n== Early and personal life ==\nAnnie LeBlanc was born to parents Billy and Katie while her father was stationed at [[Fort Gordon]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gazettereview.com/2018/01/annie-leblanc-height-weight-age-boyfriend/|title=Annie LeBlanc Height, Weight, Age & Boyfriend|last=Carter|first=Brooke|date=January 5, 2018|work=Gazette Review|access-date=June 19, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>{{Better source|date=November 2018}} She has two siblings, a younger sister Hayley, and an older brother Caleb Logan (July 13, 2002&nbsp;\u2013 October 1, 2015). In 2015, Caleb died from a heart condition, [[hypertrophic cardiomyopathy]] at the age of 13.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/oct/09/caleb-bratayley-vlogger-death-not-mystery-youtube|title=Caleb Bratayley's death is not a mystery \u2013 online sleuths should stand down|last=Parkinson|first=Hannah Jane|date=2015-10-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-02|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> LeBlanc started taking gymnastics classes when she was 2 years old, and her family started posting videos of her online when she was three.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}} She became famous as one of the three siblings featured on the family vlog YouTube channel Bratayley. She trained as a gymnast until August 2017.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}} She became popular on the app [[musical.ly]] under the name presshandstands7 but later changed it to annieleblanc, earning over 13 million fans.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}} She stars on the [[Brat (digital network)|Brat]] web series ''Chicken Girls'', ''[[A Girl Named Jo]]'', and \u201cWe Are Savvy\u201d.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}} \n\nThe LeBlancs previously lived in [[Severna Park, Maryland]] but then moved to [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] so that Annie would be able to start acting and doing music.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n== Career ==\nLeBlanc was originally known for her gymnastic videos.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://gazettereview.com/2017/08/annie-leblanc-net-worth-wealthy-gymnast-now/|title=Annie LeBlanc Net Worth 2018 \u2013 How Rich is the Gymnast \u2013 Gazette Review|last=Carter|first=Brooke|date=August 23, 2017|work=Gazette Review|access-date=June 20, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.santafenewmexican.com/life/family/youtube-youth-market-anti--mean-girl-image/article_6aa99f01-5646-563b-9633-24ae679ccc10.html|title=YouTube youth market anti-'mean girl' image|last=Times|first=Hayley KrischerThe New York|work=The Santa Fe New Mexican|access-date=June 20, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Her gymnastic meets and tutorials started being published in 2008 on her YouTube channel, formerly known as Acroanna, when she was 3 years old.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}} The channel's name was changed to Annie Leblanc in 2017, and features now music videos of Leblanc.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nLeBlanc is one of the stars of a daily [[vlog]] on the [[YouTube]] channel \"Bratayley\" (7M+ subscribers). The vlog, which was initially just for relatives and started being filmed when LeBlanc was six, follows the lives of the LeBlanc family.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://people.com/celebrity/5-things-to-know-about-the-bratayleys/|title=5 Things to Know About the Bratayleys|last1=Heyde|first1=Jennifer|website=PEOPLE.com|publisher=PEOPLE|language=en|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref> The stars include parents Billy and Katie with their two daughters Annie and Hayley. The name \"Bratayley\" was initially a nickname for Hayley, combining the word \"brat\" and the name \"Hayley.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nLeBlanc had begun to receive attention for her music on her [[TikTok]] handle @annieleblanc.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/news/music/ultimate-musically-stars/|title=The 12 musical.ly Stars You Need To Start Following Right Now|work=Capital|access-date=June 19, 2018|language=en}}</ref> In April 2018, she won the [[Shorty Awards|Shorty Award]] for \"Muser of the Year\".<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|title=Annie LeBlanc \u2013 The Shorty Awards|url=http://shortyawards.com/10th/annieleblanc|website=shortyawards.com|publisher=Shorty Awards}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thecelebritycafe.com/2018/04/shorty-awards-2018-complete-winners-list/|title=Shorty Awards: 2018 Complete Winners List - TheCelebrityCafe.com|website=thecelebritycafe.com|language=en-US|access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.celebritysauce.com/annie-leblanc-wins-big-at-the-shorty-awards/|title=Annie LeBlanc Wins Big at the Shorty Awards \u2013 Celebrity Sauce|date=April 17, 2018|work=Celebrity Sauce|access-date=June 19, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAfter it was speculated that LeBlanc was dating fellow social media star Hayden Summerall in 2017, the alleged couple was dubbed \"Hannie\" by fans, who created elaborate fan-fiction with complex storylines about their high school relationship, and photoshopped thousands of pictures that appear to show the two together.<ref name=beast>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/how-fans-invented-hannie-the-ultimate-social-media-supercouple|title=How Fans Invented #Hannie, the Ultimate Social Media Supercouple|last=Lorenz|first=Taylor|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=December 28, 2017|accessdate=July 27, 2019}}</ref> LeBlanc and Summerall collaborated on a YouTube cover of \"Little Do You Know\" by [[Alex & Sierra]], which went viral.<ref name=beast /> After Brat media founder Rob Fishman learned of the \"Hannie\" phenomenon, he cast LeBlanc and Summerall into an upcoming show, and their faux relationship was written into the storyline.<ref name=beast />\n\nLeBlanc and Summerall's cover appeared at position 48 on the Emerging Artists Billboard Chart.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/annie-leblanc/chart-history/AAF/song/1030763|title=Annie LeBlanc Artist Chart Chart History|work=Billboard|access-date=July 11, 2018}}</ref> On September 9, 2017, LeBlanc's cover of the song \"[[Fly (Maddie & Tae song)|Fly]]\" by [[Maddie & Tae]] peaked at 34 on the [[Billboard charts|Billboard Charts]] in \"Country\" songs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Annie LeBlanc |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/annie-leblanc |website=Billboard |publisher=Billboard |accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.itunescharts.net/us/artists/music/annie-leblanc/|title=iTunesCharts.net: Annie LeBlanc (American iTunes Music Chart Performance)|website=www.itunescharts.net|language=en|access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref> In November 2017, LeBlanc released her first original single, \"Ordinary Girl.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.itunescharts.net/us/artists/music/annie-leblanc/songs/ordinary-girl/|title=iTunesCharts.net: 'Ordinary Girl' by Annie LeBlanc (American Songs iTunes Chart)|website=www.itunescharts.net|language=en|access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.girlslife.com/trending/celebs/33480/youtube-star-annie-leblanc-shares-how-she-relieves-stress|title=YouTube star Annie LeBlanc shares her worst on-stage blunder!|access-date=June 20, 2018}}</ref> In December 2017, teen fan magazine ''[[Tiger Beat]]'' announced that LeBlanc would be going on her first U.S. tour in early 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Booth|first1=Ali|title=Annie LeBlanc to Join Hayden Summerall on Tour|url=http://tigerbeat.com/2017/12/annie-leblanc-left-me-hangin-tour/|website=Tiger Beat|publisher=Tiger Beat|accessdate=March 12, 2018|date=December 4, 2017}}</ref>  In February 2018, LeBlanc released a single, \"Little Things.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> In early May 2018, LeBlanc released a new [[Country pop|pop country]] compilation album on [[iTunes]] called, \"Lollipop\", with music label [[Heard Well]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|last1=Wingfield|first1=Katie|title=Annie LeBlanc Releases 'Lollipop' Compilation Album With Heard Well|url=http://tigerbeat.com/2018/05/annie-leblanc-lollipop-heard-well/|website=BOP and Tiger Beat|publisher=Tiger Beat|date=May 4, 2018}}</ref> The curated collection also includes two songs by LeBlanc, \"Somebody's Heart\" and \"Photograph.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> She then released her new single \"Picture This\" in early June with social media star Austin Brown.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}} A little before December 2018 she released her single \u201cIt\u2019s Gonna Snow\u201d as a new Christmas Carol.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nIn August 2017, ''Variety'' announced that YouTube greenlit the [[YouTube Premium|YouTube Red]] Originals series, ''We Are Savvy'', as a continuation of a teen magazine series of the same name on Canada's [[Family Channel (Canadian TV network)|Family Channel]].<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|last1=Clarke|first1=Stewart|title=YouTube Red Orders Original Kids Series 'We Are Savvy'|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/global/youtube-red-we-are-savvy-annie-leblanc-1202522280/|website=Variety|accessdate=March 12, 2018|date=August 10, 2017}}</ref> LeBlanc was introduced as a co-host of the series, which debuted with over 4.2M+ views in its pilot episode and focuses on music, fashion, and lifestyle elements.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAlso in August 2017, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' announced that digital company [[Brat (digital network)|Brat]] would release a new YouTube series called \"Chicken Girls\". The series features LeBlanc and Summerall's relationship, and focuses on the daily lives of a group of friends and dancers at the faux high school, \"Attaway High\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Digital Creator Brat Unveils Fall Slate of High School-Set Shows|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/digital-creator-brat-fall-slate-set-in-high-school-exclusive-1202532236/|website=Variety|accessdate=March 12, 2018|date=August 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe show's debut episode has received over 10 million YouTube views, and as of May 2018, the second season had between 2 million and 4.5 million views per episode.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/brat-founder-rob-fishman-talks-franchise-building-book-and-movie-deals-2018-4|title=A founder who sold his last startup for ~$50 million is using book and movie deals to boost his new YouTube-centric media company|work=Business Insider|access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref> In February 2018, Variety announced that [[Lionsgate]] would be distributing a full-length feature film of ''[[Chicken Girls: The Movie]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Lionsgate Unveils 'Studio L' Digital Slate With 'Honor List,' 'Most Likely to Murder'|url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/lionsgate-unveils-studio-l-digital-slate-1202707449/|website=Variety|publisher=Variety|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tigerbeat.com/2018/02/chicken-girls-movie-brat/|title=Brat Confirms 'Chicken Girls: The Movie' is Happening  {{!}} TigerBeat|date=February 22, 2018|work=BOP and Tiger Beat|access-date=June 19, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> There is also a deal with [[Skyhorse Publishing]] to turn the show into a book series.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2018/03/22/chicken-girls-brat-book/|title='Chicken Girls' Web Series, Starring Annie LeBlanc And Hayden Summerall, To Be Adapted Into Books \u2013 Tubefilter|date=March 22, 2018|work=Tubefilter|access-date=June 20, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> In September 2018, the third season of Chicken Girls premiered on Brat's YouTube channel.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}} Season 4 premiered on March 19, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4DUjgQ4aTms&list=PLVewHiZp3_LP1bQVt8g9PlCHCx-syp_4f&index=2&t=0s|title=CHICKEN GIRLS &#124; Season 4 &#124; Ep. 1: \"Flour Babies\"|date=March 19, 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, it was announced that LeBlanc and her sister Hayley LeBlanc would be starring in a new series on the [[Brat (digital network)|Brat]] YouTube channel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tigerbeat.com/video/annie-hayley-leblanc-sneak-peek/|title=Annie and Hayley LeBlanc Give Fans a Sneak Peek at Their New Brat Series|last1=Stivale|first1=Shelby|website=tigerbeat.com|publisher=Tiger Beat|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref> That same month, it was announced that LeBlanc and Addison Riecke would star in a Brat teen mystery series called ''A Girl Named Jo'' which takes place in 1963 in a small town.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/brat-orders-new-series-a-girl-named-jo-annie-leblanc-1202818065/|title=Brat Announces New Series 'A Girl Named Jo' Starring Annie LeBlanc, Addison Riecke|last=Carras|first=Christi|date=May 21, 2018|work=Variety|access-date=June 19, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Also in May 2018, Leblanc appeared in Asher Angel's music video for \"Chemistry\" as the fans dubbed them as \"Ashannie\"\n\nIn December 2018, [[Business Insider]] called LeBlanc one of the \"most famous teens in the world.\"<ref name=bi>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/annie-leblanc-kenzie-ziegler-star-in-brat-holiday-spectacular-analysis-2018-12|title=The 'two biggest female Gen Z stars' are about to be in a holiday YouTube movie together, and an expert says it will be a massive hit|last=McAlone|first=Nathan|website=[[Business Insider]]|date=December 12, 2018|accessdate=July 27, 2019}}</ref> That same month she starred in Brat's feature film, Holiday Spectacular. Months later, she also starred in another Brat feature film, Spring Breakaway.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0tMLGEsCI8o|title=SPRING BREAKAWAY|date=March 15, 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, LeBlanc was cast in a lead role for an upcoming [[Nickelodeon]] buddy comedy series, ''Side Hustle'' alongside Jayden Bartels.<ref name=\"dlSideHustle\">{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2020/02/side-hustle-buddy-comedy-annie-leblanc-jayden-bartels-nickelodeon-series-order-1202866753/ | title = 'Side Hustle' Buddy Comedy Starring Annie LeBlanc & Jayden Bartels Gets Nickelodeon Series Order | publisher = [[Deadline Hollywood]] | author = Denise Petski | date = February 24, 2020 | access-date = February 24, 2020}}</ref> april 20 she has interwiuv with hollywire. and nearly 19 had make song assosition.\n\n== Discography ==\n===Compilation albums===\n* ''Lollipop'', Label: [[Heard Well]] Released: May 2018<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Singles ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Title\n! colspan=\"3\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Hot Country Songs|US<br>Country]]<br><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/annie-leblanc/chart-history/country-songs|title=Annie LeBlanc Chart History \u2013 Hot Country Songs|work=Billboard|access-date=July 11, 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Canadian Digital Song Sales|CA<br>Digital]]<br><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/annie-leblanc/chart-history/hot-canada-digital-song-sales|title=Annie LeBlanc Chart History \u2013 Hot Canadian Digital Song Sales|work=Billboard|access-date=July 11, 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Digital Songs|US<br>Digital]]<br><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/annie-leblanc/chart-history/digital-song-sales|title=Annie LeBlanc Chart History \u2013 Digital Song Sales|work=Billboard|access-date=July 11, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"| 2017\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Fly (Maddie & Tae song)|Fly]]\"\n| 34 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Little Do You Know\" <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(with Hayden Summerall)</span>\n| \u2014 || 38 || 30\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Birds of a Feather\"<ref>{{cite web|publisher=LeBlanc Lately|title=Annie LeBlanc Singing 'Birds of a Feather' (Chicken Girls Theme Song)|date=September 17, 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FnH9Iq1BERk|via=YouTube|access-date=July 11, 2018}}</ref>\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Photograph\"<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Brat|title=PHOTOGRAPH {{!}} Official Music Video {{!}} Annie LeBlanc|date=November 30, 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hEp1G3bPZGM|via=YouTube|access-date=July 11, 2018}}</ref>\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Ordinary Girl\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| 2018\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Little Things (One Direction song)|Little Things]]\"<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/29/nyregion/childrens-hospital-tv-station.html|title=Live, From the Children's Ward|last=Newman|first=Andy|date=June 29, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 11, 2018}}</ref>\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2019\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Two Things\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- \n! scope=\"row\"| \"Play Nice\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- \n! scope=\"row\"| \"Who You Are\n(feat. Sky Katz)\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- \n! scope=\"row\"| \"Utopia\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Web series, television and film roles\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2015 || ''Neon Arcade'' || Annie Bratayley |