{"title_page": "Maya Goded", "text_new": "{{Spanish name 2|Goded|Colichio}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Maya Goded\n| image = Maya Goded Colichio.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Maya Goded Colichio\n| birth_date = 1967<!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place = [[Mexico City]]\n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[Mexico|Mexican]]\n| field = Photography and Film documentaries of people from hidden or shunned communities\n| works = ''Tierra Negra'', ''Plaza de la Soledad'', ''Good Girls''\n| influenced by = \n| influenced = \n| awards = Masterclass, [[World Press Photo]] (2006), [[Prince Claus Awards|Prince Claus Award]] (2010) and more\n| website = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| bgcolour = \n}}\n'''Maya Goded Colichio''' (born 1967, Mexico City, Mexico)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tfiny.org/filmmakers/detail/maya_goded|title=Maya Goded|website=Tribeca Film Institute|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> is a [[Mexico|Mexican]] [[photographer]] and [[documentary film|documentary]] [[film maker]]. Since 2002 she has been allied with [[Magnum Photos]]<ref>Magnum Photos, [http://www.magnumphotos.com/C.aspx?VP=XSpecific_MAG.Biography_VPage&AID=2K7O3R149QDW biography]</ref> and has developed a special focus on images of people from hidden or shunned communities.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Life ==\nGoded was born in 1967 in [[Mexico City]]. In 1993 she worked as an assistant to Mexican photographer [[Graciela Iturbide]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rencontres-arles.com//en/artistes/view/578/|title=Maya Goded|last=d'Arles|first=Les Rencontres|website=www.rencontres-arles.com|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nShe did her first project in 1994, called ''Tierra Negra'' (''Black Earth''). She worked for three years on this project which consists of a collection images of [[Afro-Mexican]]s.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://princeclausfund.org/laureate/maya-goded|title=Maya Goded - Prince Claus Fund|website=princeclausfund.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently she went on to explore female sexuality, gender violence, prostitution and the way women in Mexican society are seen in the traditional role of motherhood. Furthermore, she investigates people in harsh living conditions or living in hidden or shunned communities. Her photographs are accompanied by a name and description of the life of the person portrayed.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe work in her exhibition \"Sexoservidoras\" at the [[Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sof\u00eda|Reina Sofia Museum]] in [[Madrid]], [[Spain]] was described as:<blockquote>Goded does not propose the glorification of these women, but rather wants to establish an iconography of a model that is the complete opposite of the good and perfect Christian mother. ''Sexoservidoras'' refers to those prostitutes living in the margins, victims of the guiding principle of morality in Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museoreinasofia.es/en/exhibitions/maya-goded-sexoservidoras-1995-2000|title=Maya Goded. Sexoservidoras 1995-2000 {{!}} Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sof\u00eda|last=|first=|date=|website=Museo Reina Sofia|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref></blockquote>Goded has published several books and has been the co-author of others as well. She has won several international awards. In 2009 she was involved in the making of a [[video]] and a [[short film]], called ''Una Reina a su Gusto''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://moreliafilmfest.com/peliculas/una-reina-a-su-gusto/|title=Una reina a su gusto|website=FICM|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sdpnoticias.com/nacional/competira-novena-gusto-corto-reina.html|title=Competir\u00e1 el corto \"Una reina a su gusto\" en novena edici\u00f3n del FIC|last=SDPnoticias.com|website=SDPnoticias.com|language=spanish|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> After this she concentrated on the making of [[documentary film]]s.<ref name=\"WPP\">World Press Photo, [http://www.worldpressphoto.org/maya-goded biography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130318013249/http://www.worldpressphoto.org/maya-goded |date=2013-03-18 }}</ref> \n\nHer 2016 release film about ageing prostitutes, ''Plaza de la Soledad (Loneliness Square),''<ref>{{Citation|title=Plaza de la Soledad|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt5261818/|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/97173-photographer-turned-filmmaker-maya-goded-talks-sundance-doc-plaza-de-la-soledad/|title=Photographer turned Filmmaker Maya Goded Talks Sundance Doc Plaza de la Soledad|last=Rezayazdi|first=Soheil|website=Filmmaker Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> won the Impulso Morelia Prize at the 2015 Festival Internacional de Cine de Morelia, in Mexico.<ref name=\":1\" /> The film has been described as \"a sumptuous \u200bvisual celebration \u200band \u200ba \u200brefreshingly honest \u200bexploration\u200b of physical and emotional \u200bself-determination against difficult odds.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sundance.org/projects/plaza-de-la-soledad|title=plaza-de-la-soledad|last=|first=|date=|website=Sundance Institute|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nGoded won several international award. Here follows a selection:<ref name=\"WPP\" />\n*1993: First Prize, Mother Jones Foundation\n*1994: First Prize, Mexico at Crossroads, [[Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich|University of Munich]], [[Germany]]\n*1996: Masterclass, [[World Press Photo]]\n*2000: Fotopres '01 - La Caixa Foundation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ilexphoto.com/artist/maya-goded/|title=Maya Goded|website=ILEX Photo|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n*2001: [[W. Eugene Smith Memorial Fund|W. Eugene Smith Grant]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smithfund.org/recipients/2001-maya-goded|title=2001 Maya Goded|website=W. Eugene Smith Memorial Fund|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n*2003: [[Guggenheim Fellowship]]<ref name=\":1\" />\n*2004: System Nacional de Creators\n*2010: [[Prince Claus Awards|Prince Claus Award]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n*2015 Impulso Morelia Prize<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/festivals/mexico-up-next-maya-goded-1201631136/|title=Mexico: Up Next! \u2013 Maya Goded|last=Hopewell|first=John|last2=|first2=|date=2015-11-01|website=Variety|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*1994: ''Tierra negra: fotograf\u00edas de la Costa Chica en Guerrero y Oaxaca, M\u00e9xico'', El Milagro\n*2006: ''Plaza de la Soledad'', Lunwerg, Spain, {{ISBN|978-8497852722}}\n*2006: ''Good Girls'', Umbrage Editions, {{ISBN|9781884167621}}\n\n== References ==\n<References />\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goded, Maya}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican photographers]]\n[[Category:Magnum photographers]]\n[[Category:Mexican documentary filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Mexican women photographers]]\n[[Category:Mexican women film directors]]\n[[Category:Women documentary filmmakers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Spanish name 2|Goded|Colichio}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Maya Goded\n| image = Maya Goded Colichio.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Maya Goded Colichio\n| birth_date = 1967<!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place = [[Mexico City]]\n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[Mexico|Mexican]]\n| field = Photography and Film documentaries of people from hidden or shunned communities\n| works = ''Tierra Negra'', ''Plaza de la Soledad'', ''Good Girls''\n| influenced by = \n| influenced = \n| awards = Masterclass, [[World Press Photo]] (2006), [[Prince Claus Awards|Prince Claus Award]] (2010) and more\n| website = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| bgcolour = \n}}\n'''Maya Goded Colichio''' (born 1967, Mexico City, Mexico)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tfiny.org/filmmakers/detail/maya_goded|title=Maya Goded|website=Tribeca Film Institute|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> is a [[Mexico|Mexican]] [[photographer]] and [[documentary film|documentary]] [[film maker]]. Since 2002 she has been allied with [[Magnum Photos]]<ref>Magnum Photos, [http://www.magnumphotos.com/C.aspx?VP=XSpecific_MAG.Biography_VPage&AID=2K7O3R149QDW biography]</ref> and has developed a special focus on images of people from hidden or shunned communities.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Life ==\nGoded was born in 1967 in [[Mexico City]]. In 1993 she worked as an assistant to Mexican photographer [[Graciela Iturbide]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rencontres-arles.com//en/artistes/view/578/|title=Maya Goded|last=d'Arles|first=Les Rencontres|website=www.rencontres-arles.com|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nShe did her first project in 1994, called ''Tierra Negra'' (''Black Earth''). She worked for three years on this project which consists of a collection images of [[Afro-Mexican]]s.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://princeclausfund.org/laureate/maya-goded|title=Maya Goded - Prince Claus Fund|website=princeclausfund.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently she went on to explore female sexuality, gender violence, prostitution and the way women in Mexican society are seen in the traditional role of motherhood. Furthermore, she investigates people in harsh living conditions or living in hidden or shunned communities. Her photographs are accompanied by a name and description of the life of the person portrayed.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe work in her exhibition \"Sexoservidoras\" at the [[Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sof\u00eda|Reina Sofia Museum]] in Madrid, Spain was described as:<blockquote>Goded does not propose the glorification of these women, but rather wants to establish an iconography of a model that is the complete opposite of the good and perfect Christian mother. ''Sexoservidoras'' refers to those prostitutes living in the margins, victims of the guiding principle of morality in Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museoreinasofia.es/en/exhibitions/maya-goded-sexoservidoras-1995-2000|title=Maya Goded. Sexoservidoras 1995-2000 {{!}} Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sof\u00eda|last=|first=|date=|website=Museo Reina Sofia|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref></blockquote>Goded has published several books and has been the co-author of others as well. She has won several international awards. In 2009 she was involved in the making of a [[video]] and a [[short film]], called ''Una Reina a su Gusto''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://moreliafilmfest.com/peliculas/una-reina-a-su-gusto/|title=Una reina a su gusto|website=FICM|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sdpnoticias.com/nacional/competira-novena-gusto-corto-reina.html|title=Competir\u00e1 el corto \"Una reina a su gusto\" en novena edici\u00f3n del FIC|last=SDPnoticias.com|website=SDPnoticias.com|language=spanish|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> After this she concentrated on the making of [[documentary film]]s.<ref name=\"WPP\">World Press Photo, [http://www.worldpressphoto.org/maya-goded biography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130318013249/http://www.worldpressphoto.org/maya-goded |date=2013-03-18 }}</ref> \n\nHer 2016 release film about ageing prostitutes, ''Plaza de la Soledad (Loneliness Square),''<ref>{{Citation|title=Plaza de la Soledad|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt5261818/|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/97173-photographer-turned-filmmaker-maya-goded-talks-sundance-doc-plaza-de-la-soledad/|title=Photographer turned Filmmaker Maya Goded Talks Sundance Doc Plaza de la Soledad|last=Rezayazdi|first=Soheil|website=Filmmaker Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> won the Impulso Morelia Prize at the 2015 Festival Internacional de Cine de Morelia, in Mexico.<ref name=\":1\" /> The film has been described as \"a sumptuous \u200bvisual celebration \u200band \u200ba \u200brefreshingly honest \u200bexploration\u200b of physical and emotional \u200bself-determination against difficult odds.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sundance.org/projects/plaza-de-la-soledad|title=plaza-de-la-soledad|last=|first=|date=|website=Sundance Institute|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nGoded won several international award. Here follows a selection:<ref name=\"WPP\" />\n*1993: First Prize, Mother Jones Foundation\n*1994: First Prize, Mexico at Crossroads, [[Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich|University of Munich]], [[Germany]]\n*1996: Masterclass, [[World Press Photo]]\n*2000: Fotopres '01 - La Caixa Foundation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ilexphoto.com/artist/maya-goded/|title=Maya Goded|website=ILEX Photo|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n*2001: [[W. Eugene Smith Memorial Fund|W. Eugene Smith Grant]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smithfund.org/recipients/2001-maya-goded|title=2001 Maya Goded|website=W. Eugene Smith Memorial Fund|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n*2003: [[Guggenheim Fellowship]]<ref name=\":1\" />\n*2004: System Nacional de Creators\n*2010: [[Prince Claus Awards|Prince Claus Award]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n*2015 Impulso Morelia Prize<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/festivals/mexico-up-next-maya-goded-1201631136/|title=Mexico: Up Next! \u2013 Maya Goded|last=Hopewell|first=John|last2=|first2=|date=2015-11-01|website=Variety|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*1994: ''Tierra negra: fotograf\u00edas de la Costa Chica en Guerrero y Oaxaca, M\u00e9xico'', El Milagro\n*2006: ''Plaza de la Soledad'', Lunwerg, Spain, {{ISBN|978-8497852722}}\n*2006: ''Good Girls'', Umbrage Editions, {{ISBN|9781884167621}}\n\n== References ==\n<References />\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goded, Maya}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican photographers]]\n[[Category:Magnum photographers]]\n[[Category:Mexican documentary filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Mexican women photographers]]\n[[Category:Mexican women film directors]]\n[[Category:Women documentary filmmakers]]\n", "name_user": "Soydeaguadilla", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maya_Goded"}
